WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.760
[Amit Varma]: If you set out to change the world, where do you even begin?

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:13.720
[Amit Varma]: Some might start by changing themselves, be the change you want to see.

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:15.980
[Amit Varma]: But that has a limited impact on the world.

00:00:15.980 --> 00:00:21.200
[Amit Varma]: To make a bigger difference, you need to change the views of others, be an activist even.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:23.800
[Amit Varma]: Maybe you do this by writing op-eds in columns.

00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:25.840
[Amit Varma]: Maybe you do morchas on the streets.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:29.180
[Amit Varma]: Maybe you become a mover and shaker in politics to shake things up.

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:34.440
[Amit Varma]: If you really care, then over time, you figure out those small ways in which you can help

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:36.240
[Amit Varma]: bring about big change.

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:41.080
[Amit Varma]: My guest on the show today thought long and hard about how he could help change the world.

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:46.040
[Amit Varma]: Fired up by deep emotion, he forged the road ahead with cold logic.

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:51.400
[Amit Varma]: Can there be a better combination?

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:56.600
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:57.600
[Unknown]: science.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:03.160
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bhardwaj.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:04.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:09.680
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Parmesh Shahani, founder of the famous Godrej India Culture Lab and

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:12.920
[Amit Varma]: an advocate of LGBTQ inclusion in corporate India.

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:15.480
[Amit Varma]: Yes, that's right, in corporate India.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:21.600
[Amit Varma]: Even as Indian society changes slowly, Parmesh works with corporates to help make them friendlier

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:24.880
[Amit Varma]: and more open spaces for LGBTQ people.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:30.480
[Amit Varma]: He's written a fabulous book about this called Queeristan, which he describes as memoir plus

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:31.680
[Amit Varma]: manifesto.

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:35.840
[Amit Varma]: I was delighted to have him on The Seen and The Unseen to share his thoughts with me.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Before we move on to our conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:45.600
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Seen and The Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:46.880
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:49.920
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and The Unseen has been a labor of love for me.

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:55.520
[Amit Varma]: I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe,

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:56.520
[Amit Varma]: and hopefully yours as well.

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:01.840
[Amit Varma]: But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off the show.

00:02:01.840 --> 00:02:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Although The Seen and The Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken

00:02:05.840 --> 00:02:08.840
[Amit Varma]: up to the insane engagement level of podcasts.

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:13.240
[Amit Varma]: And I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode, besides all the logistics

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:19.360
[Amit Varma]: of producing the show myself, scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:20.360
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.720
[Amit Varma]: So, well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves you.

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: My proposition for you is this.

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:31.780
[Amit Varma]: For every episode of The Seen and The Unseen that you enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:34.600
[Amit Varma]: even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth.

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:40.400
[Amit Varma]: You can do this by heading over to seenunseen.in slash support and contributing an amount of

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:41.400
[Amit Varma]: your choice.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:43.480
[Amit Varma]: This is not a subscription.

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:50.520
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and The Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at seenunseen.in.

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:56.840
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation, help keep this thing going seenunseen.in slash

00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:57.840
[Amit Varma]: support.

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:02.960
[Amit Varma]: Parmesh, welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:03.960
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:05.680
[Guest]: I'm very happy to be here.

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:15.440
[Guest]: I remember we were at TED in 2009, that evening in Mysore, music, happiness, so much possibility.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.800
[Guest]: Did you imagine 11 years later, here we would be?

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:23.320
[Amit Varma]: What's kind of fascinating is that, you know, just for the listeners, we were both TED India

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:29.400
[Amit Varma]: fellows when TED happened in Mysore in 2009, the actual TED, not some TEDx.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:32.520
[Amit Varma]: And Parmesh and I were both TED India fellows.

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:36.080
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that for me, it was just an event, it came and it went

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:40.160
[Amit Varma]: and it was nice to meet all these people, but I didn't think much about it.

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:44.080
[Amit Varma]: But reading your book, I sort of realized that it's played a slightly more important

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:49.040
[Amit Varma]: role in your journey than in mine, which is, you know, so interesting to me how, you know,

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:53.040
[Amit Varma]: these the same event can have such a different impact on people.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:58.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've described your book at the start as a memoir plus manifesto.

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of seemed to me that even the manifesto part of it in a sense is, it's almost

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:06.000
[Amit Varma]: a lived manifesto.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.600
[Amit Varma]: So that's also in a sense, it arises out of the memoir.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:14.640
[Amit Varma]: And I'd like to sort of before we get to your book, which I really enjoyed reading and learn

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:19.880
[Amit Varma]: from, but before we get there, I'd like to kind of explore the memoir part a bit and,

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:25.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, ask you more about your personal journey, and how that's been.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:29.720
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about that about, you know, growing up as a middle class kid, first in

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:34.320
[Amit Varma]: Colaba, then you went to the Middle East, coming back to Bombay, navigating all of that.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:35.320
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:40.080
[Guest]: So yeah, it was interesting to reflect, to look back in the book.

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:45.560
[Guest]: The aim was always, I think with both my books, right, Gay Bombay that came out first, Gay

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:51.180
[Guest]: Bombay actually was the book that got me into that Ted India, because the book had come

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:57.320
[Guest]: out in 2008, and I applied using that and, you know, I got to come to this conference

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.680
[Guest]: and like meet all of you, you know.

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:08.280
[Guest]: So even there, even that book, which was very much an ethnography, that was an academic

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:13.760
[Guest]: book that came out of my MIT program, that came out of research.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:18.800
[Guest]: So it was digital ethnography, it was anthropology, it was LGBTQ studies, it was so many of those

00:05:18.800 --> 00:05:19.800
[Guest]: things.

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:27.640
[Guest]: And over there, I kind of had placed myself in the middle of all the stories I was telling.

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:34.720
[Guest]: And this format actually comes very much from my schooling and from my, not while growing

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:38.000
[Guest]: up, but from my academic training.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:44.520
[Guest]: So the program that I did at MIT, for example, comparative media studies, is something that

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:51.320
[Guest]: Henry Jenkins, William Eurekio, these incredible scholars whom I love and admire so much began.

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:55.840
[Guest]: And it was very much a program that kind of, I mean, you know, I want to use the word queer

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:56.840
[Guest]: here.

00:05:56.840 --> 00:06:01.640
[Guest]: It queered media studies, because it kind of queered academia, not in the sense of talking

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:06.440
[Guest]: about queers, which of course it does, queer people, queer lives, queer hopes, but also

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.080
[Guest]: how do you do academia?

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:09.560
[Guest]: How do you tell stories?

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:15.520
[Guest]: And that's also been the kind of change in anthropology over the years, from a researcher

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:23.880
[Guest]: being someone who goes to a distant land to study the other, and lives in, immerses themselves

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:28.620
[Guest]: into that culture, and then writes up about it as a distant observer.

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:32.760
[Guest]: Anthropology over the years, media studies, all these disciplines have become very much

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:36.720
[Guest]: about the intimate, about what does it mean when you study your own self?

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:42.360
[Guest]: What does it mean to reflect, you know, on your own journey while you are studying others

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:44.680
[Guest]: like you, not others different from you?

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:46.040
[Guest]: And what does that do to the research?

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:52.800
[Guest]: So the method of Queeristan, which is deep, personal, mixed with facts, figures, data,

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:57.320
[Guest]: other people's stories, was actually, I mean, I've honed it more in Queeristan, but, you

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:01.400
[Guest]: know, the initial experiment almost was Gay Bombay.

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:04.720
[Guest]: And that came from my training, which also kind of validated.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:09.120
[Guest]: So one of the beautiful things about being in that program was, you know, my professors

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:13.120
[Guest]: were like, your background matters, your experience matters.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.840
[Guest]: You know, we don't want to wipe out everything you are, and where you've come from, and train

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:19.040
[Guest]: you to be a particular kind of scholar.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:23.200
[Guest]: We want you to inform your scholarship with all of these.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:27.280
[Guest]: And that was so amazing that, you know, and you know, Henry was an incredible mentor,

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:28.280
[Guest]: especially in this.

00:07:28.280 --> 00:07:32.840
[Guest]: And if you see his own scholarship, right, whether about comics or video games, or Star

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:38.360
[Guest]: Wars, he actually started the field of fandom studies, you know, which now over the years

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:42.120
[Guest]: has become, you know, a legit academic pursuit.

00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:45.040
[Guest]: He was like, it's all, it's all about the personal, right?

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:51.560
[Guest]: So that personal memoir meets manifesto thing has its origins, I mean, in my training, in

00:07:51.560 --> 00:07:56.200
[Guest]: the validation I got from my program that you can talk about, you know, you can reflect

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:58.840
[Guest]: on your own journey, seriously.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:03.320
[Guest]: And I tried to do that for various reasons, because I thought it was also very, very important

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:06.120
[Guest]: in Queeristan, which is a business book.

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:11.160
[Guest]: And so many of the business books that I was reading, or that I tried to read, to prepare

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:17.800
[Guest]: for this, were just about business, or they just put you in and they said, you know, five

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:21.040
[Guest]: things to do, six things to do, case study here.

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:25.440
[Guest]: I was yearning, I was thirsting to know more about the people behind those decisions, right?

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:26.440
[Guest]: Why are you doing this?

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:30.480
[Guest]: Why are you recommending I do these five things, or like, why are you recommending I swim in

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:31.480
[Guest]: this blue ocean?

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:36.720
[Guest]: Or, you know, why are you, like, I kind of thought that it would be really nice to write

00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:39.720
[Guest]: a deeply personal business book.

00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:44.880
[Guest]: Because in a sense, what I was also trying to do in this book was to visibilize, right?

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:49.000
[Guest]: So large parts of the book are, you know, cases, steps, etc.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.840
[Guest]: But really a large part of the book is, you know, for people who might not have met queer

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.080
[Guest]: people, you know, this is us.

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:57.460
[Guest]: This is our lives, right?

00:08:57.460 --> 00:08:58.460
[Guest]: This is my life.

00:08:58.460 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest]: This is my personal journey.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.520
[Guest]: This is what has happened to me when my family has accepted and my company has accepted.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:09.400
[Guest]: This is how my background has played into, you know, the privileges that I have, and

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:17.820
[Guest]: that I can use at this point to kind of strategize in whatever way I can for, you know, to create

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:20.200
[Guest]: a more inclusive playing field, and things like this.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:24.640
[Guest]: I thought it was very important to put all those personal bits in, even before we reach

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:25.960
[Guest]: the business path.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:30.640
[Guest]: So a reader kind of knows me, they're like, ah, we understand this Parmesh, we understand

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:36.520
[Guest]: not just where he's come from, but, you know, also, all the other things in the book, right?

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:42.720
[Guest]: So I thought that also kind of would open them up more to kind of have that empathy

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:46.400
[Guest]: to understand the case, and then to do which is what I really want them to do at the end

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:48.920
[Guest]: of the book, which is implement those steps.

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:53.400
[Guest]: So the personal, putting that personal in was very strategic, and it has always been

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:56.240
[Guest]: very strategic for me in both my books.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:57.760
[Guest]: It's not indulgence.

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:04.040
[Guest]: It's very much a conscious act of creating that link of empathy with my readers so that

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:05.720
[Amit Varma]: they come with me on this journey.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:09.840
[Amit Varma]: So I had a couple of observations, a second one sort of going into a question, and they're

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:11.120
[Amit Varma]: both kind of tangential.

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:16.640
[Amit Varma]: And one is that, firstly, I think that worked beautifully, the fusing of the personal with

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:17.640
[Amit Varma]: whatever the book is about.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.640
[Amit Varma]: So it never felt like a business book that Manifesto feel doesn't really come across.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, out of the five parts, you could say the fourth part is one which actually, you

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.880
[Amit Varma]: know, talks about what companies can do.

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:31.280
[Amit Varma]: And even there, you've weaved in the personal, but it worked beautifully in the story.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:36.560
[Amit Varma]: My second observation and also perhaps a question is that, you know, one of the other questions

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:41.520
[Amit Varma]: I had, which I first noted down before I even started reading the book that I want to ask

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:45.960
[Amit Varma]: Parmesh about, you know, when he was growing up, the process of getting comfortable in

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:49.880
[Amit Varma]: his own skin, which is hard for anyone, which was hard for me as well.

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:52.760
[Amit Varma]: So it doesn't matter what your sexuality or anything might be.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:57.160
[Amit Varma]: All of us are so anxious about fitting into the world and just reaching that stage where

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:00.400
[Amit Varma]: we are comfortable with who we are is a journey in itself.

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:05.560
[Amit Varma]: But that seems to also have found a very interesting reflection in the voice of the book, where

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:09.920
[Amit Varma]: at first I was taken aback because, you know, there are so many places where, you know,

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:14.160
[Amit Varma]: and I always say with writers, I know that when you read something by them, because the

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:17.600
[Amit Varma]: writing is authentic, it sounds like you can hear their voice speaking out.

00:11:17.600 --> 00:11:21.760
[Amit Varma]: And that's even more in your case, because, you know, somewhere you'll say, no, Baba and

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:27.240
[Amit Varma]: you'll continue or at the end of saying something, you know, you'll say Hannah, you know, and

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:28.240
[Amit Varma]: which was very interesting.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:31.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the first couple of times it startled me a bit because you don't expect

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:35.280
[Amit Varma]: that kind of a conversational and formal tone in a book.

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:40.020
[Amit Varma]: So what was sort of, you know, is that something that you thought about that the voice has

00:11:40.020 --> 00:11:45.680
[Amit Varma]: to be me and it has to be me to the extent that it has to be, you know, that process

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:50.960
[Amit Varma]: of people hearing your voice feels more explicit, you know, so is that something you thought

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:51.960
[Amit Varma]: about?

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.400
[Amit Varma]: Did your publisher have a problem and say, what is this?

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:55.680
[Guest]: No, Baba, cut it out.

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:56.680
[Guest]: Oh, yes.

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:58.120
[Guest]: And I hope she's listening to this.

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:01.840
[Guest]: And I hope she realizes how much people like it.

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:04.480
[Guest]: Because we didn't have many arguments through the book.

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:09.560
[Guest]: But if there was one bone of contention, it was this, you know, for Westland, it was very

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:14.080
[Guest]: much Parmesh, this is a business book, you are not Shobha Dey.

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:16.600
[Guest]: And then I was like, hey, but I can be Shobha Dey.

00:12:16.600 --> 00:12:22.960
[Guest]: And I told Shobha also this, and they were like, no, no, no, no, you know, don't forget

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:24.360
[Guest]: it's a business book.

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:31.880
[Guest]: And I was very much keen, but it's my business book, darling, I think of business is different.

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:32.880
[Guest]: And that was the point.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:39.120
[Guest]: So we, if you read the, at some point, I think I should do a director's cut of the book with

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:43.080
[Guest]: all the bits that were left out.

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:47.320
[Guest]: If you see what was on the chopping table, it's essentially a whole bunch of this, they

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:50.140
[Guest]: were like, okay, I love it.

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:53.960
[Guest]: But I think maybe it's becoming too personal, why we need to tell this, why we have to say

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:54.960
[Guest]: this.

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:58.040
[Guest]: I can you every time not say, this, this, this.

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:01.840
[Guest]: And I was like, but you know, this is so then we reached one.

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:06.960
[Guest]: Like any good editor, publisher, author relationship.

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:12.480
[Guest]: And I see my auntie likes to say, it was all about compromise and adjustment.

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:15.000
[Guest]: I was like, look, my voice is important.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.720
[Guest]: Here is what you're going to, I, you know, I think here, I want to talk like this.

00:13:18.720 --> 00:13:21.480
[Guest]: And they were like, okay, here is very good.

00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:25.480
[Guest]: But maybe here, if we make it a little more serious, a little more this or that, because

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:27.320
[Guest]: remember, it's ultimately a business book.

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:33.160
[Guest]: So but I'm glad that the voice came through, because I was really afraid that, you know,

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:37.880
[Guest]: I really wanted it to sound like me, which is also by recording the audible version.

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:42.440
[Guest]: I mean, I could just read it out, because it's like, I, you know, thought of it.

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:44.600
[Guest]: And if you read the audible version, it's exactly like that.

00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:46.360
[Guest]: It's like, I'm sitting next to you.

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:47.840
[Guest]: I'm taking you on this journey.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:51.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the first time I came across some of those, and I think that right there

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:56.800
[Amit Varma]: from the preface, I was, you know, with my editor's hat on, I was a little bit like,

00:13:56.800 --> 00:14:00.640
[Amit Varma]: okay, this, this, you know, the reader will notice this, it snaps them out of the narrative,

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:01.680
[Amit Varma]: is it a good thing.

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:05.320
[Amit Varma]: But as I went on, I found it a charming and be authentic to the person.

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:09.720
[Amit Varma]: So you feel that this is actually, you know, someone sitting across you and talking the

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:12.040
[Amit Varma]: way they talk, even if they don't know you.

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:14.240
[Amit Varma]: And I thought that really worked for me.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:19.440
[Amit Varma]: So kind of getting back to your sort of the early part of your memoir, you know, what

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:26.040
[Amit Varma]: was it sort of like growing up in 80s, 90s, Mumbai, and, you know, in terms of you often

00:14:26.040 --> 00:14:31.880
[Amit Varma]: said that you didn't have an issue with figuring out your sexuality, but with articulating

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:32.880
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:35.080
[Guest]: So take me a bit through those years and what it was like.

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:36.080
[Guest]: Yeah, it was.

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:38.400
[Guest]: I mean, everyone is nostalgic about their past.

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:43.520
[Guest]: And as you're saying, 80s, 90s, I'm thinking of this Bappi Lehri album called Habiba.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:47.500
[Guest]: I don't know if anyone else remembers it, but you know, I do.

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:48.880
[Guest]: This is before Made in India.

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:50.400
[Guest]: This is before pop music, right?

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:52.280
[Guest]: This is before MTV.

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:55.760
[Guest]: And Bappi Lehri had released this incredible music album.

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:59.440
[Guest]: I mean, a non-film music album called Habiba, which I still remember so much.

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:01.480
[Guest]: And, you know, we were not that rich.

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:05.200
[Guest]: So, you know, to get a cassette was something and how much I argued with my mom saying,

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:06.200
[Guest]: I really want it.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:08.440
[Guest]: And she was like, but, you know, it's a cassette.

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:09.640
[Guest]: It has one song on it.

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:10.640
[Guest]: You'll get tired of it.

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:13.000
[Guest]: Because that was essentially it was Habiba multiple times.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.600
[Guest]: It was a single.

00:15:14.600 --> 00:15:17.480
[Guest]: But you know, it was, yeah, it was so different.

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:19.320
[Guest]: It was so innocent.

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:23.480
[Guest]: I suppose every generation looks back at their childhood with wistfulness and, you know,

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:25.880
[Guest]: with that sense of innocence.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:29.400
[Guest]: For me, it was also pre-internet India, right?

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:35.800
[Guest]: So, you know, access to information was not, was not very easy at all.

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:41.080
[Guest]: And in my case, it was, I mean, you know, as I write in the book, it was a very, we

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:45.800
[Guest]: lived in a, we were not, we were, we were middle class, I suppose, we lived in a one

00:15:45.800 --> 00:15:48.080
[Guest]: room house in Colaba.

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:51.080
[Guest]: I went to St. Joseph's High School, RC Church.

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:54.000
[Guest]: I was in the green house, the best house.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.040
[Guest]: And I used to go to school by BST.

00:15:57.040 --> 00:16:01.400
[Guest]: I mean, in those days, it was a big thing, you know, because in the moment Seventh Standard

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:05.600
[Guest]: got over, you would wear long pants and you would say, I'm not taking the school bus,

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:10.240
[Guest]: because it was like a matter of pride to like, take the BST and go to school by yourself.

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:11.240
[Guest]: It was a big thing.

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:13.080
[Guest]: And I would do that.

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:19.840
[Guest]: And I was always very, I mean, I suppose, and, you know, I'm glad that you said that

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:26.200
[Guest]: even it was a process of, you know, even how does one realize one's own straightness, right?

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:30.880
[Guest]: I mean, it's not like, but I suppose if you're straight, and you live in a heteronormative

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:33.000
[Guest]: society, it's not a big thing.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:37.440
[Guest]: At some point, I suppose you realize that you are attracted.

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:41.720
[Guest]: And then you're comfortable with it, because that's the way that everyone around you assumes

00:16:41.720 --> 00:16:43.780
[Guest]: that you will be in any case.

00:16:43.780 --> 00:16:45.520
[Guest]: But when you're queer, it's different, right?

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:49.760
[Guest]: Because you live in a society which kind of expects one thing, but I never I mean, I was

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:56.000
[Guest]: always really very comfortable with me, it was an 8th, 9th, 10th, that I became aware

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:02.560
[Guest]: of my, the fact that I was, you know, emotionally and physically attracted to other boys.

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:07.560
[Guest]: You know, I had a lovely boyfriend, I suppose, in school.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:11.120
[Guest]: Of course, we didn't use that term, we didn't know the term.

00:17:11.120 --> 00:17:15.920
[Guest]: But we knew that we we didn't even know the term homosexual or gay, what we knew is that

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:17.760
[Guest]: we liked each other.

00:17:17.760 --> 00:17:19.320
[Guest]: And we enjoyed each other's company.

00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:23.880
[Guest]: And you know, one thing led to the other and we were very, you know, comfortable, it seemed

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:26.560
[Guest]: right, it seemed natural.

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:30.240
[Guest]: And you know, as I write in the book about how, you know, one day we were walking holding

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:35.160
[Guest]: hands, and again, you know, it was, boys could hold hands and walk, I mean, even I suppose

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:40.120
[Guest]: today boys can, but like in those, I mean, we were very happy holding hands and walking

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:42.560
[Guest]: together near the gateway.

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:46.120
[Guest]: And one of the seniors, because I think I remember, we were in the 9th standard and

00:17:46.120 --> 00:17:52.080
[Guest]: one of the seniors looked at us from school, he saw us and he was like, you both are homos.

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:55.720
[Guest]: And it was the first time we'd heard that word homos.

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:58.920
[Guest]: So you know, we went back home and tried to do research.

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:02.960
[Guest]: And the next day in school, he was like, you know, this homo is not a good thing.

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:05.520
[Guest]: I don't think we should be homos.

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:08.760
[Guest]: And I was like, I was actually quite relieved that there was a word.

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:12.600
[Guest]: I was like, you know, it doesn't feel like a bad thing.

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:16.000
[Guest]: And he was like, no, no, no, we should focus on our board exams.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:21.160
[Guest]: Because you know, 10th standard is, that's what you're obsessed with.

00:18:21.160 --> 00:18:26.120
[Guest]: And I found it very strange, because, you know, I didn't think that there was anything

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:29.120
[Guest]: wrong or something to be ashamed about, but he did.

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:32.120
[Guest]: So he kind of recoiled.

00:18:32.120 --> 00:18:35.400
[Guest]: And I just remember, I mean, you know, it's, it was interesting.

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:37.840
[Guest]: It was sad, because I liked him very much.

00:18:37.840 --> 00:18:43.340
[Guest]: And but for me, it was a good, I mean, it was always, I was always comfortable.

00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:47.960
[Guest]: So it's just that later on, when you discover that, you know, okay, there's, it's homo,

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:53.480
[Guest]: there's gay, this is what it means, you learn more, you read more, you understand more earlier,

00:18:53.480 --> 00:18:58.060
[Guest]: of course, I think, which is also why the current generation is so blessed.

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:04.560
[Guest]: Because you know, there are so many role models, stories, whether you know, books, films, web

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:08.840
[Guest]: series, websites, that talk about being queer in an Indian context.

00:19:08.840 --> 00:19:14.080
[Guest]: Whereas, but you know, in the 80s, late 80s, early 90s, which is when I was in school growing

00:19:14.080 --> 00:19:18.960
[Guest]: up, I mean, there was it was like, you had to like, search for like, you know, maybe

00:19:18.960 --> 00:19:24.040
[Guest]: there will be a little clipping, talking about boy George, or maybe there'll be a hint of

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:28.720
[Guest]: Freddie Mercury, or maybe they will, you know, George Michael, at some point will come out

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:31.880
[Guest]: and it will be gasp.

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:36.300
[Guest]: George Michael is gay, or you know, it was that right, we were we were like, so even

00:19:36.300 --> 00:19:41.280
[Guest]: when you're comfortable, you want a context.

00:19:41.280 --> 00:19:48.880
[Guest]: And for me, I, you know, I, I wanted a context of being queer in a desi way, you know, all

00:19:48.880 --> 00:19:53.480
[Guest]: the foreign role models, etc, were nice, but you know, it didn't feel like my experience.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:58.680
[Guest]: And you know, which is also, I guess, why ultimately, when I went off to study further

00:19:58.680 --> 00:20:04.600
[Guest]: and all my first book was about what does it mean to be queer and Indian, it was largely

00:20:04.600 --> 00:20:07.720
[Guest]: about Indianness about desi pan.

00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:09.240
[Guest]: So that's what it was growing up.

00:20:09.240 --> 00:20:12.600
[Guest]: It was about Doordarshan and He-Man.

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:16.900
[Guest]: And it was about, you know, different kinds of friendships.

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:18.260
[Guest]: It was about long walks.

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:20.760
[Guest]: It was about, I guess, there were less distractions.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:24.320
[Guest]: So I could, you know, spend time to read.

00:20:24.320 --> 00:20:26.360
[Guest]: I used to live with my grandparents.

00:20:26.360 --> 00:20:32.520
[Guest]: So one of the pleasures of my life was every evening going for a long walk with my grandfather.

00:20:32.520 --> 00:20:37.600
[Guest]: And he would expose me, he didn't, you know, he didn't study much, but he would go for

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:40.120
[Guest]: like, you know, and of course, we were not rich.

00:20:40.120 --> 00:20:44.800
[Guest]: But we would go to Jahangir Art Gallery every time a new show would open, and we would look

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:45.840
[Guest]: at the art, right?

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:46.840
[Guest]: And we would walk.

00:20:46.840 --> 00:20:52.720
[Guest]: And I think that, so it was, it was formative years in terms of just understanding myself,

00:20:52.720 --> 00:20:56.080
[Guest]: feeling very comfortable with who I am, but of course, not being able to share this with

00:20:56.080 --> 00:21:00.360
[Guest]: my parents or grandparents, or even friends for that matter, because I didn't know what

00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:03.080
[Guest]: to say, I didn't know how to articulate it.

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:07.520
[Guest]: And then, you know, my dad got a job in the Middle East.

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:12.240
[Guest]: And that was a very different kind of because in the 80s and 90s, you know, being a simple

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:18.920
[Guest]: middle class kid, you know, and in India, where everything is prohibited, and then suddenly

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:22.360
[Guest]: being able to go, and it wasn't a great job.

00:21:22.360 --> 00:21:27.400
[Guest]: I mean, he was working in a supermarket, but it was, I mean, you know, to go on a plane

00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:35.520
[Guest]: to be able to actually buy a Toblerone, to see a supermarket, all these things were quite

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:36.520
[Guest]: exciting.

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:45.360
[Guest]: So it was a way out of middle class mundane-ness into this really exotic world of like, wow,

00:21:45.360 --> 00:21:46.360
[Guest]: all this happens.

00:21:46.360 --> 00:21:47.360
[Amit Varma]: And

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:51.320
[Amit Varma]: in fact, the phrase that you've used in your book for it is you've called it quote, a journey

00:21:51.320 --> 00:21:55.040
[Amit Varma]: out of middle class frugality to Toblerone heaven.

00:21:55.040 --> 00:22:01.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, a tangential sort of thought strikes me here that you know, being you know, someone

00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:04.240
[Amit Varma]: who sort of grew up at the same time and all of that.

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:08.960
[Amit Varma]: And I just felt this wave of nostalgia when you just use the word cassettes, because,

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:13.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, it was such a big deal for us in those days to discover new music to somehow

00:22:13.480 --> 00:22:17.800
[Amit Varma]: plan and scrape together a mixtape of the stuff you like, and all of that.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:21.840
[Amit Varma]: And equally, like you point out that, you know, it's almost difficult today to imagine

00:22:21.840 --> 00:22:25.640
[Amit Varma]: a world without the internet as difficult as it would have been for us to imagine a

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:27.840
[Unknown]: world without electricity, maybe.

00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of strikes me, therefore, that, like, do you think that the whole experience

00:22:32.840 --> 00:22:38.080
[Amit Varma]: of growing up and discovering yourself is then becomes very different?

00:22:38.080 --> 00:22:41.860
[Amit Varma]: Because like you pointed out, like, you know, you mentioned that you went on long walks

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:43.520
[Amit Varma]: with your grandfather.

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:47.320
[Amit Varma]: And I'd imagine that if you're growing up today, you're not going on so many long walks

00:22:47.320 --> 00:22:54.120
[Amit Varma]: with your grandfather, you because you're bombarded all the times by, you know, so much

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:58.320
[Amit Varma]: for your senses by so much information, there is so much to discover.

00:22:58.320 --> 00:23:02.440
[Amit Varma]: And on the one hand, of course, kids growing up today are just the luckiest generation

00:23:02.440 --> 00:23:05.240
[Amit Varma]: ever, because they have all this at their fingertips.

00:23:05.240 --> 00:23:09.800
[Amit Varma]: But you know, is there something you think lost in the fact that they don't have that

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:14.000
[Amit Varma]: time and that space to sort of be with themselves and so on?

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.400
[Guest]: I think so, for sure.

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:17.840
[Guest]: And now, you know, I'm sounding like an uncle already.

00:23:17.840 --> 00:23:25.240
[Guest]: So everyone who's listening to this will say, sit down, uncle or shut up, uncle or something.

00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:30.040
[Guest]: But I think I think there is something different from not being connected, right?

00:23:30.040 --> 00:23:34.120
[Guest]: So even now, I mean, you know, I go for walks with my partner, who happens to be younger

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:39.120
[Guest]: than me, you know, different generation, and it's hard to walk for 10 minutes without him

00:23:39.120 --> 00:23:43.880
[Guest]: whipping out his phone and taking a picture for a future Instagram story.

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:54.360
[Guest]: So and then he's like, you know, we have to think of the story also, I'm like, okay.

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:57.040
[Guest]: So I think that is fundamentally different.

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:00.520
[Guest]: But even with us, right, I mean, one is so attached to the gadget right now, one is so

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:02.640
[Guest]: attached to the screen right now.

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:04.280
[Guest]: So it's not just younger people.

00:24:04.280 --> 00:24:10.360
[Guest]: I think we've also fundamentally in some way, culturally and, you know, physically, in terms

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:13.520
[Guest]: of how we experience things change.

00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:14.960
[Guest]: But it has pros and cons, right?

00:24:14.960 --> 00:24:17.160
[Guest]: I mean, the pros is you have a lot of time, etc.

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:22.800
[Guest]: The cons is when you're growing up in an economy, which is frugal, in a world where information

00:24:22.800 --> 00:24:25.640
[Guest]: is limited, it takes you a long time.

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:30.800
[Guest]: So you know, my generation, our generation of people come out a lot later, people spend

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:34.960
[Guest]: years and in my case, I didn't struggle with self acceptance, right?

00:24:34.960 --> 00:24:37.320
[Guest]: It was, I was comfortable.

00:24:37.320 --> 00:24:44.040
[Guest]: So many people in our generation, torture themselves, you know, about whether what they

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:47.880
[Guest]: are feeling or who they are, is normal or not.

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:53.400
[Guest]: So many destroy their own lives and the lives of others by conforming either to the pressures

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.360
[Guest]: of an arranged heterosexual marriage, and so many other things, right?

00:24:57.360 --> 00:25:02.560
[Guest]: So I think for today's, I mean, you know, for younger people, for today's generation,

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:07.560
[Guest]: I'm just so glad that there is an ecosystem built for those who can access it, so that

00:25:07.560 --> 00:25:14.000
[Guest]: they can learn, they can, you know, understand themselves, they can, you know, express themselves,

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:18.320
[Guest]: and they can imagine a better future for themselves in whichever they wish, right?

00:25:18.320 --> 00:25:21.280
[Guest]: So I don't want to be too nostalgic and romanticize and say everything was good.

00:25:21.280 --> 00:25:25.560
[Guest]: I mean, in those days, of course, you know, it was our childhood, so it was good.

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:30.320
[Guest]: But young people today have so much more access to, you know, to knowledge and opportunities.

00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:31.960
[Guest]: And that's excellent as well.

00:25:31.960 --> 00:25:36.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it struck me as kind of poignant and charming, but poignant also, that you

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:41.000
[Amit Varma]: speak about how, you know, you watch Kayamat Se Kayamat Tak and then you made a fantasy

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:45.600
[Amit Varma]: out of it and called it Gayamat Se Gayamat Tak where, you know, Aamir is romancing you

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:50.480
[Amit Varma]: instead of Juhi Chawla, which is charming, but it's also poignant because it sort of

00:25:50.480 --> 00:25:55.560
[Amit Varma]: indicates what you were just speaking about, that the search for role models is so futile

00:25:55.560 --> 00:25:58.160
[Amit Varma]: that you have to eventually find it in your own fantasies.

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:03.520
[Guest]: Yeah, we didn't have Made in Heaven, right, where you see a gay couple, or four more shards

00:26:03.520 --> 00:26:05.980
[Guest]: where you can see a lesbian wedding or whatever, right?

00:26:05.980 --> 00:26:08.560
[Guest]: So we had to interpolate ourselves into these stories.

00:26:08.560 --> 00:26:14.840
[Guest]: And imagine that Sholay is a gay bromance, and of course, Jai and Veeru are gay.

00:26:14.840 --> 00:26:22.360
[Guest]: You know, that's true, but because, you know, we didn't have My Brother Nikhil or Aligarh

00:26:22.360 --> 00:26:27.200
[Guest]: or Ik Lerki or Shubh Mangal where, you know, it's very clear in the first 10 minutes that

00:26:27.200 --> 00:26:31.640
[Guest]: they're gay, there's a gay kiss, and you know, then the story goes on.

00:26:31.640 --> 00:26:37.160
[Guest]: So yeah, we had to, we had to fantasize, we had to imagine, we had to...

00:26:37.160 --> 00:26:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another thing that's kind of struck me in many different contexts is that,

00:26:42.640 --> 00:26:47.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, being born a straight person in a heteronormative society as I am, my identity

00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:51.000
[Amit Varma]: doesn't really play a big part in my life, I can take it for granted, I don't have to

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:52.160
[Amit Varma]: think about it.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:57.040
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if you're a woman, or if you're gay, or if you're any number of things, if, you

00:26:57.040 --> 00:27:02.360
[Amit Varma]: know, if you're Dalit, that identity is like an extra layer that you always have to be

00:27:02.360 --> 00:27:04.600
[Amit Varma]: aware of, and you carry it with you.

00:27:04.600 --> 00:27:08.680
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of factors into everything you do.

00:27:08.680 --> 00:27:12.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, was that sense of that extra layer strong in you?

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:17.680
[Amit Varma]: Was there a sense of frustration at kind of, you know, having to navigate the world with

00:27:17.680 --> 00:27:22.560
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, that extra layer of awareness attached to it, which, you know, most people

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:24.800
[Guest]: around you would not have to bother with?

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:28.560
[Guest]: So Amit, here, I would like to, I would like to disagree.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:32.680
[Guest]: And I would like to say that I don't think that as a straight person, your identity does

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:35.680
[Guest]: not play a role, or that you are not conscious about it.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:42.520
[Guest]: In fact, a lot of good academic research now is coming up about straightness, or whiteness,

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:48.840
[Guest]: or, you know, all these things, which are the majority that you assume, need not think

00:27:48.840 --> 00:27:55.080
[Guest]: about themselves, need not have issues, need not be conscious, need not articulate themselves.

00:27:55.080 --> 00:28:01.640
[Guest]: So straight people also articulate their straightness in different and unique ways.

00:28:01.640 --> 00:28:05.200
[Guest]: And a lot of, in fact, I've been really toying with this idea of doing another book called

00:28:05.200 --> 00:28:10.800
[Guest]: Straightistan, where I understand straight people, and immerse myself in their world

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:12.080
[Guest]: and just see what it's like.

00:28:12.080 --> 00:28:13.080
[Guest]: What does it mean being straight?

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:18.440
[Guest]: How were you like when you were nine years old, growing up straight in India?

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:23.760
[Guest]: So I think a lot of us, you know, we, I think we're all conscious of the various facets

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:25.920
[Guest]: of our identity.

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:31.840
[Guest]: But certainly, and you live in a heteronormative, patriarchal, and in India, you know, a casteist

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:37.120
[Guest]: society which is oriented towards certain things, when you happen to be the majority,

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:40.600
[Guest]: it's a luxury to imagine that you don't have to think about certain things, right?

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:45.160
[Guest]: So as you said, you know, when you feel you're not the majority, these things, you become

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:47.680
[Guest]: slightly more conscious of it.

00:28:47.680 --> 00:28:48.880
[Guest]: So that's the thing.

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:53.160
[Guest]: But I don't think I mean, you know, I think if you're upper caste, you are conscious or

00:28:53.160 --> 00:28:57.720
[Guest]: you are aware, and your identity really frames everything that you do, in the confidence

00:28:57.720 --> 00:29:03.680
[Guest]: you have and how you physically navigate through space, how you fill up a space, how you, you

00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:09.960
[Guest]: know, have, just imagine that you have access to things, and so on, in a way that someone

00:29:09.960 --> 00:29:13.680
[Guest]: who's not upper caste might not, same way with men, right?

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:14.880
[Guest]: And that's what's so interesting.

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:20.200
[Guest]: In fact, another TED fellow, Jasmeen Patheja, you know, from that same 2009 conference has

00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:26.400
[Guest]: done these incredible experiments with blank noise, where she and, you know, fellow artist

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:32.920
[Guest]: activists go to public spaces, and just see what it does to men, when they occupy those

00:29:32.920 --> 00:29:35.800
[Guest]: spaces in a way that men do, you know.

00:29:35.800 --> 00:29:42.200
[Guest]: So for example, 10 women sit on a parapet, put one leg up on a wall, spread themselves,

00:29:42.200 --> 00:29:44.320
[Guest]: because men tend to spread themselves.

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:50.560
[Guest]: And when men pass by these women, look at them and do, you know, or whatever, you know,

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:55.280
[Guest]: make noises, or go and lie down in a park and occupy that space in that sense, right?

00:29:55.280 --> 00:30:00.560
[Guest]: In a way that, and then they record reactions of men, because men have never seen women,

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:05.680
[Guest]: in that sense, be comfortable together in a public park or lying down, or, you know,

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:11.040
[Guest]: it's very strange for men to walk by and have a group of women, maybe call them out.

00:30:11.040 --> 00:30:15.680
[Guest]: But it seems very normal for the opposite to happen, in that sense, right?

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:21.880
[Guest]: So I think, you know, when you're not in this, in the majority, then you are conscious of

00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:23.120
[Guest]: that difference, for sure.

00:30:23.120 --> 00:30:28.280
[Guest]: If you're a woman in India, you're conscious, if you're, you know, if you're Dalit, if you're

00:30:28.280 --> 00:30:35.880
[Guest]: queer, if you're Muslim, you would be conscious of how you navigate, you know, the spaces,

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:41.800
[Guest]: but also how you think of yourself, how you imagine, you know, a future for yourself,

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:46.920
[Guest]: how you negotiate, you know, various aspects of yourself.

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:53.240
[Guest]: So yeah, so certainly for me, my, while my queerness is not the only part of me that

00:30:53.240 --> 00:30:57.920
[Guest]: I talk about, I mean, you know, I'm also Sindhi, and, you know, and that comes out in so many

00:30:57.920 --> 00:30:58.920
[Guest]: ways.

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:01.680
[Guest]: I love bling, of course, and so many other things.

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:04.840
[Guest]: I mean, there's so many aspects of my identity.

00:31:04.840 --> 00:31:09.680
[Guest]: But you know, but certainly in it's tough, these are aspects that I am conscious that

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:11.840
[Guest]: I would be slightly a little more conscious about.

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:17.080
[Guest]: But by that, I'm not saying that, you know, you are also conscious of your straightness

00:31:17.080 --> 00:31:18.800
[Amit Varma]: and the way you express it in different ways.

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:20.240
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, I don't dispute that.

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:25.880
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, in the world we live in, straightness is itself an enormous privilege of a sort.

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:30.640
[Amit Varma]: What I kind of meant was that, you know, let's say, for example, just to take the male female

00:31:30.640 --> 00:31:35.760
[Amit Varma]: context, if I want to go out for a walk at 11pm, I don't have to think twice.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:40.680
[Amit Varma]: If I get into say, if I get into an elevator with five strangers, I don't have to be on

00:31:40.680 --> 00:31:45.680
[Amit Varma]: high alert and I don't have to have that extra layer of alertness, which women will naturally

00:31:45.680 --> 00:31:50.000
[Amit Varma]: have just because of the world that we unfortunately, kind of live in.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:53.760
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, I sort of, by your point there, my other question is like you pointed out

00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:57.240
[Amit Varma]: and you know, one of the things that, you know, through the book, you've spoken of how

00:31:57.240 --> 00:32:01.440
[Amit Varma]: all of us have many selves, and therefore can't just be sort of, you know, and that

00:32:01.440 --> 00:32:05.680
[Amit Varma]: is a danger to be defined by one particular kind of identity.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me there that, you know, being gay in a heteronormative society where there

00:32:09.600 --> 00:32:14.960
[Amit Varma]: is so much discrimination and prejudice and all of that, then it is such a big deal.

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:20.840
[Amit Varma]: How much then does that part of your identity sort of shape and define your life like supposing

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:25.880
[Amit Varma]: we lived in an entirely just society, where none of this existed, where it was completely

00:32:25.880 --> 00:32:29.760
[Amit Varma]: where it was as normal to be gay as to be straight, as normal in the sense in the way

00:32:29.760 --> 00:32:34.960
[Amit Varma]: of how society treats you and all that, you know, what direction would your life then

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:36.120
[Amit Varma]: have taken?

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:40.520
[Amit Varma]: It's kind of moved in this direction, because, you know, you've been kind of driven by this

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:45.760
[Amit Varma]: great cause at some level, maybe it begins with self discovery, and then it goes on to

00:32:45.760 --> 00:32:47.720
[Amit Varma]: trying to make the world a better place.

00:32:47.720 --> 00:32:51.800
[Amit Varma]: But what if the world did not need to be made better in this way?

00:32:51.800 --> 00:32:52.800
[Amit Varma]: What would you be doing today?

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Who would, you know, Parmeshani have been?

00:32:55.160 --> 00:32:58.240
[Amit Varma]: Would you still be in management at a top company?

00:32:58.240 --> 00:32:59.760
[Amit Varma]: Would there be any reason to be there?

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:01.580
[Amit Varma]: Would you be maybe an artist or something?

00:33:01.580 --> 00:33:02.640
[Guest]: What would you be?

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:04.760
[Guest]: I can still be all those other things too.

00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:08.440
[Guest]: No, I think in my case, I've been, I've been really blessed.

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:12.400
[Guest]: And I talked about these multiple privileges in the book as well as something that really,

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:16.840
[Guest]: really pushed me to create, you know, more fairer ecosystems for everyone.

00:33:16.840 --> 00:33:21.720
[Guest]: But I've been blessed in the sense that I've had, you know, while I didn't grow up in wealth,

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:27.280
[Guest]: I've had like very supportive parents, you know, who could give me an education, you

00:33:27.280 --> 00:33:30.240
[Guest]: know, at least in India until, you know, until college level.

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:35.280
[Guest]: And then, you know, when I went to the US, I, I got it on scholarship, but to have that

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:40.120
[Guest]: support, even in terms of sexuality, when I came out, it was easier with my mom and

00:33:40.120 --> 00:33:43.760
[Guest]: dad took some more time, but there was never a rejection.

00:33:43.760 --> 00:33:49.240
[Guest]: And there was never that drama of like, you know, you become straight otherwise, or like

00:33:49.240 --> 00:33:54.320
[Guest]: a lot of queer people go through real hell, there's no other word for it, they go through

00:33:54.320 --> 00:34:00.440
[Guest]: torture by their own parents and families, whether it is things like conversion therapy,

00:34:00.440 --> 00:34:06.040
[Guest]: which is sickening, that it's still happening, whether it is forced heterosexual marriage,

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:12.680
[Guest]: all the way up to people to people's own families, torturing their own children, killing them,

00:34:12.680 --> 00:34:13.680
[Guest]: all of that, right.

00:34:13.680 --> 00:34:17.280
[Guest]: So all that happens in our country, not just if you're queer, but if you're different in

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:18.280
[Guest]: any way.

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:22.520
[Guest]: So given that range of horrible things that might have happened, I think, you know, to

00:34:22.520 --> 00:34:28.280
[Guest]: have, you know, parents who love and understand you is the biggest blessing and the biggest

00:34:28.280 --> 00:34:33.480
[Guest]: privilege, which is why a lot of my book, Queeristan, is about this, about this parental

00:34:33.480 --> 00:34:36.720
[Guest]: gaze and this parental framework is something that is so vital.

00:34:36.720 --> 00:34:42.320
[Guest]: I've had schools and colleges, which have, you know, been in different levels supportive.

00:34:42.320 --> 00:34:47.320
[Guest]: I've been blessed with workplaces of, you know, different kinds, which have, even if

00:34:47.320 --> 00:34:50.680
[Guest]: they've not been supportive, they've not been overtly discriminatory.

00:34:50.680 --> 00:34:56.640
[Guest]: And these are all blessings and, you know, whether it's having academic, you know, the

00:34:56.640 --> 00:35:01.440
[Guest]: fortune of going to a place like MIT or like, you know, doing classes at places like Yale

00:35:01.440 --> 00:35:06.120
[Guest]: and all of that, which is like, opened my mind up to not just possibilities, but also

00:35:06.120 --> 00:35:09.880
[Guest]: networks of like, just amazing, inspiring people.

00:35:09.880 --> 00:35:12.320
[Guest]: Some of whom I write about in the book, right?

00:35:12.320 --> 00:35:17.400
[Guest]: People like Ahmed Katrada, who unfortunately is no more, who shared, who was in the next

00:35:17.400 --> 00:35:23.360
[Guest]: cell of Nelson Mandela on Robben Island, and who spoke to me about hope and forgiveness

00:35:23.360 --> 00:35:24.360
[Guest]: and resilience.

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:26.120
[Guest]: So, so many people, right?

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:30.640
[Guest]: Assam Dawood, who's doing incredible work on refugees in Israel and Palestine.

00:35:30.640 --> 00:35:35.200
[Guest]: And there's so many incredible people whom I've met through this, you know, through my

00:35:35.200 --> 00:35:36.600
[Guest]: education journeys.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:42.120
[Guest]: So I think I would have been doing exactly this because, you know, I don't think I would

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:47.320
[Guest]: have been doing anything different had we been living in a, you know, in a more heteronormative,

00:35:47.320 --> 00:35:50.680
[Guest]: I think I would have been working on the different things that interest me.

00:35:50.680 --> 00:35:53.520
[Guest]: I would have been trying to connect them together.

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:57.720
[Guest]: And in a way, this is where I'm going to even now, because, you know, one of my realizations

00:35:57.720 --> 00:36:05.680
[Guest]: over the past 10 years and in between the two books has been very much about intersectionality.

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:10.780
[Guest]: This is something that I've learned completely from the young people that I've been lucky

00:36:10.780 --> 00:36:14.120
[Guest]: enough to hang out with and learn my own team members.

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:18.600
[Guest]: So many of the people that you encounter in the book, whether it's Professor Dhiren Borissa

00:36:18.600 --> 00:36:26.240
[Guest]: from OP Jindal, whether it's Grace Banu, who's an incredible trans rights activist from Tuticorin

00:36:26.240 --> 00:36:32.680
[Guest]: in Tamil Nadu, whether it's Rafiul, who runs the Queer Muslim Project, whether it's Aro,

00:36:32.680 --> 00:36:38.080
[Guest]: who along with an incredible team run Dalit Queer Project, and people whom I haven't met,

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:42.360
[Guest]: whether it's Greta Thurberg or others, right, all around the world are trying to create

00:36:42.360 --> 00:36:52.440
[Guest]: a better world in terms of environment, gender, and so on.

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:57.240
[Guest]: Even my own learning over the past 10 years has been that if you care about queer rights

00:36:57.240 --> 00:37:02.760
[Guest]: and queer inclusion, like I do, you really have to contextualize these in the context

00:37:02.760 --> 00:37:06.820
[Guest]: of other movements for social change and social justice.

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:12.720
[Guest]: And you really need to, in a sense, build bridges of solidarity with others, because

00:37:12.720 --> 00:37:17.760
[Guest]: we can't say that you want a more better world for queer people only, and not recognize that

00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:25.400
[Guest]: the struggle is linked to the anti-caste movement, or the movement for a better, cleaner environment,

00:37:25.400 --> 00:37:30.840
[Guest]: or Black Lives Matter in the US or other parts of the world, and so many other social justice

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:35.380
[Guest]: movements which are happening all over the world, all powered by young people.

00:37:35.380 --> 00:37:40.600
[Guest]: So my thinking also has grown because of the people I've encountered and met into realizing

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:47.260
[Guest]: the intersectional nature of the struggle, that's one.

00:37:47.260 --> 00:37:53.560
[Guest]: And the other is in realizing that the interconnected nature of what the solution might be.

00:37:53.560 --> 00:37:59.080
[Guest]: So a lot of Queeristan, the book itself, talks about the fact that we live in a world where

00:37:59.080 --> 00:38:08.960
[Guest]: companies, NGOs, different governments, national, state, municipal, will have to come together

00:38:08.960 --> 00:38:13.720
[Guest]: in different ways, in different formations to solve some of these issues.

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:20.520
[Guest]: Because the challenges are not something that any one of these stakeholders will be able

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:23.120
[Guest]: to do by themselves, right?

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:27.280
[Guest]: So I mean, this is where my mind is moving towards more and more.

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:32.240
[Guest]: How do we create, they needn't be tight networks of collaboration, they could be loose for

00:38:32.240 --> 00:38:39.980
[Guest]: certain projects or things, as we saw post-COVID, for example, we saw companies come forward

00:38:39.980 --> 00:38:47.120
[Guest]: and give money and resources, we saw incredible NGOs come together and organize relief, we

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:51.640
[Guest]: saw state governments that got into action and helped and empowered, things like that,

00:38:51.640 --> 00:38:55.680
[Guest]: which is why, I mean, some of the stuff could happen.

00:38:55.680 --> 00:38:58.400
[Guest]: So I think a lot of the future is going to be about this.

00:38:58.400 --> 00:39:03.760
[Guest]: And my thinking is that, you know, I would have anyway been on this track, even otherwise.

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:08.920
[Guest]: Now I'm more and more on just thinking about what would it mean to build these other kinds

00:39:08.920 --> 00:39:13.240
[Guest]: of connections, these other kinds of solidarities, and move ahead.

00:39:13.240 --> 00:39:16.240
[Guest]: And I've completely rambled, but yours is a long form podcast.

00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:17.240
[Guest]: So that's wonderful.

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:21.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, rambling here is a feature, not a bug, that's what the listeners kind

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:22.840
[Amit Varma]: of appreciate.

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:25.760
[Amit Varma]: But there's sort of, you know, some fascinating strands in what you just said.

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And one, of course, is, you know, you mentioned Amit Katrada, who was, you know, Mandela's

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.080
[Amit Varma]: cell mate, and you recount this fascinating bit in your book, where he was showing you

00:39:35.080 --> 00:39:38.000
[Amit Varma]: around the cell block where the two of them were housed.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:43.800
[Amit Varma]: And the part that really jumped out at me over there is about how he was talking about,

00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:48.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, it took us 10 years of agitation to be allowed to read newspapers, and 15 years

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:52.400
[Amit Varma]: of agitation to sort of be allowed pen and paper or whatever.

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:56.960
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, those were the kind of timespans that you're talking about, where you just

00:39:56.960 --> 00:40:00.960
[Amit Varma]: keep trying, you don't know if it will happen in your own lifetime, and you make incremental

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:04.000
[Amit Varma]: progress at 10 year and five year chunks.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Whereas, you know, in these modern times, perhaps, that's vastly accelerated by, you

00:40:10.160 --> 00:40:14.000
[Amit Varma]: know, social media and globalization, would you say that's the case?

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:18.960
[Amit Varma]: Like I'm, there's one passage in your book also that kind of struck me, which is about

00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:25.360
[Amit Varma]: the impact of liberalization on the gay movement, where at one point, you write, I'll quote

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:30.880
[Amit Varma]: your words, quote, consider the designer Janjum Gadi, who hails from Tirbin, a remote village

00:40:30.880 --> 00:40:35.680
[Amit Varma]: in Arunachal Pradesh, electricity came to his village only in the late 1990s.

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:39.880
[Amit Varma]: He stumbled upon fashion while going through old issues of femina, imagine the journey

00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:44.600
[Amit Varma]: of transportation from the northeast to Delhi, possibly because of new post liberalization

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:50.280
[Amit Varma]: air routes of education at Wigan and Lake College possible because of post 1990s needed

00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:55.440
[Amit Varma]: new kinds of colleges of internship with Rohit Bal, the legend who attended Janjum's graduation

00:40:55.440 --> 00:40:59.920
[Amit Varma]: at which he won Best Designer of his debut Fashion Week presentation, possible because

00:40:59.920 --> 00:41:04.440
[Amit Varma]: there was now a network of such biannual shows offering visibility to young talent and of

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:05.440
[Amit Varma]: sales.

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:09.760
[Amit Varma]: Again, this post liberalization India had created a new customer base, eager to consume

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:11.560
[Amit Varma]: fashion, stop quote.

00:41:11.560 --> 00:41:17.920
[Amit Varma]: And this is, again, sort of tangential, but it strikes me that in a lot of activism, especially

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:23.120
[Amit Varma]: left wing activism, you know, free markets and capitalism are often given such a bad

00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:24.120
[Amit Varma]: name.

00:41:24.120 --> 00:41:28.740
[Amit Varma]: Well, the way I kind of look at markets is that markets are the way by which a society

00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:35.280
[Amit Varma]: fulfills its own needs, you know, voluntary actions in about so to say, and this is also

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:41.680
[Amit Varma]: something that you seem to have embraced, because rather than sort of work in a dusty NGO and

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:46.720
[Amit Varma]: work in villages in the bylanes of towns, one of the things that you do is, you know,

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:52.520
[Amit Varma]: work within a company and work with corporates to actually make things better on the ground.

00:41:52.520 --> 00:41:59.080
[Amit Varma]: So in this one aspect, you seem to have a more optimistic view than, you know, many

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:02.600
[Amit Varma]: other activists would, is this something that you've thought about?

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:05.960
[Amit Varma]: Or is this something that you, you know, that you evolved towards?

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Or did you always sort of disagree with the demonization of markets and evil capitalists

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:12.440
[Amit Varma]: and so on?

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:17.480
[Guest]: No, I don't disagree with the demonization of markets and evil capitalism, there is a

00:42:17.480 --> 00:42:21.280
[Guest]: lot of merit in the criticism of capitalism.

00:42:21.280 --> 00:42:25.080
[Guest]: And we are seeing, we have seen it in the past few years, right, Piketty has written

00:42:25.080 --> 00:42:29.960
[Guest]: about this, as have so many others, whether it's, you know, Amartya Sen, John Reyes in

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:37.360
[Guest]: India, and so many others, about, you know, how inequality and even, you know, Abhijit

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:40.840
[Guest]: and Esther, right, you know, who work so much on poverty, right.

00:42:40.840 --> 00:42:46.960
[Guest]: So clearly, our world is becoming more and more unequal.

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:51.600
[Guest]: And you know, one of the perils of capitalism is that it has been widening inequalities,

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:53.520
[Guest]: and that has been terrible.

00:42:53.520 --> 00:42:55.640
[Guest]: Capitalism has been is good in so many ways, right.

00:42:55.640 --> 00:43:02.000
[Guest]: In that passage that you read out, it shows you the liberating, you know, both in an imaginative

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:07.320
[Guest]: and in a really, in an economic sense, power of capitalism, say, for young Janjum, and

00:43:07.320 --> 00:43:09.260
[Guest]: the leap that Janjum has been able to make.

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:13.840
[Guest]: But in so many other cases, and you know, that's, I mean, that's been that's great.

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:18.120
[Guest]: But in so many other cases, certainly, I mean, you know, capitalism has led to a widening

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:19.120
[Guest]: of inequalities.

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:27.520
[Guest]: And so I think it's really time to reimagine capitalism, really look at this inequality,

00:43:27.520 --> 00:43:34.560
[Guest]: and figure out how to, you know, stem it, stop it, reduce it, cannot continue like this

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:35.560
[Guest]: forever.

00:43:35.560 --> 00:43:40.400
[Amit Varma]: Can I interject and sort of make a larger point about economic inequality, which I keep

00:43:40.400 --> 00:43:46.440
[Amit Varma]: making is that I think people who worry about economic inequality commit what I call the

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:50.680
[Amit Varma]: zero sum fallacy, where they assume that there is a fixed amount of money in the world.

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:54.600
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, inequality is bad, because of the rich get richer, the poor get poorer,

00:43:54.600 --> 00:43:58.500
[Amit Varma]: obviously, in a zero sum world, more inequality would mean more poverty.

00:43:58.500 --> 00:44:02.240
[Amit Varma]: But what happens in developing countries, and what has certainly happened in India over

00:44:02.240 --> 00:44:08.560
[Amit Varma]: the last, you know, 30 years, is that inequality has grown as poverty has declined, because

00:44:08.560 --> 00:44:13.120
[Amit Varma]: we're not in a zero sum world, every voluntary transaction is both people better off.

00:44:13.120 --> 00:44:17.560
[Amit Varma]: So what you've, you know, the post liberalization estimates say there have been some 300 million

00:44:17.560 --> 00:44:23.160
[Amit Varma]: people come out of poverty, which to me is a moral triumph, because poverty is to me

00:44:23.160 --> 00:44:25.040
[Amit Varma]: India's biggest problem.

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:29.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the solutions for poverty and inequality are very different, you could solve

00:44:29.760 --> 00:44:33.320
[Amit Varma]: inequality in a flash by making everybody equally poor.

00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And I kind of go by what Harry Frankfurt calls the doctrine of sufficiency, Harry Frankfurt

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:43.320
[Amit Varma]: is a philosopher who's written this great book called on inequality, and he's also written

00:44:43.320 --> 00:44:47.080
[Amit Varma]: a fabulous book called on bullshit, which kind of describes a lot of what comes out

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:49.360
[Amit Varma]: of Trump and Modi these days.

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:53.120
[Amit Varma]: But the phrase that he coins is a doctrine of sufficiency, where he says that what is

00:44:53.120 --> 00:45:00.440
[Amit Varma]: important is to go by, you know, how absolute levels of poverty are that the doctrine of

00:45:00.440 --> 00:45:05.040
[Amit Varma]: sufficiency essentially states and I'm obviously paraphrasing here, because it's from memory,

00:45:05.040 --> 00:45:11.400
[Amit Varma]: that everyone should have enough to kind of whatever suffices to live a good life at least.

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:16.680
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, India, you know, I think a lot of our dialogue about inequality doesn't

00:45:16.680 --> 00:45:19.640
[Amit Varma]: take this into account, it assumes that there is a zero sum world.

00:45:19.640 --> 00:45:24.360
[Amit Varma]: But the point is that, as poverty declines, inequality will go up.

00:45:24.360 --> 00:45:26.940
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, in India, vice versa.

00:45:26.940 --> 00:45:32.120
[Amit Varma]: But the larger issue of the zero sum fallacy, and I'm just thinking aloud here, it seems

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:40.400
[Amit Varma]: to me can also, you know, crop up in certain kinds of activism, where, you know, the way

00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:46.100
[Amit Varma]: I see it is that I would love all individuals to be empowered and have the same kind of

00:45:46.100 --> 00:45:48.960
[Amit Varma]: opportunities and we can all grow together.

00:45:48.960 --> 00:45:54.800
[Amit Varma]: And yet there is a sense in some kinds of dialogue and some kinds of discourse that,

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:59.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, people with x identity are enemies of people with y identity.

00:45:59.040 --> 00:46:05.480
[Amit Varma]: And it almost has a feel of a zero sum game that, you know, x oppressed us for centuries

00:46:05.480 --> 00:46:09.600
[Amit Varma]: or x broke our temple and made a mosque or whatever, it can come from either the right

00:46:09.600 --> 00:46:11.080
[Amit Varma]: or the left.

00:46:11.080 --> 00:46:16.280
[Amit Varma]: And, and therefore, as why we must stand up and take revenge, which again, sort of to

00:46:16.280 --> 00:46:23.520
[Amit Varma]: me, seems to be stuck in that kind of mindset, it's not really leading to a question.

00:46:23.520 --> 00:46:27.560
[Amit Varma]: But since you kind of brought it up, I thought it's, I'll just kind of state this counter

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:28.560
[Guest]: view.

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:33.920
[Guest]: I agree completely with you that zero sum games are, you know, are limiting, which is

00:46:33.920 --> 00:46:38.360
[Guest]: right, this, you know, the book is very much about win-win scenarios.

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:45.000
[Guest]: And across everyone, which is also why the book has a range of individuals across the

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:46.040
[Guest]: spectrum in it.

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:50.840
[Guest]: It's an inclusive book in the sense that it has people who might be right leaning, it

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:55.520
[Guest]: has people who might be left leaning, it has people who are centrist.

00:46:55.520 --> 00:47:02.040
[Guest]: And to get back to your question earlier about a tension, say, between activism and capitalism

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:08.640
[Guest]: in that sense, I actually think, I don't think of it as oppositional.

00:47:08.640 --> 00:47:14.240
[Guest]: I think a lot of the work that we are doing, and we need to acknowledge it, a lot of the

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:18.640
[Guest]: work that we are doing in the corporate world, for example, is built on years and years of

00:47:18.640 --> 00:47:22.320
[Guest]: labor of our activist friends.

00:47:22.320 --> 00:47:27.120
[Guest]: And I think it's vital to acknowledge the fact that all this work is being built upon

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:29.240
[Guest]: it, and it continues to be built upon it, right?

00:47:29.240 --> 00:47:37.040
[Guest]: So whether it is NGOs who have struggled for years, whether it is activists who came out

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:44.000
[Guest]: from the 70s onwards, and paved the way for, you know, this generation to do the kind of

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:48.640
[Guest]: work that it's doing, whether it's the lawyers who fought everyone, you know, there are so

00:47:48.640 --> 00:47:52.480
[Guest]: many cases from the 90s onwards.

00:47:52.480 --> 00:47:55.960
[Guest]: And you know, people remember the 2018 victory.

00:47:55.960 --> 00:48:01.280
[Guest]: But you know, there were lawyers who were involved in 2013, 2009, even before that,

00:48:01.280 --> 00:48:02.280
[Guest]: right?

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:03.540
[Guest]: All those struggles.

00:48:03.540 --> 00:48:07.400
[Guest]: So I actually think, I don't think of it as oppositional at all.

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:13.760
[Guest]: I think, you know, I think of it as a universe in which we all are doing whatever we can,

00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:14.840
[Guest]: wherever, wherever we can.

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:19.680
[Guest]: So I situated myself in the corporate world, because I could, because I also felt that

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:27.800
[Guest]: there was a need for someone like me, who is able to, in a sense, shape, shift and translate.

00:48:27.800 --> 00:48:32.600
[Guest]: And I felt that my work would be more useful from a corporate world.

00:48:32.600 --> 00:48:36.120
[Guest]: Because even with the toehold that I have, like, I don't have power in the corporate

00:48:36.120 --> 00:48:39.840
[Guest]: world, honestly, I have influence, right?

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:41.720
[Guest]: But I have a toehold of influence.

00:48:41.720 --> 00:48:49.320
[Guest]: So how can I use that position to put that toe in, kind of Biden, open a door, you know,

00:48:49.320 --> 00:48:50.560
[Guest]: first at Godrej.

00:48:50.560 --> 00:48:54.800
[Guest]: And then, you know, hopefully in other companies, and say, let's talk about this.

00:48:54.800 --> 00:48:55.800
[Guest]: Let's do this.

00:48:55.800 --> 00:48:56.800
[Guest]: Let's do this, right?

00:48:56.800 --> 00:49:01.400
[Guest]: There's no way that I could be, that I would be successful at doing all of the work that

00:49:01.400 --> 00:49:06.480
[Guest]: I've been doing, actually, if it was not for my activist friends on the ground, who are

00:49:06.480 --> 00:49:09.120
[Guest]: actually doing the real heavy lifting.

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:14.560
[Guest]: If it was not for my academic friends in universities, who are questioning, who are pushing, who

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:18.360
[Guest]: are countering, who are reflecting.

00:49:18.360 --> 00:49:23.480
[Guest]: So I think we have to stop thinking of these spaces as oppositional, and instead think

00:49:23.480 --> 00:49:25.440
[Guest]: of them as nodes.

00:49:25.440 --> 00:49:31.440
[Guest]: What we should also stop thinking of them as silos, silos, from which we cannot share,

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:38.240
[Guest]: connect, interact, disagree with each other, but hopefully, ultimately be productive in

00:49:38.240 --> 00:49:41.120
[Guest]: the kind of world building that we want to engage in.

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:46.200
[Guest]: And I learned this from Sir Ian McKellen, who when he visited Bombay some years ago,

00:49:46.200 --> 00:49:50.960
[Guest]: younger viewers of this podcast might know him as Gandalf and Magneto.

00:49:50.960 --> 00:49:57.680
[Guest]: For the older listeners, it would be the famous Shakespearean actor, Sir Ian McKellen.

00:49:57.680 --> 00:50:05.640
[Guest]: And you know, Ian is Ian for me, Sir Ian for all of y'all, because he's my friend.

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:11.640
[Guest]: Yeah, Magneto is my friend, all of y'all must be so jealous.

00:50:11.640 --> 00:50:13.640
[Guest]: This is why you're so magnetic.

00:50:13.640 --> 00:50:16.800
[Guest]: Yes, it rubbed off.

00:50:16.800 --> 00:50:17.800
[Guest]: And he said that, right.

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:25.040
[Guest]: So Ian is also, he started Stonewall, which is this incredible queer rights NGO based

00:50:25.040 --> 00:50:26.480
[Guest]: out of the UK.

00:50:26.480 --> 00:50:30.840
[Guest]: And he actually told me, he said, Look, Parmesh, I've been doing this for years.

00:50:30.840 --> 00:50:35.240
[Guest]: And we all I mean, my realization is that we are all needed, right?

00:50:35.240 --> 00:50:39.000
[Guest]: We need our activist friends on the streets to push for change.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:44.440
[Guest]: We need people in academia to imagine new worlds, and to teach generations of people

00:50:44.440 --> 00:50:45.880
[Guest]: about these new worlds.

00:50:45.880 --> 00:50:51.280
[Guest]: But we need people like you and me, who can, you know, maybe wear a business suit, go to

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:55.560
[Guest]: the businesses, go to the politicians, talk to them and say, Look, there's a new world

00:50:55.560 --> 00:50:56.560
[Guest]: coming.

00:50:56.560 --> 00:50:57.560
[Guest]: How do we work together?

00:50:57.560 --> 00:51:00.720
[Guest]: And he said, we all need to do our role.

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:04.080
[Guest]: And to imagine that, you know, just one of us is going to bring about change would be

00:51:04.080 --> 00:51:05.880
[Guest]: whatever, change comes with the whole system.

00:51:05.880 --> 00:51:10.200
[Guest]: Now, my point in this whole book is to recognize that there's an ecosystem.

00:51:10.200 --> 00:51:15.260
[Guest]: And to recognize that, you know, there are multiple spaces where change is happening,

00:51:15.260 --> 00:51:18.560
[Guest]: but also to help correct some of those things, right?

00:51:18.560 --> 00:51:25.200
[Guest]: I think even within the queer movement, right, there is a genuine dissatisfaction that, you

00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:30.760
[Guest]: know, gay men tend to do a lot of the talking and tend to get a lot of the credit, right.

00:51:30.760 --> 00:51:34.640
[Guest]: So I've written this book being very conscious that I'm a gay person, that I'm a gay man

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:37.040
[Guest]: myself, right?

00:51:37.040 --> 00:51:43.120
[Guest]: How does one use these projects to create platforms and amplify other voices, which

00:51:43.120 --> 00:51:48.360
[Guest]: are, you know, within the movements, which have been, you know, fundamental in helping

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:53.440
[Guest]: shape the movement, but because of structure, or so many other things not been heard, right?

00:51:53.440 --> 00:52:00.320
[Guest]: So how do we foreground or create platforms to forefront trans voices, lesbian voices,

00:52:00.320 --> 00:52:05.320
[Guest]: Dalit voices, you know, so many of these other things is also something that I've been, you

00:52:05.320 --> 00:52:10.040
[Guest]: know, very, very conscious of in this process.

00:52:10.040 --> 00:52:13.840
[Amit Varma]: One of the sort of things that I found profoundly impressive about the work that you've done

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:19.480
[Amit Varma]: and Sir Ian has done, I can't call him Ian, that Sir Ian has done and almost all the people

00:52:19.480 --> 00:52:24.280
[Amit Varma]: whose stories you've related in your book have done comes from sort of a common, you

00:52:24.280 --> 00:52:30.080
[Amit Varma]: know, bypasses a common complaint that I often have about how liberals in India have approached,

00:52:30.080 --> 00:52:33.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, their idea of India, where, you know, one of the themes, which is almost a

00:52:33.640 --> 00:52:37.660
[Amit Varma]: cliche on this podcast, which I'll often ask guests when I'm talking about political philosophy

00:52:37.660 --> 00:52:44.920
[Amit Varma]: and so on, is what we seem to have done in 1950 is a bunch of liberal elites imposed

00:52:44.920 --> 00:52:50.000
[Amit Varma]: relatively liberal constitution, not as liberal as I'd like, but a relatively liberal constitution

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.520
[Amit Varma]: on an illiberal society.

00:52:52.520 --> 00:52:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And but we couldn't see those ideas within society itself.

00:52:57.040 --> 00:53:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And what has happened today is that if you look at our politics, you know, our politics

00:53:01.960 --> 00:53:06.240
[Amit Varma]: has caught up with our culture, you know, Andrew Breitbart once said that politics is

00:53:06.240 --> 00:53:07.400
[Amit Varma]: downstream of culture.

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:12.700
[Amit Varma]: So it kind of strikes me that if you want to affect true change is difficult to do it

00:53:12.700 --> 00:53:13.700
[Amit Varma]: from the top down.

00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:16.720
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it simply will not work, it has to go the other way.

00:53:16.720 --> 00:53:22.320
[Amit Varma]: And that's much harder, you know, it's much easier to, you know, try to get the state

00:53:22.320 --> 00:53:26.420
[Amit Varma]: to do things in a top down way, it's far harder to get into the culture, because then it takes

00:53:26.420 --> 00:53:30.600
[Amit Varma]: years, if not decades for these ideas to sort of percolate through because you want the

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:36.680
[Amit Varma]: culture to change, you want, you know, LGBTQ people to be accepted, not because there is

00:53:36.680 --> 00:53:41.640
[Amit Varma]: a law which says you shall not discriminate, but because people accept it from their hearts.

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think, you know, one of the things that does make me hopeful, despite the way our

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:51.280
[Amit Varma]: politics is going, is that, you know, to paraphrase Martin Luther King, the arc of history seems

00:53:51.280 --> 00:53:56.560
[Amit Varma]: to be bending towards inclusion, in the sense that, you know, I remember when in 2018, when

00:53:56.560 --> 00:53:59.940
[Amit Varma]: the judgment happened, where 377 was outlawed once again.

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:04.280
[Amit Varma]: And I thought to myself that if this had happened in 1988, there would be so many voices raised

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:05.280
[Amit Varma]: against it.

00:54:05.280 --> 00:54:11.100
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I can't recall, you know, apart from people on the fringes, anybody really

00:54:11.100 --> 00:54:15.000
[Amit Varma]: against that sort of wonderful judgment in 2018.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:21.100
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, it seems to me that, you know, for a variety of reasons, maybe openness

00:54:21.100 --> 00:54:26.120
[Amit Varma]: to global influences and social media and all that, you know, society has changed and

00:54:26.120 --> 00:54:30.480
[Amit Varma]: become more tolerant and all of that, at least in these specific contexts.

00:54:30.480 --> 00:54:36.440
[Amit Varma]: But the other sort of interesting aspect that I really liked and admired is that, you know,

00:54:36.440 --> 00:54:40.200
[Amit Varma]: what you're trying to do in your case, in the context of corporates, but also other

00:54:40.200 --> 00:54:45.000
[Amit Varma]: contexts like you do with the Goodrich Culture Lab, is bring this bottom up change in the

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:46.000
[Amit Varma]: culture.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:51.760
[Amit Varma]: Is this something that you've kind of thought about, you know, was there a conscious understanding

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:53.560
[Amit Varma]: that this is how we need to do it?

00:54:53.560 --> 00:54:55.400
[Amit Varma]: Or did things just happen along the way?

00:54:55.400 --> 00:54:57.440
[Guest]: Yeah, so I try and do both.

00:54:57.440 --> 00:55:02.080
[Guest]: And, you know, I don't know how much of say the work through the lab is bottoms up, because,

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:07.000
[Guest]: you know, there's so much we're just one of the multiple spaces in, you know, Mumbai and

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:12.040
[Guest]: then the country, which hosts and different kinds of conversations.

00:55:12.040 --> 00:55:17.280
[Guest]: It's certainly an attempt to platform and amplify a range of voices, which are all talking

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:19.280
[Guest]: about contemporary India.

00:55:19.280 --> 00:55:23.520
[Guest]: And over the years, I think we've, you know, based on different themes, I think we've been

00:55:23.520 --> 00:55:29.880
[Guest]: able to showcase, you know, incredible individuals, through a range of different formats as well,

00:55:29.880 --> 00:55:34.400
[Guest]: physical, mostly physical events, but now shifting to online.

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:36.660
[Guest]: So yeah, that's been very, very good.

00:55:36.660 --> 00:55:38.520
[Guest]: But I also think that it is a combination.

00:55:38.520 --> 00:55:44.680
[Guest]: Again, it's not, because I think, at least in the corporate world, I'm very impatient,

00:55:44.680 --> 00:55:47.280
[Guest]: and I can't wait for bottoms up change to happen.

00:55:47.280 --> 00:55:53.080
[Guest]: So I strongly recommend in the corporate world, and given how, you know, hierarchical Indian

00:55:53.080 --> 00:55:56.880
[Guest]: society is in terms of, you know, where the government, where the corporations, etc, I

00:55:56.880 --> 00:56:03.440
[Guest]: actually say, if you can influence people at the top, and if until the culture, I mean,

00:56:03.440 --> 00:56:08.400
[Guest]: I'm not saying we shouldn't focus on the cultural change, and, you know, help change societal

00:56:08.400 --> 00:56:11.000
[Guest]: attitudes, values, etc, towards.

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:15.920
[Guest]: But as you rightly said, that's a long term project, until then, it would really help

00:56:15.920 --> 00:56:21.280
[Guest]: if we had the chairperson, the chief minister, etc, say, look, this matters.

00:56:21.280 --> 00:56:22.280
[Guest]: I want to do this.

00:56:22.280 --> 00:56:23.760
[Guest]: Here's how we're going to do it.

00:56:23.760 --> 00:56:26.840
[Guest]: I want to report in like, you know, one year or whatever.

00:56:26.840 --> 00:56:30.840
[Guest]: I mean, India also really works like that.

00:56:30.840 --> 00:56:36.560
[Guest]: And one of the reasons that say, Godrej has been made maybe more successful in this, in

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:40.520
[Guest]: the small journey that we've taken so far than the other companies is at Godrej.

00:56:40.520 --> 00:56:45.880
[Guest]: It was Nisa Godrej from the Godrej family chairperson saying inclusion matters to us.

00:56:45.880 --> 00:56:47.440
[Guest]: Here is what we're going to do.

00:56:47.440 --> 00:56:51.520
[Guest]: I want to create a Godrej which is more inclusive, make it happen.

00:56:51.520 --> 00:56:57.800
[Guest]: So everyone across the group, right, would read this message and say, okay, you know,

00:56:57.800 --> 00:57:04.760
[Guest]: the chairperson from the family, this is what, you know, let's think about this, right?

00:57:04.760 --> 00:57:09.720
[Guest]: In so many other companies, it might be someone really well-meaning from HR, driving it through

00:57:09.720 --> 00:57:12.200
[Guest]: diversity and inclusion.

00:57:12.200 --> 00:57:15.040
[Guest]: It might not have the same impact.

00:57:15.040 --> 00:57:19.440
[Guest]: So I think we have to do in, you know, which is why in states, right, and we talk about

00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:25.680
[Guest]: some of the progressive states in India, right, in Kerala, in Chhattisgarh, the chief ministers

00:57:25.680 --> 00:57:31.200
[Guest]: have gone on record to say that, you know, they care about LGBT inclusion, they've given

00:57:31.200 --> 00:57:37.280
[Guest]: scholarships to trans people, they have supported so many events and so on.

00:57:37.280 --> 00:57:41.360
[Guest]: The bureaucracy will change, you know, when that clear direction comes, right?

00:57:41.360 --> 00:57:42.760
[Guest]: And then that change percolates as well.

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:45.440
[Guest]: So I actually think it's a combination of both.

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:51.240
[Guest]: I think for immediate effect, it's actually more timely and like it just, you know, it's

00:57:51.240 --> 00:57:54.640
[Guest]: just more clever to work with a top-down approach.

00:57:54.640 --> 00:58:02.360
[Guest]: But certainly the long-term project has to be, you know, a long drawn attempt at cultural,

00:58:02.360 --> 00:58:07.320
[Guest]: at socio-cultural change through various things, through education, through movies, through

00:58:07.320 --> 00:58:09.480
[Guest]: role modeling and, you know, so on.

00:58:09.480 --> 00:58:10.560
[Guest]: That takes time.

00:58:10.560 --> 00:58:14.640
[Guest]: And you know, as I write in the book, I don't have, I mean, I don't want to wait.

00:58:14.640 --> 00:58:15.640
[Guest]: I don't want to wait.

00:58:15.640 --> 00:58:20.600
[Guest]: I mean, we waited for seven decades after independence.

00:58:20.600 --> 00:58:25.980
[Guest]: My queer brothers and sisters have waited for seven decades to be decriminalized.

00:58:25.980 --> 00:58:29.680
[Guest]: And having said that as well, there's no equality as such, right?

00:58:29.680 --> 00:58:35.800
[Guest]: Because we may have had this 2018 verdict, but we've also had at the same time, and you

00:58:35.800 --> 00:58:41.600
[Guest]: know, people tend to forget that we had a 2014 NALSA judgment, which was visionary in

00:58:41.600 --> 00:58:48.920
[Guest]: terms of the scope of rights it offered our trans citizens of this country, which has

00:58:48.920 --> 00:58:54.280
[Guest]: led to actually a not so sensitive Trans Act, which has recently been followed, right?

00:58:54.280 --> 00:59:00.760
[Guest]: So there's so much we need to change the Trans Act, you know, hopefully soon, so that the

00:59:00.760 --> 00:59:05.040
[Guest]: spirit of the NALSA judgment can actually be, can live in the Trans Act, you know, on

00:59:05.040 --> 00:59:06.320
[Guest]: multiple fronts.

00:59:06.320 --> 00:59:12.360
[Guest]: We need to convert the non-criminality, which is what section 377 going away has offered

00:59:12.360 --> 00:59:19.000
[Guest]: us into real equality on multiple fronts, which is comprehensive anti-discrimination

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:23.880
[Guest]: laws in our country, which we don't have other kinds of equality laws.

00:59:23.880 --> 00:59:28.600
[Guest]: I write in the book about how, you know, at least for me personally, I would love to be

00:59:28.600 --> 00:59:32.920
[Guest]: married to my partner, I would love to frame my marriage certificate on the wall, and do

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:35.300
[Guest]: all those kind of maybe it's very silly.

00:59:35.300 --> 00:59:39.880
[Guest]: So many of my friends critique me, they say, you know, you're doing heteronormative mimicry.

00:59:39.880 --> 00:59:43.880
[Guest]: But you know, I want the right to do that if I choose, I mean, it's not heteronormative

00:59:43.880 --> 00:59:44.880
[Guest]: mimicry.

00:59:44.880 --> 00:59:50.160
[Guest]: For me, it's Karan Johar and Yash Chopra obsessed, Bollywood obsessed mimicry.

00:59:50.160 --> 00:59:51.840
[Guest]: Growing up in the 80s and 90s, what to do?

00:59:51.840 --> 00:59:57.000
[Guest]: I blame Shah Rukh for all my romantic constructs.

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:02.300
[Guest]: But why shouldn't we have, I mean, why shouldn't I have the rights to be as silly and stupid

01:00:02.300 --> 01:00:05.200
[Guest]: as everyone else if you know, in doing all of these things, right?

01:00:05.200 --> 01:00:08.200
[Guest]: So I think we have a lot of work to do.

01:00:08.200 --> 01:00:13.800
[Guest]: And in that work, I mean, I think a top down approach, I would like both.

01:00:13.800 --> 01:00:17.480
[Guest]: I would like people in positions of power saying this matters, and let's do it as well

01:00:17.480 --> 01:00:18.480
[Guest]: as cultural change.

01:00:18.480 --> 01:00:21.480
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I buy that, you know, both together can be helpful.

01:00:21.480 --> 01:00:22.780
[Amit Varma]: And it's not either or.

01:00:22.780 --> 01:00:27.000
[Amit Varma]: But I was actually interpreting the work that you do with corporate leaders, like, you know,

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:32.080
[Amit Varma]: Nisa Godrej doing the things that she does, as, in a sense, bottom up, because it's not

01:00:32.080 --> 01:00:36.600
[Amit Varma]: imposed by the state saying do this, it is voluntary action.

01:00:36.600 --> 01:00:41.560
[Amit Varma]: It's someone who runs a company herself saying that, you know, this is a sort of culture

01:00:41.560 --> 01:00:44.400
[Amit Varma]: I would like in my company, and this is what I'll do for it.

01:00:44.400 --> 01:00:49.360
[Amit Varma]: So in that sense, you know, because it's voluntary action and not imposed by the state, I was

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:53.640
[Amit Varma]: referring to that as bottom up, I can see how in through another prism, it can seem

01:00:53.640 --> 01:00:58.080
[Amit Varma]: as top down and in the context of what is happening within the company.

01:00:58.080 --> 01:01:02.360
[Amit Varma]: And my next question kind of comes there, that, you know, as you've sort of detailed

01:01:02.360 --> 01:01:06.600
[Amit Varma]: through your book, it's, you know, you've done pioneering work with Godrej and you know,

01:01:06.600 --> 01:01:11.400
[Amit Varma]: various other companies have also kind of been doing great work from, you know, IBM

01:01:11.400 --> 01:01:14.440
[Amit Varma]: to Cummins to, you know, various other people.

01:01:14.440 --> 01:01:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Now, the question is that there was also that sort of disturbing example of that person

01:01:20.720 --> 01:01:26.160
[Amit Varma]: in charge of diversity and inclusion at Tech Mahindra, who was, you know, bigoted towards

01:01:26.160 --> 01:01:27.240
[Amit Varma]: a gay employee.

01:01:27.240 --> 01:01:30.960
[Amit Varma]: And when that came out, of course, when it became a big thing on Twitter, she was fired

01:01:30.960 --> 01:01:32.840
[Amit Varma]: and an inquiry was done and all of that.

01:01:32.840 --> 01:01:38.600
[Amit Varma]: And as you point out, the people who actually, you know, Anand Mahindra, who actually runs

01:01:38.600 --> 01:01:42.960
[Amit Varma]: a company is extremely enlightened that way, but that doesn't necessarily seep through

01:01:42.960 --> 01:01:43.960
[Amit Varma]: the culture.

01:01:43.960 --> 01:01:48.800
[Amit Varma]: And this is a question that you've sort of raised yourself at that point where you talk

01:01:48.800 --> 01:01:53.200
[Amit Varma]: about this incident, that, you know, it's okay to have enlightened people at the top

01:01:53.200 --> 01:01:57.720
[Amit Varma]: make these rules and make these whatever, but it's also, you know, you know, that doesn't

01:01:57.720 --> 01:02:03.200
[Amit Varma]: necessarily mean that the culture down below changes and the homophobia goes away.

01:02:03.200 --> 01:02:06.840
[Amit Varma]: Whereas I would imagine if you're working in a company and you have rules that forbid

01:02:06.840 --> 01:02:10.680
[Amit Varma]: you from doing certain things, you will have to follow those rules, and you'll internalize

01:02:10.680 --> 01:02:12.840
[Amit Varma]: them and the culture will change a bit.

01:02:12.840 --> 01:02:18.400
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you're bringing in these sort of normalized attitude towards, you know,

01:02:18.400 --> 01:02:22.720
[Amit Varma]: certain kinds of people and those are not going to disappear, those will manifest in

01:02:22.720 --> 01:02:23.720
[Amit Varma]: other ways.

01:02:23.720 --> 01:02:27.260
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I know your thoughts on this are still evolving as you raise it as a question

01:02:27.260 --> 01:02:28.260
[Amit Varma]: in the book.

01:02:28.260 --> 01:02:33.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, can you tell me a little bit more about how you've thought on this?

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:38.480
[Amit Varma]: Have there been moments where you felt despair and said that, you know, even if, you know,

01:02:38.480 --> 01:02:41.320
[Amit Varma]: we do all this work, people are what they are?

01:02:41.320 --> 01:02:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Or are you generally hopeful?

01:02:43.080 --> 01:02:48.760
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, your book is full of such stories of hope and such stories of inclusion.

01:02:48.760 --> 01:02:49.760
[Guest]: What's your sort of overall take on this?

01:02:49.760 --> 01:02:50.760
[Guest]: No, no, I feel despair every day.

01:02:50.760 --> 01:02:55.960
[Guest]: Every day I fluctuate between hope and despair, hope and despair all the time.

01:02:55.960 --> 01:03:03.100
[Guest]: If I end on hope, 51% of the time and despair 49%, I'm fine.

01:03:03.100 --> 01:03:08.120
[Guest]: My thoughts on this are, I think what TechMindr did ultimately was very good.

01:03:08.120 --> 01:03:12.800
[Guest]: Because I think they role modeled what, you know, in that sense, in terms of when the

01:03:12.800 --> 01:03:18.000
[Guest]: issue comes out, how you respond, I thought the response was amazing.

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:25.760
[Guest]: And it also sent a strong message throughout, right, we will not tolerate this at all.

01:03:25.760 --> 01:03:30.280
[Guest]: And in fact, TechMindr has since then, in another part of the book, I talk about how

01:03:30.280 --> 01:03:34.480
[Guest]: they've launched, you know, same sex partnership benefits, and so many other things.

01:03:34.480 --> 01:03:38.120
[Guest]: So since then, they've gone on a great learning journey, which is great.

01:03:38.120 --> 01:03:42.480
[Guest]: So I'm, you know, was it good for the individual who went through this?

01:03:42.480 --> 01:03:43.480
[Guest]: Of course not.

01:03:43.480 --> 01:03:46.360
[Guest]: I mean, you know, he, I'm in touch with him.

01:03:46.360 --> 01:03:47.960
[Guest]: And he has still been traumatized with that.

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:49.640
[Guest]: And that is what I talk about in the chapter, right?

01:03:49.640 --> 01:03:51.660
[Guest]: I said, these are real people.

01:03:51.660 --> 01:03:56.200
[Guest]: Even if you take all the steps, after something has been found, you know, it's very, very

01:03:56.200 --> 01:03:57.200
[Guest]: hard, right?

01:03:57.200 --> 01:03:59.120
[Guest]: That person has suffered for all these years.

01:03:59.120 --> 01:04:04.440
[Guest]: I think this is only going to become less and less if companies role model this kind

01:04:04.440 --> 01:04:05.440
[Guest]: of behavior, right?

01:04:05.440 --> 01:04:10.240
[Guest]: So, I mean, I think it would be very naive to imagine that just because you have policies

01:04:10.240 --> 01:04:13.240
[Guest]: and you have senior people who say this is the kind of world we want to create, we're

01:04:13.240 --> 01:04:17.800
[Guest]: not going to have people, you know, who are going to be bigoted.

01:04:17.800 --> 01:04:19.960
[Guest]: But which is why then you need to act, right?

01:04:19.960 --> 01:04:23.760
[Guest]: You need to translate the intent of your policies into action.

01:04:23.760 --> 01:04:28.000
[Guest]: If you are saying we don't discriminate, and when someone discriminates, how do you act?

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.080
[Guest]: Because everyone else is watching, right?

01:04:30.080 --> 01:04:32.520
[Guest]: All the thousands of employees at Tech Mahindra were watching.

01:04:32.520 --> 01:04:34.920
[Guest]: They were like, discrimination happened.

01:04:34.920 --> 01:04:36.120
[Guest]: Look what happened.

01:04:36.120 --> 01:04:42.360
[Guest]: The CEO tweeted, Anand Mahindra tweeted, inquiry was made, that person was fired.

01:04:42.360 --> 01:04:43.360
[Guest]: Okay.

01:04:43.360 --> 01:04:46.400
[Guest]: Which means that rights matter here.

01:04:46.400 --> 01:04:50.560
[Guest]: Which means that tomorrow, if I have some issue that I go to them with, they will take

01:04:50.560 --> 01:04:51.560
[Guest]: me seriously.

01:04:51.560 --> 01:04:52.560
[Guest]: Right?

01:04:52.560 --> 01:04:53.560
[Guest]: And everyone else outside was also watching.

01:04:53.560 --> 01:04:57.460
[Guest]: They said, look, here's a company, mistakes happen everywhere.

01:04:57.460 --> 01:04:58.840
[Guest]: This thing has happened here.

01:04:58.840 --> 01:05:01.080
[Guest]: They've acted in this way.

01:05:01.080 --> 01:05:04.440
[Guest]: So I think it's how you behave at these moments also that matters.

01:05:04.440 --> 01:05:09.880
[Guest]: I mean, you can role model more and more of this thing that we have a zero tolerance policy.

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:12.360
[Guest]: You know, it's very clear how we expect you to behave.

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:16.160
[Guest]: And I've given so many other, there's been so many other cases as well in the book, right?

01:05:16.160 --> 01:05:21.000
[Guest]: I talk about say maybe a community business where Sandeep goes through and Sandeep has

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:27.960
[Guest]: a boss who's like, who makes a joke about, you know, when Sandeep says, I'm getting married

01:05:27.960 --> 01:05:33.720
[Guest]: to my partner, this, you know, the insensitive boss says, why are you, you know, number nine

01:05:33.720 --> 01:05:34.720
[Guest]: or something?

01:05:34.720 --> 01:05:38.480
[Guest]: And then like, Sandeep raises the complaint.

01:05:38.480 --> 01:05:40.200
[Guest]: Now this was a comment.

01:05:40.200 --> 01:05:45.160
[Guest]: And then the company here sends that boss for sensitivity training.

01:05:45.160 --> 01:05:48.960
[Guest]: And you know, the boss comes back and says, I'm sorry, I, you know, I made that comment.

01:05:48.960 --> 01:05:50.480
[Guest]: I didn't realize.

01:05:50.480 --> 01:05:52.120
[Guest]: And they go through that sensitivity training, right?

01:05:52.120 --> 01:05:55.880
[Guest]: So there's, I think it's important to respond at this time, right?

01:05:55.880 --> 01:06:01.080
[Guest]: And to say that as an organization, we are setting these policies, we are investing in

01:06:01.080 --> 01:06:04.000
[Guest]: the in a culture of training our employees.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:08.080
[Guest]: And if mistakes happen, here is how we are going to act on them.

01:06:08.080 --> 01:06:13.360
[Guest]: I think the more and more you role model this good behavior, the less you have chances of

01:06:13.360 --> 01:06:15.560
[Guest]: these incidents happening.

01:06:15.560 --> 01:06:18.800
[Guest]: Another interesting case study is Kochi Metro, right?

01:06:18.800 --> 01:06:24.280
[Guest]: Which is not about discrimination, but about the fact that, you know, this is an evolving

01:06:24.280 --> 01:06:25.280
[Guest]: journey.

01:06:25.280 --> 01:06:30.920
[Guest]: So Kochi Metro takes a great step of saying we want to increase, we want to hire trans

01:06:30.920 --> 01:06:33.440
[Guest]: people, which is incredible.

01:06:33.440 --> 01:06:38.960
[Guest]: A lot of trans people are hired, but then many of them leave, not because Kochi Metro

01:06:38.960 --> 01:06:45.280
[Guest]: is necessarily a discriminating organization, but because they're unable to find houses,

01:06:45.280 --> 01:06:48.040
[Guest]: because people don't want to rent, you know, homes to trans people.

01:06:48.040 --> 01:06:52.600
[Guest]: And so it's very hard for them to like to arrive at work, to stay close to office and

01:06:52.600 --> 01:06:53.960
[Guest]: to arrive at work, etc, right?

01:06:53.960 --> 01:06:58.840
[Guest]: So as I write in the book, organizations have to think through some of these things.

01:06:58.840 --> 01:07:02.040
[Guest]: Now Kochi Metro understood, relearned.

01:07:02.040 --> 01:07:06.840
[Guest]: And I believe right now when it hires trans people, it goes a little extra mile in helping

01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:11.640
[Guest]: them either as a guarantee in terms of, you know, when they're looking for houses in terms

01:07:11.640 --> 01:07:15.520
[Guest]: of landlords and saying, we will serve as a guarantor or so on, but going that extra

01:07:15.520 --> 01:07:16.520
[Guest]: mile.

01:07:16.520 --> 01:07:17.520
[Guest]: So I think this is iterative.

01:07:17.520 --> 01:07:24.000
[Guest]: There's enough examples also to show of how companies and, you know, Kochi Metro is not

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:29.800
[Guest]: a company, it's a state organization, are learning on the way, and learning how to,

01:07:29.800 --> 01:07:33.200
[Guest]: you know, act decently and to be good.

01:07:33.200 --> 01:07:34.960
[Guest]: So that gives me hope.

01:07:34.960 --> 01:07:35.960
[Guest]: In that sense.

01:07:35.960 --> 01:07:40.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, in your book, there's also the great example of the Lalit and, you know, how they

01:07:40.240 --> 01:07:43.080
[Amit Varma]: have a policy of sort of hiring more and more trans employees.

01:07:43.080 --> 01:07:46.960
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, I mean, that, you know, one of the lessons perhaps from the book is that how

01:07:46.960 --> 01:07:53.720
[Amit Varma]: incentives can also sort of shape culture, you know, as I keep saying in my economist

01:07:53.720 --> 01:07:56.360
[Amit Varma]: jargony way, we'll take a quick commercial break now.

