[Amit Varma]: prologue or, you know, the start of your book was when you know, you point out how your

01:09:49.360 --> 01:09:53.320
[Amit Varma]: dad got to know of your being gay through the BBC.

01:09:53.320 --> 01:09:54.320
[Amit Varma]: That was pretty fascinating.

01:09:54.320 --> 01:09:59.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that and how did he react and how did your parents kind of sort of deal

01:09:59.440 --> 01:10:00.440
[Amit Varma]: with it?

01:10:00.440 --> 01:10:08.960
[Guest]: Yeah, so it was, I was at MIT, I had just organized a big South Asian LGBTQ film festival

01:10:08.960 --> 01:10:09.960
[Guest]: over there.

01:10:09.960 --> 01:10:14.800
[Guest]: It was very hard because in the middle of my, you know, academic semester, I thought

01:10:14.800 --> 01:10:16.600
[Guest]: he one must do this.

01:10:16.600 --> 01:10:22.160
[Guest]: And so it was the first time that something like this was happening on the East Coast,

01:10:22.160 --> 01:10:28.480
[Guest]: on the West Coast, there was, say, Tricorne and a lot of, you know, queer stuff happening.

01:10:28.480 --> 01:10:32.640
[Guest]: But you know, Boston had Masala, which was a South Asian LGBTQ organization, but they'd

01:10:32.640 --> 01:10:36.920
[Guest]: never really, and you know, New York had Salga and all, but they never attempted something

01:10:36.920 --> 01:10:40.360
[Guest]: like, you know, like a queer festival of this nature before.

01:10:40.360 --> 01:10:42.760
[Guest]: So it was newsworthy.

01:10:42.760 --> 01:10:47.320
[Guest]: And a BBC journalist called me and they asked, they talked to us, talked to me about it.

01:10:47.320 --> 01:10:49.880
[Guest]: And I happily gave the interview.

01:10:49.880 --> 01:10:56.920
[Guest]: And the BBC chose to put it up on their front page, on their homepage, when the interview

01:10:56.920 --> 01:10:57.920
[Guest]: ran.

01:10:57.920 --> 01:11:01.520
[Guest]: And it was interesting because the top story was Parvez Musharraf and Parvez Musharraf's

01:11:01.520 --> 01:11:06.320
[Guest]: picture, who at that time was first president of Pakistan.

01:11:06.320 --> 01:11:12.440
[Guest]: And then below that was this article with my photo saying South Asian gays find US voice.

01:11:12.440 --> 01:11:18.040
[Guest]: And it was very interesting because, you know, I started getting calls from people all around

01:11:18.040 --> 01:11:25.160
[Guest]: the world saying, you know, BBC is saying that you're gay and you're doing all of this.

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:27.040
[Guest]: And my cousin actually called me for a moment.

01:11:27.040 --> 01:11:31.720
[Guest]: She's like, listen, because I hadn't, I was out to my mom, but I wasn't out to my dad

01:11:31.720 --> 01:11:33.240
[Guest]: at that time.

01:11:33.240 --> 01:11:39.320
[Guest]: And so, yeah, so she was like, you know, it's not going to be fun if someone forwards this

01:11:39.320 --> 01:11:40.320
[Guest]: to your dad.

01:11:40.320 --> 01:11:42.280
[Guest]: I think you should call him.

01:11:42.280 --> 01:11:45.080
[Guest]: So I called him and I had to tell him, I had to tell him a bunch of things.

01:11:45.080 --> 01:11:50.160
[Guest]: I said, look, I'm gay and the whole world knows about it because the BBC did a story.

01:11:50.160 --> 01:11:58.040
[Guest]: So, and, you know, the BBC is right, at least in those days it used to be right.

01:11:58.040 --> 01:12:00.000
[Guest]: It was known for its accuracy.

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:01.000
[Guest]: Even now, I suppose.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:04.440
[Guest]: So it's like, you know, it's on the BBC, it's true.

01:12:04.440 --> 01:12:08.160
[Guest]: And he had to react at that, right?

01:12:08.160 --> 01:12:12.880
[Guest]: So not only did he have to deal with the fact that his son was gay, he had to deal with

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:15.640
[Guest]: the fact that it was now a world story.

01:12:15.640 --> 01:12:21.600
[Guest]: Given that, I think he was, it took him some time because he reacted more like a typical

01:12:21.600 --> 01:12:27.520
[Guest]: Indian parent than my mom, because he was like, oh, what will the world, as the world

01:12:27.520 --> 01:12:29.080
[Guest]: knows now already, no, darling?

01:12:29.080 --> 01:12:31.880
[Guest]: He was like, oh, I wanted grandchildren.

01:12:31.880 --> 01:12:35.560
[Guest]: I was like, we can get grandchildren, we can get grandchildren, don't worry.

01:12:35.560 --> 01:12:37.240
[Guest]: Like, yeah, I thought you would get married.

01:12:37.240 --> 01:12:38.520
[Guest]: I was like, we'll get married.

01:12:38.520 --> 01:12:39.520
[Guest]: Just be a guy.

01:12:39.520 --> 01:12:42.760
[Guest]: He was like, that's not what I had in mind.

01:12:42.760 --> 01:12:45.760
[Guest]: Life is sometimes like that.

01:12:45.760 --> 01:12:48.840
[Guest]: And over time, he has accepted.

01:12:48.840 --> 01:12:54.000
[Guest]: Now with Queeristan out, he forwards me articles that he's read about it.

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:58.000
[Guest]: And he's like, I saw your show with Faye D'Souza, you spoke well, or things like that, right?

01:12:58.000 --> 01:12:59.000
[Guest]: So it's been a journey.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.000
[Guest]: With my mom, it was immediate.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:06.180
[Guest]: It was kind of underwhelming, because I told my mom, mom, I think I'm gay.

01:13:06.180 --> 01:13:09.120
[Guest]: And she was like, you think or you're sure?

01:13:09.120 --> 01:13:10.120
[Guest]: And I was like, I'm sure I'm gay.

01:13:10.120 --> 01:13:12.960
[Guest]: And she was like, okay, what should we have for dinner?

01:13:12.960 --> 01:13:15.640
[Guest]: And that was really the conversation with her.

01:13:15.640 --> 01:13:22.080
[Guest]: And I kind of felt cheated, because I had made all these like, you know, but you don't

01:13:22.080 --> 01:13:26.600
[Guest]: understand but this, but that I made all these dialogues in my head, which I couldn't use.

01:13:26.600 --> 01:13:28.960
[Guest]: And then I told her, I said, why aren't you having any drama?

01:13:28.960 --> 01:13:34.160
[Guest]: And she was like, you know, I don't, what is there to have drama?

01:13:34.160 --> 01:13:40.400
[Guest]: But she was like, refreshingly cool about it.

01:13:40.400 --> 01:13:43.400
[Unknown]: Who took out the chickpeas from the cooker?

01:13:43.400 --> 01:13:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, if they're listening to this, hello, uncle and auntie.

01:13:47.520 --> 01:13:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of now move on, you're at MIT, you've you've even set up a sort of a kind

01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:57.720
[Amit Varma]: of a forum there, you're, you know, you're considering, you know, helping to run that

01:13:57.720 --> 01:13:58.880
[Amit Varma]: while you're there.

01:13:58.880 --> 01:14:02.200
[Amit Varma]: And then you decide to come back to India and join the corporate life.

01:14:02.200 --> 01:14:06.160
[Guest]: So how did that sort of shift, that was all because of, you know, Shahrukh Khan, I think

01:14:06.160 --> 01:14:07.160
[Guest]: has ruined my life.

01:14:07.160 --> 01:14:15.240
[Guest]: First with those ideas of love, romance, I'm also doing, you know, arms ahead and Yash

01:14:15.240 --> 01:14:20.200
[Guest]: Chopra first, because of you know, Chandni and that rooftop helicopter rose petals, I

01:14:20.200 --> 01:14:24.240
[Guest]: began to think, I also want like that only.

01:14:24.240 --> 01:14:30.480
[Guest]: These days, if the husband smiles at me after waking up, I feel happy.

01:14:30.480 --> 01:14:33.800
[Guest]: My ideas of romance and know everything.

01:14:33.800 --> 01:14:38.320
[Guest]: I mean, I think Bollywood, I'm super Bollywood influenced.

01:14:38.320 --> 01:14:42.960
[Guest]: So multiple things, actually, it's, I saw Swades, I think a lot of people who came back

01:14:42.960 --> 01:14:48.800
[Guest]: at that time, you know, Shahrukh, Ashutosh, we could have been living nicely in Seattle.

01:14:48.800 --> 01:14:56.600
[Guest]: You made us come back, I would have had a nice house with a picket fence.

01:14:56.600 --> 01:15:00.680
[Guest]: And maybe like, you know, an exotic foreign husband.

01:15:00.680 --> 01:15:07.000
[Guest]: No, I saw Swades, it was a bunch of things that had happened, I'd seen, I'd finished

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:13.040
[Guest]: my thesis, I was very tired, I was working on this, you know, MIT think tank that I'd

01:15:13.040 --> 01:15:17.880
[Guest]: set up with Henry Jenkins, my professor, I was enjoying that.

01:15:17.880 --> 01:15:25.360
[Guest]: I was interviewing, because I did want to, you know, stay back my I was, I was in a relationship,

01:15:25.360 --> 01:15:28.320
[Guest]: I was in a committed relationship.

01:15:28.320 --> 01:15:31.240
[Guest]: And my partner at that time was finishing his PhD at MIT.

01:15:31.240 --> 01:15:33.600
[Guest]: So I did want to stay on in America.

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:38.880
[Guest]: But the kind of job offers I was getting were from Microsoft, and they were very nice.

01:15:38.880 --> 01:15:44.600
[Guest]: But you know, I'd studied as a media, I mean, I studied as a humanist, and, you know, and

01:15:44.600 --> 01:15:50.680
[Guest]: the kind of offers I was getting were to help market Windows, and things like that.

01:15:50.680 --> 01:15:52.120
[Guest]: And it was very good money.

01:15:52.120 --> 01:15:57.800
[Guest]: But I kind of didn't see how my background and my humanities training would be of any

01:15:57.800 --> 01:16:00.200
[Guest]: use there.

01:16:00.200 --> 01:16:03.640
[Guest]: So I was thinking these things through.

01:16:03.640 --> 01:16:07.240
[Guest]: And then a bunch of things happened, you know, I saw Swades, and I was like, No, no, no,

01:16:07.240 --> 01:16:13.360
[Guest]: I think I should use this, I should come back to India and see what I can do with these

01:16:13.360 --> 01:16:15.960
[Guest]: different things that one has learned.

01:16:15.960 --> 01:16:19.880
[Guest]: And I then happened to meet say, Anand and Anuradha in Boston who were visiting and they

01:16:19.880 --> 01:16:25.160
[Guest]: were like, you know, listen, now that you're done or whatever, if you want to come and

01:16:25.160 --> 01:16:29.280
[Guest]: work, come and work at Mahindra, there's lots that one can do.

01:16:29.280 --> 01:16:34.280
[Guest]: So it was a combination of both of those things, the fact that there was a blank kind of canvas

01:16:34.280 --> 01:16:36.720
[Guest]: waiting for me at Mahindra.

01:16:36.720 --> 01:16:41.480
[Guest]: But plus, I'd seen Swades, I think if I'd had that conversation without seeing Swades,

01:16:41.480 --> 01:16:43.000
[Guest]: I would have said, yeah, yeah, fine, fine.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:45.000
[Guest]: But you know, I want to be here only.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:52.480
[Guest]: If I'd seen Swades and not met them, then I mean, there was, there was the opportunity.

01:16:52.480 --> 01:16:53.480
[Guest]: So I think it was everything.

01:16:53.480 --> 01:17:02.960
[Guest]: There are days when I'm grateful I came back, there are days when I feel like I could have

01:17:02.960 --> 01:17:12.240
[Guest]: been a nice foreign NRI gay person coming once every year or whatever, for weddings.

01:17:12.240 --> 01:17:16.040
[Guest]: And I'm like, okay, whatever happened, happened.

01:17:16.040 --> 01:17:17.040
[Guest]: Now I'm here.

01:17:17.040 --> 01:17:21.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's interesting that you should ascribe so much credit to Shah Rukh Khan because,

01:17:21.480 --> 01:17:25.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, one of the quotes I really liked in your book was about how your friend Ian,

01:17:25.480 --> 01:17:32.360
[Amit Varma]: Sir Ian to the rest of us, Sir Ian McKellen says that, you know, once he came out as gay,

01:17:32.360 --> 01:17:37.720
[Amit Varma]: the nature of his acting changed, where, you know, you quote him telling you that, you

01:17:37.720 --> 01:17:41.600
[Amit Varma]: know, coming out was such a relief on all accounts, everything improved, including my

01:17:41.600 --> 01:17:42.600
[Amit Varma]: acting.

01:17:42.600 --> 01:17:45.400
[Amit Varma]: Up until then, my acting was about disguising.

01:17:45.400 --> 01:17:48.520
[Amit Varma]: After I came out, it became about revelation.

01:17:48.520 --> 01:17:49.520
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:17:49.520 --> 01:17:50.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's such a beautiful quote.

01:17:50.520 --> 01:17:55.160
[Amit Varma]: And it just made me sort of stop and think about it for a while before I continued reading.

01:17:55.160 --> 01:17:59.520
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that Shah Rukh Khan's acting is just all performative as Bollywood has

01:17:59.520 --> 01:18:01.860
[Amit Varma]: to be and not about revelation at all.

01:18:01.860 --> 01:18:07.560
[Amit Varma]: But that sort of aside apart, you also point out in your book about how sort of Ted India

01:18:07.560 --> 01:18:14.040
[Amit Varma]: 2009, where, by the way, just to kind of tell our listeners, you know, Ted had their first

01:18:14.040 --> 01:18:18.080
[Amit Varma]: conference in India, the only conference in India in 2009.

01:18:18.080 --> 01:18:23.560
[Amit Varma]: And they selected a bunch of India fellows for that, which included, you know, Parmesh

01:18:23.560 --> 01:18:27.640
[Amit Varma]: and me and, you know, various people you've named, like, you named Jasmeen Patheja of

01:18:27.640 --> 01:18:31.320
[Amit Varma]: Blank Noise, who's done such incredible, innovative work.

01:18:31.320 --> 01:18:36.080
[Amit Varma]: And so the bunch of us were all brought together in Mysore for this great TED conference.

01:18:36.080 --> 01:18:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And even that, that Mysore at Infosys campus was crazy, because I think it was made by

01:18:39.880 --> 01:18:40.880
[Amit Varma]: Hercules Contractor.

01:18:40.880 --> 01:18:47.440
[Guest]: It was surreal because all the buildings were based on famous buildings.

01:18:47.440 --> 01:18:51.240
[Amit Varma]: So somewhere there were the White House, somewhere there was a Capitol, somewhere there was the

01:18:51.240 --> 01:18:53.080
[Amit Varma]: Parthenon and whatever.

01:18:53.080 --> 01:18:58.320
[Amit Varma]: And it was completely surreal, but also in a sense, perhaps an apt place to gather like

01:18:58.320 --> 01:19:01.680
[Amit Varma]: this because it was this vast global gathering.

01:19:01.680 --> 01:19:05.420
[Amit Varma]: But you know, for me, it was just an event where I go, I watch some great talks, which

01:19:05.420 --> 01:19:11.320
[Amit Varma]: I could even have watched on YouTube, you know, and, you know, get to meet, get to hang

01:19:11.320 --> 01:19:13.440
[Amit Varma]: out with cool people like you.

01:19:13.440 --> 01:19:18.640
[Amit Varma]: But you've spoken about how it then, you know, gave you an impetus to do some of what you

01:19:18.640 --> 01:19:22.520
[Amit Varma]: did next, especially later with the Godrej Culture Lab, tell me a little bit about that.

01:19:22.520 --> 01:19:23.520
[Guest]: I will.

01:19:23.520 --> 01:19:28.000
[Guest]: But before that, I want to dispute the fact that Shah Rukh's acting is all performative

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:30.000
[Guest]: and not about revelation.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:38.040
[Guest]: As an avowed Shah Rukh fan, I would like to humbly disagree.

01:19:38.040 --> 01:19:44.160
[Guest]: I think if you have seen Raees, if you have seen Zero, which I loved, I thought it was

01:19:44.160 --> 01:19:45.320
[Guest]: one of his best films.

01:19:45.320 --> 01:19:48.320
[Guest]: If you've seen Fan, which was incredible.

01:19:48.320 --> 01:19:53.360
[Guest]: If you have seen Paheli, if you've seen Kabhi Haan Kabhi Na, if you've seen Chakde, if you've

01:19:53.360 --> 01:19:57.880
[Guest]: seen The Ranger, if you've seen Swades, for that matter, you know, or Raju, or, you know,

01:19:57.880 --> 01:20:04.440
[Guest]: if you see the range of films that Shah Rukh has done, they are so much about revelation.

01:20:04.440 --> 01:20:08.680
[Guest]: I think one of the highlights of Shah Rukh is that he makes you feel that you are taking

01:20:08.680 --> 01:20:10.300
[Guest]: a piece of him.

01:20:10.300 --> 01:20:12.920
[Guest]: He genuinely gives that to you as well.

01:20:12.920 --> 01:20:19.920
[Guest]: So I would urge you to relook Shah Rukh with a more loving gaze and discover the joy of

01:20:19.920 --> 01:20:22.320
[Guest]: Shah Rukh, if you can.

01:20:22.320 --> 01:20:26.160
[Amit Varma]: He gives you the same piece of him in every film, but we'll agree to disagree for the

01:20:26.160 --> 01:20:33.560
[Amit Varma]: sake of amity and sort of continue with our conversation.

01:20:33.560 --> 01:20:34.560
[Guest]: Tell me about TED India.

01:20:34.560 --> 01:20:35.560
[Guest]: So sure.

01:20:35.560 --> 01:20:38.680
[Guest]: So Shah Rukh incidentally also gave a great TED talk in Vancouver.

01:20:38.680 --> 01:20:41.920
[Guest]: And I must tell you that at that same TED conference, which I happened to be there at

01:20:41.920 --> 01:20:48.200
[Guest]: Vancouver, you know, there was Elon Musk hanging around on the side, no one cared much.

01:20:48.200 --> 01:20:54.800
[Guest]: There was Al Gore was standing behind me in the buffet line, eating very quietly.

01:20:54.800 --> 01:20:56.960
[Guest]: No one got any, you know, whatever.

01:20:56.960 --> 01:21:01.400
[Guest]: But for Shah Rukh, the moment the door opened, the moment, whatever, there were like thousands

01:21:01.400 --> 01:21:08.400
[Guest]: of people waiting in Vancouver, screaming their heads out.

01:21:08.400 --> 01:21:10.720
[Guest]: So you know, Shah Rukh is Shah Rukh.

01:21:10.720 --> 01:21:14.560
[Amit Varma]: I just say that, look, popularity is not a sign of quality.

01:21:14.560 --> 01:21:15.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, look at Modiji.

01:21:15.920 --> 01:21:24.760
[Guest]: As a fan, as a Shah Rukh fan, as an avowed Shah Rukh fan, as a connoisseur of Shah Rukh

01:21:24.760 --> 01:21:28.680
[Guest]: acting and revelation, sometimes you can have it all.

01:21:28.680 --> 01:21:29.680
[Guest]: You can have...

01:21:29.680 --> 01:21:37.840
[Amit Varma]: My God, you know, I had a similar conversation with Parumita Hora, she was on my show and

01:21:37.840 --> 01:21:39.320
[Amit Varma]: she's also a Shah Rukh fan.

01:21:39.320 --> 01:21:41.680
[Amit Varma]: So maybe you guys will make me reconsider.

01:21:41.680 --> 01:21:48.320
[Amit Varma]: I don't think so, but it's kind of, I'll have to let you have the last word on this as we

01:21:48.320 --> 01:21:49.320
[Guest]: kind of move ahead.

01:21:49.320 --> 01:21:51.760
[Guest]: Okay, I can see you want to move ahead from talking.

01:21:51.760 --> 01:21:53.360
[Guest]: Shah Rukh, we love you.

01:21:53.360 --> 01:21:54.360
[Guest]: Okay.

01:21:54.360 --> 01:21:59.560
[Guest]: Having said that, yes, TED India being selected as a TED India fellow, and I would say off

01:21:59.560 --> 01:22:05.720
[Guest]: late being a TED senior fellow, because I've just finished that stint has been quite transformative.

01:22:05.720 --> 01:22:10.840
[Guest]: I mean, in 2009, TED was not this great global juggernaut.

01:22:10.840 --> 01:22:14.400
[Guest]: You know, TED has just started putting up talks online.

01:22:14.400 --> 01:22:17.560
[Guest]: And if you see some of these early talks, it's like, you know, it's not the kind of

01:22:17.560 --> 01:22:22.800
[Guest]: highly produced TED talk, which has now almost become a meme, like, oh, you gave a TED talk,

01:22:22.800 --> 01:22:27.280
[Guest]: okay, you're uncool, you know, that kind of thing hasn't come, that kind of, you know,

01:22:27.280 --> 01:22:30.840
[Guest]: in those days, it was very, very early, it was very, very new.

01:22:30.840 --> 01:22:36.560
[Guest]: And this whole format, which Chris and the team have like, you know, taken to such incredible

01:22:36.560 --> 01:22:41.080
[Guest]: different directions over the years, was just about being, you know, coming into its own,

01:22:41.080 --> 01:22:42.080
[Guest]: right.

01:22:42.080 --> 01:22:46.720
[Guest]: So for me, being a TED was like a brain popping experience.

01:22:46.720 --> 01:22:52.360
[Guest]: It transformed my life in so many ways, because at that time, I had agreed to, I had gone

01:22:52.360 --> 01:22:57.800
[Guest]: back to America, I'd left the Mahindra job, I'd started a PhD at UPenn.

01:22:57.800 --> 01:23:03.360
[Guest]: And I'd chosen to go back to digging deep again, I'd spent some years and, and my life

01:23:03.360 --> 01:23:08.840
[Guest]: has been this constant tension between do I dig deep, or do I spread wide, you know.

01:23:08.840 --> 01:23:12.760
[Guest]: And for those who are listening to the podcast, Amit is grinning right now.

01:23:12.760 --> 01:23:15.920
[Guest]: No, it's not what you're thinking about Amit.

01:23:15.920 --> 01:23:18.640
[Guest]: I wasn't grinning and I wasn't thinking that at all.

01:23:18.640 --> 01:23:19.640
[Guest]: Naughty boy.

01:23:19.640 --> 01:23:21.240
[Guest]: I was talking about my career.

01:23:21.240 --> 01:23:24.680
[Guest]: So, you know, at that time, I had gone back to the PhD.

01:23:24.680 --> 01:23:31.840
[Guest]: And I had said, you know, I want to spend some years and working on, on academic research.

01:23:31.840 --> 01:23:35.480
[Guest]: But then I came to this, you know, then I got selected for the TED India Fellowship,

01:23:35.480 --> 01:23:37.360
[Guest]: and then I flew back.

01:23:37.360 --> 01:23:46.400
[Guest]: And to have a space where you could have science, humanities, medicine, people from NGOs, spirituality,

01:23:46.400 --> 01:23:54.160
[Guest]: love, romance, dance, music, everything kind of come together fatafat one after the other

01:23:54.160 --> 01:24:01.280
[Guest]: in this like, you know, bhel puri mix of like a brain massage, kind of, yeah, for me, I'd

01:24:01.280 --> 01:24:04.200
[Guest]: never seen anything like it.

01:24:04.200 --> 01:24:06.400
[Guest]: Just being there, witnessing it all.

01:24:06.400 --> 01:24:12.560
[Guest]: And then witnessing all of us, right, seeing all these amazing TED India fellows, so many

01:24:12.560 --> 01:24:16.000
[Guest]: of whom I've like, tracked with admiration over the years, right?

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:23.080
[Guest]: Someone like a Rikim Gandhi, who was my classmate, who was also with me at MIT, who then, who

01:24:23.080 --> 01:24:28.640
[Guest]: was training to become, you know, training for NASA, who then left and formed an organization

01:24:28.640 --> 01:24:34.600
[Guest]: called Digital Green, which works with farmers in rural India, giving them information and,

01:24:34.600 --> 01:24:39.880
[Guest]: you know, technology access and things like that, to young schoolmasters like Babar Ali,

01:24:39.880 --> 01:24:46.360
[Guest]: who, despite coming from such, you know, underprivileged backgrounds, were creating education alternatives

01:24:46.360 --> 01:24:54.200
[Guest]: for so many children in their village in Bengal, to say, you know, artists like Sharmishta,

01:24:54.200 --> 01:24:58.400
[Guest]: to like, you know, I mean, so just like, really, really, really, so it was both the conference

01:24:58.400 --> 01:25:03.640
[Guest]: format that I was like, wow, you can have this kind of space to the people I was like,

01:25:03.640 --> 01:25:08.400
[Guest]: you know, I read there are so many cool people in India, all of whom are doing such amazing

01:25:08.400 --> 01:25:09.400
[Guest]: work.

01:25:09.400 --> 01:25:13.440
[Guest]: I mean, so it I was like, I don't want to go back and like, spend six years and doing

01:25:13.440 --> 01:25:14.960
[Guest]: this PhD.

01:25:14.960 --> 01:25:18.680
[Guest]: I want to do something TED like, and that was the idea.

01:25:18.680 --> 01:25:21.800
[Guest]: Now I didn't want to do TED India, I didn't want to do a three day conference.

01:25:21.800 --> 01:25:27.760
[Guest]: But I was like, now what I want to do is I want to live in this state of TEDness of any

01:25:27.760 --> 01:25:35.560
[Guest]: given day, I want to be mixing science, design, arts, policy, I want to like, you know, create

01:25:35.560 --> 01:25:37.920
[Guest]: this space in India.

01:25:37.920 --> 01:25:42.640
[Guest]: And what would it mean like to have this broad space like think.

01:25:42.640 --> 01:25:45.680
[Guest]: So that was the, that was my idea.

01:25:45.680 --> 01:25:50.440
[Guest]: I went back, I dropped out of the PhD program, which they didn't like, of course, because

01:25:50.440 --> 01:25:51.840
[Guest]: you know, I had filled a seat.

01:25:51.840 --> 01:25:53.840
[Guest]: And now suddenly I was dropping out.

01:25:53.840 --> 01:25:57.160
[Guest]: And so they said, Look, we love you, but don't ever come back here again.

01:25:57.160 --> 01:26:01.600
[Guest]: And of course, me being the drama queen said, who wants to come back to you, pen, X, never

01:26:01.600 --> 01:26:06.320
[Guest]: I'll go anywhere but except to you all and you know, we had that kind of showdown.

01:26:06.320 --> 01:26:10.360
[Guest]: And then I came back and then I started saying, Okay, now what to do?

01:26:10.360 --> 01:26:11.980
[Guest]: How do I create the space?

01:26:11.980 --> 01:26:17.520
[Guest]: And so I started talking to people, people from Mahindra, people, you know, I've encountered

01:26:17.520 --> 01:26:25.840
[Guest]: people from the media, and randomly, one of Sandeep Murthy, who's an investor, who runs

01:26:25.840 --> 01:26:30.840
[Guest]: Lightbox, which is one of the most exciting venture funds in India right now.

01:26:30.840 --> 01:26:36.160
[Guest]: At that time, he was running Sharipalo and Ram Shriram's fund and Kleiner Perkins, etc.

01:26:36.160 --> 01:26:39.200
[Guest]: And he was like, you know, you should meet Nisa.

01:26:39.200 --> 01:26:43.880
[Guest]: I think she'll get you and y'all are both kind of mad and maybe y'all will hit it off.

01:26:43.880 --> 01:26:44.880
[Guest]: And that was that.

01:26:44.880 --> 01:26:50.200
[Guest]: And that's how I met Nisa, we met, we realized that we both, you know, we're very different

01:26:50.200 --> 01:26:51.200
[Guest]: people.

01:26:51.200 --> 01:26:55.520
[Guest]: But we connected on so many things we connected on design thinking on IDEO.

01:26:55.520 --> 01:26:59.200
[Guest]: She wanted to know more about LGBTQ issues and my life.

01:26:59.200 --> 01:27:03.000
[Guest]: And we just, we just started talking and she's like, Look, I don't know what your idea is.

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:06.080
[Guest]: I still don't understand what does it mean to create the space and blah, blah, blah.

01:27:06.080 --> 01:27:08.160
[Guest]: But she's like, I like you.

01:27:08.160 --> 01:27:10.400
[Guest]: So do you want to work at Godrej?

01:27:10.400 --> 01:27:13.400
[Guest]: I was like, Godrej?

01:27:13.400 --> 01:27:15.600
[Guest]: No, I mean, I want to do this.

01:27:15.600 --> 01:27:18.280
[Guest]: She's like, Why don't you work here?

01:27:18.280 --> 01:27:22.640
[Guest]: And you know, if you help me with other things, I'll let you do your idea.

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:29.240
[Guest]: And I was like, okay, that's and 10 years later, we're still here.

01:27:29.240 --> 01:27:35.960
[Guest]: They're still arguing and talking and pushing each other and laughing and imagining.

01:27:35.960 --> 01:27:36.960
[Guest]: And it's been amazing.

01:27:36.960 --> 01:27:38.240
[Guest]: Yeah, it's been amazing.

01:27:38.240 --> 01:27:39.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:27:39.240 --> 01:27:42.840
[Amit Varma]: And what was your conception of the Culture Lab when you started it?

01:27:42.840 --> 01:27:45.640
[Amit Varma]: What did you want it to be at that early stage?

01:27:45.640 --> 01:27:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And how has it then evolved?

01:27:47.280 --> 01:27:48.280
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:27:48.280 --> 01:27:53.880
[Guest]: So my original conception was very, I mean, you know, since I've been at a place like

01:27:53.880 --> 01:27:58.880
[Guest]: MIT, it was a mixture of like, an institution, which is how the old world things of things,

01:27:58.880 --> 01:27:59.880
[Guest]: right?

01:27:59.880 --> 01:28:03.360
[Guest]: So first, I said, maybe it should be a building with people.

01:28:03.360 --> 01:28:09.160
[Guest]: And you know, like, like a building, because our model for spaces that I had seen were

01:28:09.160 --> 01:28:13.920
[Guest]: like, cultural centers, like you have to have a building and office and all.

01:28:13.920 --> 01:28:16.120
[Guest]: But then the MIT thinking started to kick in.

01:28:16.120 --> 01:28:20.440
[Guest]: And I was like, you know, why does it need a space and this and also, I mean, Nisa didn't

01:28:20.440 --> 01:28:21.440
[Guest]: give me much money.

01:28:21.440 --> 01:28:26.880
[Guest]: She was like, you have one desk in this corner and like, you know, here's a little bit of

01:28:26.880 --> 01:28:27.880
[Guest]: money.

01:28:27.880 --> 01:28:30.920
[Guest]: One can do maybe one could have done one event or two events with that money.

01:28:30.920 --> 01:28:36.320
[Guest]: It was like, clearly, this is not the kind of thing where we will have buildings and

01:28:36.320 --> 01:28:39.280
[Guest]: large amounts of people and like things like that.

01:28:39.280 --> 01:28:41.780
[Guest]: So it can't be like a university center.

01:28:41.780 --> 01:28:48.520
[Guest]: It has to be something which is shape shifting, which is packable, and you can take it anywhere.

01:28:48.520 --> 01:28:55.280
[Guest]: And so I mean, because of the nature and the frugality and you know, these challenges,

01:28:55.280 --> 01:28:59.240
[Guest]: I think we kind of evolved a new kind of space.

01:28:59.240 --> 01:29:01.680
[Guest]: So a lab could be an idea space.

01:29:01.680 --> 01:29:07.240
[Guest]: So we started and I remember that I read something that in a paper that you know, my mentor Henry

01:29:07.240 --> 01:29:12.200
[Guest]: Jenkins and my MIT classmate Sam Ford had written about surplus audiences.

01:29:12.200 --> 01:29:18.440
[Guest]: And they've done a great white paper on wrestling fans on professional wrestling fans.

01:29:18.440 --> 01:29:22.840
[Guest]: And they said that, you know, we have to look at this idea of surplus, right?

01:29:22.840 --> 01:29:28.480
[Guest]: So WWE, this professional wrestling, when they tend to think of who their audience is,

01:29:28.480 --> 01:29:34.020
[Guest]: they used to think earlier that their audience would be 18 to 35 white male, whatever.

01:29:34.020 --> 01:29:37.480
[Guest]: But as they did research, they realized, I mean, what is professional wrestling like

01:29:37.480 --> 01:29:44.800
[Guest]: it's naked men, naked sweaty men in a ring, doing very highly and you know, WWE, it's

01:29:44.800 --> 01:29:48.120
[Guest]: all kind of larger than life performance.

01:29:48.120 --> 01:29:49.120
[Guest]: So who likes seeing this?

01:29:49.120 --> 01:29:51.960
[Guest]: They said, you know, a lot of women were seeing this.

01:29:51.960 --> 01:29:56.160
[Guest]: Some women like seeing naked men throwing themselves against each other and jumping

01:29:56.160 --> 01:29:57.160
[Guest]: like that.

01:29:57.160 --> 01:30:02.480
[Guest]: So we have not thought of women as our audience, but like, you know, that's a surplus audience.

01:30:02.480 --> 01:30:04.280
[Guest]: And they looked and they said, who else likes seeing this?

01:30:04.280 --> 01:30:08.400
[Guest]: It's like, you know, gay men like seeing, you know, naked men in chaddis jumping up

01:30:08.400 --> 01:30:09.400
[Guest]: and down on each other.

01:30:09.400 --> 01:30:11.800
[Guest]: They all gay men is another demographic.

01:30:11.800 --> 01:30:16.720
[Guest]: So as they did that, they said, Okay, so this idea of surplus was very interesting.

01:30:16.720 --> 01:30:18.840
[Guest]: And, you know, so I started thinking of that.

01:30:18.840 --> 01:30:23.920
[Guest]: And I started thinking of, can we create a lab with the surplus of what is already around

01:30:23.920 --> 01:30:24.920
[Guest]: us?

01:30:24.920 --> 01:30:30.200
[Guest]: So then I said, Okay, you know, I have this, there is like, at that time, we didn't have

01:30:30.200 --> 01:30:34.960
[Guest]: an auditorium of the size that we do now, there was a small conference room somewhere

01:30:34.960 --> 01:30:39.960
[Guest]: in there, I said, but chalo, it's being used for office buildings and meetings and all.

01:30:39.960 --> 01:30:43.680
[Guest]: But if we arrange the chairs like this, it kind of becomes an auditorium.

01:30:43.680 --> 01:30:48.000
[Guest]: So I don't need to create a building without it, there is already a thing, right?

01:30:48.000 --> 01:30:50.060
[Guest]: It's just that when people are not using it, I'll use it.

01:30:50.060 --> 01:30:51.840
[Guest]: And everything came from that.

01:30:51.840 --> 01:30:56.880
[Guest]: So the time people tended not to use this conference room kind of auditorium space was

01:30:56.880 --> 01:31:02.240
[Guest]: at end of the week, 5pm on Fridays, it was easy to get booking at that time.

01:31:02.240 --> 01:31:06.840
[Guest]: So we said all our events will be at 5pm on Fridays, because nobody else was booking it

01:31:06.840 --> 01:31:07.840
[Guest]: at Godrej's at that time.

01:31:07.840 --> 01:31:10.240
[Guest]: And since then, it's kind of stayed there, whatever.

01:31:10.240 --> 01:31:14.280
[Guest]: So a lot of those decisions came from that we said, What if we don't have?

01:31:14.280 --> 01:31:19.200
[Guest]: So then we began to look at permanence, impermanence, again, inspired by, you know, by my friends

01:31:19.200 --> 01:31:24.440
[Guest]: like Rahul Mehrotra, the architect, and, you know, Rahul, who is now Dean of Graduate Studies

01:31:24.440 --> 01:31:30.560
[Guest]: at the Harvard School of Design, has done a lot of work on permanence and impermanence

01:31:30.560 --> 01:31:34.120
[Guest]: and how do you build for impermanence.

01:31:34.120 --> 01:31:39.040
[Guest]: And one of his things has been recently he's been studying the Kumbh Mela, as you know,

01:31:39.040 --> 01:31:45.720
[Guest]: as a fantastic site, where you honor the earth, because it's eco friendly, because the entire

01:31:45.720 --> 01:31:51.320
[Guest]: city is built for a short period of time, and then it's dismantled, and it's taken away.

01:31:51.320 --> 01:31:56.040
[Guest]: So unlike, say, the waste of building for the Olympics, or things like that, right,

01:31:56.040 --> 01:32:02.240
[Guest]: where so many countries build a whole infrastructure, which then is left behind, as a dead, you

01:32:02.240 --> 01:32:06.400
[Guest]: know, as this big white elephant that you don't know what to do with the Kumbh Mela

01:32:06.400 --> 01:32:12.240
[Guest]: are interesting, because they give you this framework of saying, you can design for impermanence,

01:32:12.240 --> 01:32:15.800
[Guest]: what matters is the gathering, what matters is not the building.

01:32:15.800 --> 01:32:17.560
[Guest]: So I was very informed by things like that.

01:32:17.560 --> 01:32:22.880
[Guest]: So a lot of the culture labs, whether it's philosophy, whether it's cross pollination,

01:32:22.880 --> 01:32:28.280
[Guest]: whether it's the fact that we have a loose shape shifting lab, which kind of every few

01:32:28.280 --> 01:32:31.200
[Guest]: years changes what we do.

01:32:31.200 --> 01:32:35.920
[Guest]: You know, from an event space, we said we are event space, but we're also resource space.

01:32:35.920 --> 01:32:39.040
[Guest]: So we started doing white papers that served people more.

01:32:39.040 --> 01:32:43.920
[Guest]: We've off late said we had an education space.

01:32:43.920 --> 01:32:47.720
[Guest]: So we started doing fellowships at various levels for like, you know, college students

01:32:47.720 --> 01:32:48.960
[Guest]: and things like that.

01:32:48.960 --> 01:32:52.440
[Guest]: So we said that we had a cultural node and cultural connector.

01:32:52.440 --> 01:32:57.000
[Guest]: So we started connecting other cultural organizations in the country, in interesting ways to come

01:32:57.000 --> 01:32:58.000
[Guest]: together.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:04.280
[Guest]: So whether it is what we do, how we imagine ourselves as this Jugaroo kind of place, you

01:33:04.280 --> 01:33:11.320
[Guest]: know, which kind of exists through the ephemeral, a lot of our events are about transience.

01:33:11.320 --> 01:33:14.760
[Guest]: So we started by doing a lot of these pop-up museums.

01:33:14.760 --> 01:33:20.960
[Guest]: We did a museum of memory as our first pop-up in 2011, which was an old factory that was

01:33:20.960 --> 01:33:23.160
[Guest]: being demolished the next day.

01:33:23.160 --> 01:33:28.280
[Guest]: And we filled it for one whole day with art, design, talks, dance performances.

01:33:28.280 --> 01:33:31.600
[Guest]: The next day, the bulldozers came and demolished everything.

01:33:31.600 --> 01:33:32.720
[Guest]: So it was an interesting experience.

01:33:32.720 --> 01:33:36.880
[Guest]: And everyone who was there, and there were hundreds, if not thousands of people knew

01:33:36.880 --> 01:33:41.600
[Guest]: that they were taking part in the happy death day party of that factory.

01:33:41.600 --> 01:33:48.680
[Guest]: So what does it mean to honor, you know, a space by, through this kind of solidarity,

01:33:48.680 --> 01:33:52.360
[Guest]: knowing very well together that tomorrow it won't be there.

01:33:52.360 --> 01:33:58.740
[Guest]: But what will remain are the moments we create and the digital archive, which is a trace.

01:33:58.740 --> 01:34:02.040
[Guest]: So a lot of that has kind of informed the work that we do.

01:34:02.040 --> 01:34:06.760
[Guest]: We're not obsessed with permanence, but we are obsessed with connections, creating connections

01:34:06.760 --> 01:34:13.200
[Guest]: between our speakers and performers, or our speakers and our audience, or giving resources

01:34:13.200 --> 01:34:14.200
[Guest]: and things like that.

01:34:14.200 --> 01:34:18.200
[Guest]: But it's all, I mean, so the influences have been vast and varied from architecture, from

01:34:18.200 --> 01:34:23.480
[Guest]: philosophy, from Kenya Hara, who is this incredible Japanese designer.

01:34:23.480 --> 01:34:27.960
[Guest]: You know, he was the chief designer of Muji, and he did the Nagano Olympics, spoke to me

01:34:27.960 --> 01:34:30.120
[Guest]: once about emptiness.

01:34:30.120 --> 01:34:33.000
[Guest]: And you know, he's known for his minimalism.

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:35.400
[Guest]: And I hate minimalism as a design practice.

01:34:35.400 --> 01:34:36.400
[Guest]: I mean, I hate it.

01:34:36.400 --> 01:34:37.480
[Guest]: I'm a maximalist.

01:34:37.480 --> 01:34:40.280
[Guest]: I think minimalism is boring as hell.

01:34:40.280 --> 01:34:44.520
[Guest]: You know, this whole like one long gray table with one marigold on the corner.

01:34:44.520 --> 01:34:45.520
[Guest]: I mean, it drives me crazy.

01:34:45.520 --> 01:34:48.520
[Guest]: I'm like, if you give me a small table, I'll want to keep a hundred things on it.

01:34:48.520 --> 01:34:49.520
[Amit Varma]: You know,

01:34:49.520 --> 01:34:53.160
[Amit Varma]: This explains our disagreement on Shah Rukh, by the way, because I like minimalism a bit

01:34:53.160 --> 01:34:54.160
[Amit Varma]: more.

01:34:54.160 --> 01:34:55.160
[Guest]: Oh God.

01:34:55.160 --> 01:34:58.160
[Guest]: Why be minimalist when you can be maximalist anyway.

01:34:58.160 --> 01:35:03.400
[Guest]: So Kenya Hara, who, and he has built Muji on minimalism, as I was telling you, it's

01:35:03.400 --> 01:35:05.400
[Guest]: like, you know, no, he's like, fine.

01:35:05.400 --> 01:35:07.400
[Guest]: He's like, let's not think of minimalism.

01:35:07.400 --> 01:35:10.880
[Guest]: He's like, why don't you look at it as emptiness?

01:35:10.880 --> 01:35:15.280
[Guest]: And he's like, you hate minimalism, don't, he's like, I designed for emptiness.

01:35:15.280 --> 01:35:17.600
[Guest]: And emptiness is not minimalism.

01:35:17.600 --> 01:35:21.960
[Guest]: Emptiness is, I give you something that you can fill how you want.

01:35:21.960 --> 01:35:26.240
[Guest]: So when I'm giving you something that's gray and utilitarian, it is empty, I'm offering

01:35:26.240 --> 01:35:29.120
[Guest]: it to you, do what you want.

01:35:29.120 --> 01:35:32.440
[Guest]: And I thought that was interesting as a way of viewing life, right?

01:35:32.440 --> 01:35:37.640
[Guest]: How can you design for emptiness so that everyone who goes away takes, you know, fills it with

01:35:37.640 --> 01:35:38.640
[Guest]: their own perspective.

01:35:38.640 --> 01:35:45.280
[Guest]: So anyway, the lab philosophy and has grown from so many various influences, people who

01:35:45.280 --> 01:35:49.480
[Guest]: flow through it, are incredible team members over the years.

01:35:49.480 --> 01:35:56.160
[Guest]: We've had some brilliant people, mostly young, you know, flow through the lab, you know,

01:35:56.160 --> 01:35:58.680
[Guest]: come spend some years with the lab.

01:35:58.680 --> 01:36:01.120
[Guest]: They've gone on to do amazing things.

01:36:01.120 --> 01:36:04.200
[Guest]: You know, one of our alums is in Spain doing incredible work.

01:36:04.200 --> 01:36:09.880
[Guest]: Another one left the lab and joined the UN, has been building toilets across the country

01:36:09.880 --> 01:36:15.760
[Guest]: as part of Swachh Bharat and then through, you know, a private CSR initiative.

01:36:15.760 --> 01:36:21.160
[Guest]: Someone else joined the lab, he had trained as a lawyer, joined the lab, discovered so

01:36:21.160 --> 01:36:26.600
[Guest]: many other things and is now a fashion stylist at Grazia.

01:36:26.600 --> 01:36:28.440
[Guest]: So it's been quite amazing.

01:36:28.440 --> 01:36:32.560
[Guest]: I think the legacy of the lab is just the incredible, you know, people who have spoken

01:36:32.560 --> 01:36:34.960
[Guest]: at it, collaborated with it and worked at it.

01:36:34.960 --> 01:36:37.960
[Guest]: So it's been an interesting journey.

01:36:37.960 --> 01:36:42.320
[Guest]: But really thinking about some of these things of like, you know, permanence versus impermanence

01:36:42.320 --> 01:36:43.320
[Guest]: and so on.

01:36:43.320 --> 01:36:44.560
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's so fascinating.

01:36:44.560 --> 01:36:47.640
[Amit Varma]: I need to sort of think deeper about it and process all of it.

01:36:47.640 --> 01:36:52.840
[Amit Varma]: It also strikes me that, you know, virtual spaces also by their very nature are impermanent

01:36:52.840 --> 01:36:53.840
[Amit Varma]: in a way.

01:36:53.840 --> 01:36:59.280
[Amit Varma]: They've kind of been, you know, forced upon us now by the circumstances of the lockdown.

01:36:59.280 --> 01:37:03.400
[Amit Varma]: And it also just struck me when you were speaking about filling emptiness that every time I

01:37:03.400 --> 01:37:07.440
[Amit Varma]: embark upon recording a conversation like this, I am actually what I'm trying to do

01:37:07.440 --> 01:37:13.280
[Amit Varma]: is fill that emptiness of the space that lies ahead for the two or three hours that the

01:37:13.280 --> 01:37:14.360
[Amit Varma]: conversation lasts.

01:37:14.360 --> 01:37:20.440
[Amit Varma]: I want to now, you know, let's kind of move on to the book, which also sort of describes,

01:37:20.440 --> 01:37:25.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, how you straddle these two different worlds simultaneously, like I was very struck

01:37:25.760 --> 01:37:31.520
[Amit Varma]: by your phrasing early on in the book, where you speak about how you have a day job plus

01:37:31.520 --> 01:37:32.520
[Amit Varma]: a gay job.

01:37:32.520 --> 01:37:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And the gay job, of course, is the sort of advocacy where you get corporates to become

01:37:37.120 --> 01:37:39.240
[Amit Varma]: more LGBTQ friendly.

01:37:39.240 --> 01:37:44.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you described that elsewhere in the book, quote, I am arguing from my unique

01:37:44.640 --> 01:37:49.760
[Amit Varma]: inside out position as a corporate person working on LGBTQ issues, and my outside in

01:37:49.760 --> 01:37:55.240
[Amit Varma]: position as an activist and cultural creator using the corporate world to advance my agenda,

01:37:55.240 --> 01:37:56.240
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

01:37:56.240 --> 01:38:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is not just within Godrej, elsewhere you write, quote, I use every occasion that

01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:04.680
[Amit Varma]: I can to talk about LGBTQ issues.

01:38:04.680 --> 01:38:08.360
[Amit Varma]: The Red Bull Music Academy invites me for a talk, I'll queer it.

01:38:08.360 --> 01:38:11.200
[Amit Varma]: The Elle Decor India Design ID Summit, you bet.

01:38:11.200 --> 01:38:15.400
[Amit Varma]: A new Columbia Business School batch is visiting India, time for a gay lecture.

01:38:15.400 --> 01:38:19.960
[Amit Varma]: The Society for Human Resource Management, pretty obvious what I'll be speaking about.

01:38:19.960 --> 01:38:24.440
[Amit Varma]: If I am visiting Yale, Brandeis or Harvard or the Edinburgh International Culture Summit

01:38:24.440 --> 01:38:30.400
[Amit Varma]: at the Scottish Parliament, the desi rainbow flag flies on foreign soil too, stop quote.

01:38:30.400 --> 01:38:33.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you mentioned early on at one part when I think you know, Anand Mahindra

01:38:33.720 --> 01:38:38.640
[Amit Varma]: offered you a job and you asked him that does your company have same sex spousal benefits?

01:38:38.640 --> 01:38:40.040
[Amit Varma]: And he was like, well, not yet.

01:38:40.040 --> 01:38:42.600
[Amit Varma]: But you know, we can do something like that for you.

01:38:42.600 --> 01:38:49.560
[Amit Varma]: And from that, to making this an actual mission, and in my mind is very much, it feels bottom

01:38:49.560 --> 01:38:54.760
[Amit Varma]: up to me that you're getting, you're talking to corporations and getting them to voluntarily

01:38:54.760 --> 01:38:57.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of put these practices in play.

01:38:57.320 --> 01:38:59.000
[Amit Varma]: How did this come about?

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:04.800
[Amit Varma]: Because it obviously evolved into something that had a sense of a mission about it.

01:39:04.800 --> 01:39:06.360
[Amit Varma]: Was it like that from the start?

01:39:06.360 --> 01:39:10.080
[Amit Varma]: And or, you know, how did you kind of view it going into Godrej?

01:39:10.080 --> 01:39:13.360
[Amit Varma]: Did you think that this is something I've got to spend so much time on as you ended

01:39:13.360 --> 01:39:14.360
[Amit Varma]: up doing?

01:39:14.360 --> 01:39:15.360
[Guest]: Yeah, it's very strategic.

01:39:15.360 --> 01:39:20.400
[Guest]: I mean, you know, even calling it a gay job, I mean, I say it in jest and also to rhyme,

01:39:20.400 --> 01:39:25.760
[Guest]: but also very much, because it is, there is a certain performativity, which comes through

01:39:25.760 --> 01:39:30.300
[Guest]: in the writing in Queeristan, but which also very much comes through in how I choose to

01:39:30.300 --> 01:39:32.720
[Guest]: present and interact with the world.

01:39:32.720 --> 01:39:35.440
[Guest]: There is a visibilization that I do.

01:39:35.440 --> 01:39:39.320
[Guest]: And I do it with intent, because it is a form of queering.

01:39:39.320 --> 01:39:42.840
[Guest]: I do want to queer a business in multiple ways, right?

01:39:42.840 --> 01:39:48.600
[Guest]: One is to, what would it mean for business to have a queer person, very visibly queer

01:39:48.600 --> 01:39:50.120
[Guest]: out there in their midst, right?

01:39:50.120 --> 01:39:56.280
[Guest]: So I'm querying business with my presence and with my vociferous presence.

01:39:56.280 --> 01:39:58.480
[Amit Varma]: What do you mean by visibilization, sorry?

01:39:58.480 --> 01:40:03.400
[Guest]: Because I just like other straight people talk about, you know, their lives, I mean,

01:40:03.400 --> 01:40:07.720
[Guest]: I talk in my business meetings, someone will say, because you know, people in business

01:40:07.720 --> 01:40:09.840
[Guest]: don't just talk about work, right?

01:40:09.840 --> 01:40:15.880
[Guest]: Someone will say, you know, my daughter's school this, now her 10th standard exam, I'll

01:40:15.880 --> 01:40:19.180
[Guest]: say, you know, my partner, this, my this, my that.

01:40:19.180 --> 01:40:22.360
[Guest]: And I think for too long, I mean, that's the other thing also, right?

01:40:22.360 --> 01:40:28.280
[Guest]: Either queer people are closeted, so they don't share, or they're not there.

01:40:28.280 --> 01:40:33.160
[Guest]: So a lot of people don't know what it's like, I mean, you know, and at least Godrej with

01:40:33.160 --> 01:40:37.240
[Guest]: our senior leaders, everything, I make sure that if someone is talking about straightness,

01:40:37.240 --> 01:40:41.760
[Guest]: I will make sure that I talk about queerness, because it should be as normal for them to

01:40:41.760 --> 01:40:44.960
[Guest]: listen to what I did on the weekend.

01:40:44.960 --> 01:40:48.800
[Guest]: You know, I can say my partner and me, we went here, we did this, as it is for me to

01:40:48.800 --> 01:40:51.400
[Guest]: listen to them about what they did on the weekend.

01:40:51.400 --> 01:40:58.760
[Guest]: So I mean, so when I say queer business, I queer business with my voice and my presence.

01:40:58.760 --> 01:41:04.320
[Guest]: But also with everything else, with the idea of, you know, what does it mean?

01:41:04.320 --> 01:41:11.120
[Guest]: So I love wearing bowties, you know, and I wear bowties a lot at business meetings, etc.

01:41:11.120 --> 01:41:15.280
[Guest]: I don't know if it's not this, but like, I think over the years, Godrej has changed to

01:41:15.280 --> 01:41:17.300
[Guest]: people can wear what they want.

01:41:17.300 --> 01:41:20.480
[Guest]: And you know, all the way with me with my flamboyant bowties to someone else who may

01:41:20.480 --> 01:41:23.440
[Guest]: choose not to wear a tie, who may choose to wear jeans and t-shirts, right?

01:41:23.440 --> 01:41:28.880
[Guest]: So I'd like to think that my presence, in terms of being so confident with my dress

01:41:28.880 --> 01:41:33.920
[Guest]: sense has empowered other people to say, why do we have a formal dress code, let's all

01:41:33.920 --> 01:41:35.120
[Guest]: dress the way we want, right?

01:41:35.120 --> 01:41:37.640
[Guest]: So that's another way of queering business, I suppose.

01:41:37.640 --> 01:41:39.480
[Guest]: And in so many other ways, right?

01:41:39.480 --> 01:41:42.960
[Guest]: In terms of just thinking about things in terms of how can we think differently and

01:41:42.960 --> 01:41:43.960
[Guest]: so on.

01:41:43.960 --> 01:41:46.880
[Guest]: Likewise, when I say I have a day job, I have a gay job.

01:41:46.880 --> 01:41:52.640
[Guest]: The gay job is very much about interjecting this in other companies and talking to at

01:41:52.640 --> 01:42:01.720
[Guest]: every location, at every space, etc. to widen people's horizons and imagine queerness and

01:42:01.720 --> 01:42:05.240
[Guest]: inclusion as something that they can do.

01:42:05.240 --> 01:42:11.680
[Guest]: But also to visibilize it for them that here is this person who's queer, you know, himself.

01:42:11.680 --> 01:42:15.940
[Guest]: So in that sense, it is very much me.

01:42:15.940 --> 01:42:17.580
[Guest]: So I'm not inauthentic.

01:42:17.580 --> 01:42:25.060
[Guest]: But I'm very conscious of the performative aspect of my gayness in that sense.

01:42:25.060 --> 01:42:30.900
[Guest]: And it is strategic and, you know, and I do it with great intent.

01:42:30.900 --> 01:42:37.160
[Guest]: And I don't leave any space where I can talk about the issues that matter.

01:42:37.160 --> 01:42:40.640
[Guest]: Because I know that, because who knows?

01:42:40.640 --> 01:42:41.640
[Guest]: And that's the thing, right?

01:42:41.640 --> 01:42:44.880
[Guest]: It might be a summit, it might be something, I do it for multiple reasons.

01:42:44.880 --> 01:42:47.960
[Guest]: One is to widen people's horizons, open their minds.

01:42:47.960 --> 01:42:52.280
[Guest]: Secondly, in that audience, there might be a young queer person, you know, who is going

01:42:52.280 --> 01:42:56.760
[Guest]: through doubt, who is thinking, am I the only one who is thinking, maybe the world isn't

01:42:56.760 --> 01:42:59.760
[Guest]: going to get better, who's thinking all these things.

01:42:59.760 --> 01:43:05.120
[Guest]: And I want to show that person that here is someone who is working at a company, who is

01:43:05.120 --> 01:43:06.580
[Guest]: trying to bring about change.

01:43:06.580 --> 01:43:10.560
[Guest]: And don't worry, you know, it's going to be a better world for you, don't worry.

01:43:10.560 --> 01:43:15.000
[Guest]: So one of the other reasons I do it is also to give people the sense of, you know, I'm

01:43:15.000 --> 01:43:17.560
[Guest]: visibilizing to also give them hope.

01:43:17.560 --> 01:43:18.560
[Guest]: And this has happened.

01:43:18.560 --> 01:43:24.840
[Guest]: I write in the book about how I give a lecture at IAMCoryCode one year.

01:43:24.840 --> 01:43:27.760
[Guest]: And I often do recruitment for Godrej, right?

01:43:27.760 --> 01:43:33.040
[Guest]: I go and talk about, and of course, my half an hour recruitment lecture will be 27 minutes

01:43:33.040 --> 01:43:37.000
[Guest]: about LGBTQ rights in India and three minutes about why they should join Godrej.

01:43:37.000 --> 01:43:38.000
[Guest]: And that's fine.

01:43:38.000 --> 01:43:40.900
[Guest]: Because you give me a stage, I'll talk about LGBTQ inclusion.

01:43:40.900 --> 01:43:44.400
[Guest]: So I, you know, did this one year.

01:43:44.400 --> 01:43:48.260
[Guest]: And you know, there was this one girl who stood in the corner and just looked at me

01:43:48.260 --> 01:43:49.260
[Guest]: and didn't come up.

01:43:49.260 --> 01:43:50.260
[Guest]: And this often happens.

01:43:50.260 --> 01:43:54.880
[Guest]: Sometimes students will come up, they'll say, Sir, can we take selfie, this was cool, etc.

01:43:54.880 --> 01:43:57.960
[Guest]: And sometimes people will just like kind of hang out.

01:43:57.960 --> 01:43:59.760
[Guest]: Next year, I went back again.

01:43:59.760 --> 01:44:03.720
[Guest]: And this girl came up to me and said, you know, I heard you.

01:44:03.720 --> 01:44:07.040
[Guest]: It was so because you know, I'm lesbian.

01:44:07.040 --> 01:44:09.840
[Guest]: I'd come I was, you know, I was very scared.

01:44:09.840 --> 01:44:10.840
[Guest]: I'd come to this place.

01:44:10.840 --> 01:44:15.800
[Guest]: I didn't know if IAMC would be a welcoming, inclusive environment, but just hearing you

01:44:15.800 --> 01:44:21.240
[Guest]: speak and you being not embarrassed at all and you speaking about it so naturally, gave

01:44:21.240 --> 01:44:22.240
[Guest]: me the confidence.

01:44:22.240 --> 01:44:23.240
[Guest]: I've come out.

01:44:23.240 --> 01:44:27.160
[Guest]: I'm part of the IAMC LGBTQ support group.

01:44:27.160 --> 01:44:29.640
[Guest]: And you know, we're going to do such incredible work, right?

01:44:29.640 --> 01:44:34.640
[Guest]: So one doesn't know how one's presence and when one talks about it, how it can benefit

01:44:34.640 --> 01:44:38.800
[Guest]: so many others, which is I think, like, you know, for me, this visibilizing aspect is

01:44:38.800 --> 01:44:39.800
[Guest]: very, very important.

01:44:39.800 --> 01:44:44.500
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's so fascinating that this is like a strategic choice that you made.

01:44:44.500 --> 01:44:48.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'll take one more tangent, which I promise will be the last tangent because we really

01:44:48.840 --> 01:44:53.400
[Amit Varma]: ought to get to the meat of the book, but I couldn't help this tangent because it's a subject

01:44:53.400 --> 01:44:54.980
[Amit Varma]: that's kind of close to my heart.

01:44:54.980 --> 01:44:59.360
[Amit Varma]: You spoke earlier about how it is not only young people who are addicted to their gadgets,

01:44:59.360 --> 01:45:03.760
[Amit Varma]: but also, you know, old fogies like us, at least old fogies like me, I don't want to

01:45:03.760 --> 01:45:07.280
[Amit Varma]: offend you by calling you like us.

01:45:07.280 --> 01:45:12.680
[Amit Varma]: And so I was watching a heck of a lot, a lot of TikTok for a while last year.

01:45:12.680 --> 01:45:17.040
[Amit Varma]: And I found it remarkable because, you know, one, obviously, we know how the spread of

01:45:17.040 --> 01:45:22.080
[Amit Varma]: broadband after, you know, Jio really took over that space has, you know, empowered so

01:45:22.080 --> 01:45:25.880
[Amit Varma]: many more people with broadband than they otherwise would have had access to.

01:45:25.880 --> 01:45:32.080
[Amit Varma]: And TikTok was a very fascinating example of, you know, cultural expression being enabled

01:45:32.080 --> 01:45:33.080
[Amit Varma]: by this.

01:45:33.080 --> 01:45:37.680
[Amit Varma]: I have always felt that whatever we see in mainstream entertainment, including Bollywood,

01:45:37.680 --> 01:45:42.920
[Amit Varma]: it is either the content is driven by insiders who've been there forever, but have regressive

01:45:42.920 --> 01:45:49.480
[Amit Varma]: views of Indian society, or elite outsiders who've come with notions that don't transplant

01:45:49.480 --> 01:45:55.080
[Amit Varma]: so easily on, you know, Indian soil as it were, you know, to paraphrase Ambedkar's words

01:45:55.080 --> 01:45:58.620
[Amit Varma]: in an unusual context, they're top dressing on Indian soil.

01:45:58.620 --> 01:46:03.080
[Amit Varma]: But what TikTok gave me a sense was that here was because the means of production and distribution

01:46:03.080 --> 01:46:11.040
[Amit Varma]: was so democratized, that here was sort of this enormous outpouring of what our culture

01:46:11.040 --> 01:46:12.640
[Amit Varma]: really was like.

01:46:12.640 --> 01:46:18.120
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things which I found so heartening was that there was so much, you know, gay

01:46:18.120 --> 01:46:23.200
[Amit Varma]: expression on it, LGBTQ expression on it to the extent that, you know, when the war between

01:46:23.200 --> 01:46:29.840
[Amit Varma]: YouTubers and TikTokers erupted, a lot of the pejoratives or YouTubers were using were,

01:46:29.840 --> 01:46:34.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, homophobic pejoratives, like all of that nonsense.

01:46:34.880 --> 01:46:39.200
[Amit Varma]: And I found it interesting that I think, and I wonder if you'd agree, that what I found

01:46:39.200 --> 01:46:43.440
[Amit Varma]: happening on TikTok is that because there were so many LGBTQ people who were expressing

01:46:43.440 --> 01:46:49.160
[Amit Varma]: these alternate sexualities, and even women expressing, you know, different aspects of

01:46:49.160 --> 01:46:54.360
[Amit Varma]: femininity than you'd otherwise see in popular culture, it created what you know, the sociologist

01:46:54.360 --> 01:47:00.200
[Amit Varma]: Timur Kuran calls a preference cascade, that people watching this no doubt felt empowered

01:47:00.200 --> 01:47:04.560
[Amit Varma]: by this visualization, as you say, by knowing that there are so many other people who are

01:47:04.560 --> 01:47:08.600
[Amit Varma]: like me who share the same tastes as me, and you just had an explosion of content, which

01:47:08.600 --> 01:47:13.680
[Amit Varma]: is why I feel it's like incredibly tragic and almost heartbreaking that TikTok got banned

01:47:13.680 --> 01:47:17.040
[Amit Varma]: more than I would feel about any other app.

01:47:17.040 --> 01:47:18.640
[Amit Varma]: What are sort of your thoughts on this?

01:47:18.640 --> 01:47:23.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, is this something that, you know, gets spoken about, and so on?

01:47:23.040 --> 01:47:29.120
[Guest]: Yeah, so I have a whole section in the book on TikTok, actually, which I love, which,

01:47:29.120 --> 01:47:31.880
[Guest]: you know, comes towards the end.

01:47:31.880 --> 01:47:37.920
[Guest]: And yeah, I mean, if I wish I knew about cascading preferentiality, I would have used it in the

01:47:37.920 --> 01:47:39.080
[Guest]: book.

01:47:39.080 --> 01:47:44.200
[Guest]: But I do want to if I can just read out that section from the book, which I think explains

01:47:44.200 --> 01:47:45.280
[Guest]: it wonderfully, right.

01:47:45.280 --> 01:47:51.000
[Guest]: So this comes after me writing about so many of these TikTok videos with, you know, gay

01:47:51.000 --> 01:47:56.280
[Guest]: men, gay, you know, either couple, single, etc, that, you know, my partner and me see

01:47:56.280 --> 01:48:01.720
[Guest]: every morning, at least used to see while having breakfast together.

01:48:01.720 --> 01:48:06.080
[Guest]: And you know, and this is how I end that section.

01:48:06.080 --> 01:48:12.040
[Guest]: I read this TikTok co-option by queer Indian youth as a form of mimicry and hybridity to

01:48:12.040 --> 01:48:16.240
[Guest]: use two popular terms from the cultural theorist Homi Bhabha.

01:48:16.240 --> 01:48:20.920
[Guest]: I started this chapter by saying that we first need to imagine queeristan and then live in

01:48:20.920 --> 01:48:21.920
[Guest]: it.

01:48:21.920 --> 01:48:26.600
[Guest]: I see the different acts of heteronormative mimicry being performed by the men in the

01:48:26.600 --> 01:48:33.200
[Guest]: video and the videos as both homage to heteronormative romance, as well as the articulation of a

01:48:33.200 --> 01:48:35.880
[Guest]: radical queer agenda.

01:48:35.880 --> 01:48:39.600
[Guest]: Over the course of repeated viewing, and because there are so many of these videos being produced

01:48:39.600 --> 01:48:45.360
[Guest]: and circulated, this performed queerness gets de-linked from the heteronormative homage

01:48:45.360 --> 01:48:49.040
[Guest]: it started off and becomes valid on its own terms.

01:48:49.040 --> 01:48:55.120
[Guest]: I consider this ubiquitous normalization of queer desires to be super exciting.

01:48:55.120 --> 01:48:58.640
[Guest]: We are no longer a minuscule minority.

01:48:58.640 --> 01:49:02.880
[Guest]: Through TikTok, we are showing ourselves and being seen all across India with every

01:49:02.880 --> 01:49:04.520
[Guest]: right swipe.

01:49:04.520 --> 01:49:09.480
[Guest]: And that's what I feel, which is why I think it's really tragic that TikTok was banned,

01:49:09.480 --> 01:49:12.080
[Guest]: but also because there's such a class element to it, right?

01:49:12.080 --> 01:49:20.040
[Guest]: Because so many of the TikTok superstars come from smaller towns, smaller cities, a range

01:49:20.040 --> 01:49:25.920
[Guest]: of languages, say versus, for example, Instagram users who tend to be mostly big cities or

01:49:25.920 --> 01:49:28.720
[Guest]: English speaking and so on, right?

01:49:28.720 --> 01:49:36.200
[Guest]: So it's an economic cost, because so many TikTok stars and influencers were making money

01:49:36.200 --> 01:49:38.360
[Guest]: off TikTok in that sense, right?

01:49:38.360 --> 01:49:45.860
[Guest]: So I think it's quite sad that TikTok is gone as of now.

01:49:45.860 --> 01:49:55.280
[Guest]: So maybe it will come back, and all the TikTok stars can get back to being fabulous and showing

01:49:55.280 --> 01:49:59.920
[Guest]: everyone around them, you know, the range of queer possibilities that exist across this

01:49:59.920 --> 01:50:00.920
[Amit Varma]: country.

01:50:00.920 --> 01:50:04.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that glass angle is indeed very stark, because you know, you know, you and

01:50:04.960 --> 01:50:09.400
[Amit Varma]: I being having grown up so privileged have had access to all the platforms we would want

01:50:09.400 --> 01:50:10.960
[Amit Varma]: to have access to.

01:50:10.960 --> 01:50:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And it just strikes me that TikTok just gave a platform to people who never had any platform

01:50:14.960 --> 01:50:21.520
[Amit Varma]: of any kind, not just in terms of performing themselves, but just watching entertainment

01:50:21.520 --> 01:50:27.040
[Amit Varma]: by people like themselves, and then perhaps being inspired to do stuff of their own, which

01:50:27.040 --> 01:50:28.520
[Amit Varma]: was fantastic.

01:50:28.520 --> 01:50:33.940
[Amit Varma]: Getting back to your day job plus gay job, as it were, you've also you know, at one point

01:50:33.940 --> 01:50:37.560
[Amit Varma]: in your book, you had a couple of lines where you talk about all the talks, you go from

01:50:37.560 --> 01:50:41.040
[Amit Varma]: talk to talk to talk, and you're doing all of that with a sense of mission.

01:50:41.040 --> 01:50:44.960
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, you write, not all of these talks are easy to do.

01:50:44.960 --> 01:50:49.580
[Amit Varma]: And I sometimes find it tedious to repeat myself or answer really basic questions.

01:50:49.580 --> 01:50:53.840
[Amit Varma]: But what to do, diversity line mein yeh sab karna padta hai.

01:50:53.840 --> 01:50:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And I found this very charming, by the way, this interjection of your own voice, which

01:50:57.040 --> 01:51:03.120
[Amit Varma]: is so, you know, true to you and makes a book feel like, you know, someone close to you

01:51:03.120 --> 01:51:07.480
[Amit Varma]: is sitting and talking to you rather than you're reading some boring academic track.

01:51:07.480 --> 01:51:13.160
[Amit Varma]: But how hard was sort of, like, what was the journey like, I mean, I would imagine perhaps

01:51:13.160 --> 01:51:18.200
[Amit Varma]: in a simplistic way that people are much more open now than they might have been when, you

01:51:18.200 --> 01:51:25.480
[Guest]: know, you began 10 years ago, but no, really, no, I people are still, it's still very early

01:51:25.480 --> 01:51:26.480
[Guest]: days.

01:51:26.480 --> 01:51:29.200
[Guest]: It's still really early days.

01:51:29.200 --> 01:51:33.560
[Guest]: Still I will, you know, and I'm happy that they're calling me and I'm very happy to go

01:51:33.560 --> 01:51:39.560
[Guest]: and I'm happy to talk till it will be a sea of, you know, last year, I did organizational

01:51:39.560 --> 01:51:45.320
[Guest]: of pharmaceutical producing industries, etc, OPPA is the largest pharma body in the country.

01:51:45.320 --> 01:51:50.280
[Guest]: So incredible, and I'm glad that they were doing a diversity day.

01:51:50.280 --> 01:51:54.160
[Guest]: You know, they had so many, but I go on stage.

01:51:54.160 --> 01:51:57.920
[Guest]: And one of the other things that I do is if, you know, if I'm giving a talk, and they said

01:51:57.920 --> 01:52:03.800
[Guest]: I make sure that the other people on the panel are different, because, you know, I, again,

01:52:03.800 --> 01:52:10.800
[Guest]: I'm, I'm very conscious, I don't want them to think the LGBT means having three gay men.

01:52:10.800 --> 01:52:16.200
[Guest]: So I just, you know, I make sure I said, you know, do you have a someone who's a lesbian

01:52:16.200 --> 01:52:21.320
[Guest]: by, do you have a trans person, you know, I'm happy with a well meaning ally and things

01:52:21.320 --> 01:52:22.320
[Guest]: like that.

01:52:22.320 --> 01:52:27.600
[Guest]: But I really want you to even visually show when you are showing people who are thinking

01:52:27.600 --> 01:52:32.080
[Guest]: about diversity for the first time, it can't be cis gay men, you need to have a range of

01:52:32.080 --> 01:52:35.160
[Guest]: people even visibly to show people right.

01:52:35.160 --> 01:52:39.640
[Guest]: And I think people are understanding this more and more that, you know, when you talk

01:52:39.640 --> 01:52:43.900
[Guest]: about diversity, it has to be people speaking up for ourselves, right.

01:52:43.900 --> 01:52:48.640
[Guest]: So this was again, you know, this particular thing, it was me, Naina, who's a trans woman

01:52:48.640 --> 01:52:54.000
[Guest]: from Bangalore, who's a friend who's in the book, you know, Neelam Jain, who runs an incredible

01:52:54.000 --> 01:52:59.360
[Guest]: periphery, which is an enterprise that places trans people and so on.

01:52:59.360 --> 01:53:04.040
[Guest]: And the three of us on stage, and we see the sea of blue suits.

01:53:04.040 --> 01:53:09.360
[Guest]: And it's literally like 200 men in the room, all wearing blue suits, or like shirts and

01:53:09.360 --> 01:53:12.960
[Guest]: pants and maybe like four or five women in saris conspicuous.

01:53:12.960 --> 01:53:17.600
[Guest]: And you know, they're on the sides, they're the organizers.

01:53:17.600 --> 01:53:19.000
[Guest]: And it's so interesting, right?

01:53:19.000 --> 01:53:23.600
[Guest]: It's so interesting, because, and there are glass ceilings, right, in corporate India,

01:53:23.600 --> 01:53:29.120
[Guest]: because if you look, you know, even now, in so many companies, entry level will be 50-50

01:53:29.120 --> 01:53:33.360
[Guest]: now, because more and more companies, even basic gender, right, will say, we need to

01:53:33.360 --> 01:53:34.720
[Guest]: hire more women.

01:53:34.720 --> 01:53:40.480
[Guest]: But by the time you reach senior leadership, it's 5%, 8%, 10%, and every level women drop

01:53:40.480 --> 01:53:47.080
[Guest]: off, either due to marriage, then so many women drop off after, you know, having a child

01:53:47.080 --> 01:53:48.080
[Guest]: and things like that.

01:53:48.080 --> 01:53:51.280
[Guest]: And by the time you reach top management, it's a sea of men in blue suits.

01:53:51.280 --> 01:53:56.920
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I had an episode with the amazing Namita Bhandari on how women's participation

01:53:56.920 --> 01:54:01.280
[Amit Varma]: in the workforce has actually gone down over the last 15 years, which is just mind blowing

01:54:01.280 --> 01:54:02.280
[Guest]: to me.

01:54:02.280 --> 01:54:03.280
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:54:03.280 --> 01:54:08.040
[Guest]: I mean, needless to say that when you have a room full of men in blue suits, there will

01:54:08.040 --> 01:54:10.720
[Guest]: be one or two silly questions.

01:54:10.720 --> 01:54:18.120
[Guest]: So I answer them with really with love and humor, and there's no other way.

01:54:18.120 --> 01:54:21.320
[Guest]: So and with empathy, and I try and like personalize it, right.

01:54:21.320 --> 01:54:26.200
[Guest]: So with a lot of people, I can understand, there is so much ignorance.

01:54:26.200 --> 01:54:30.680
[Guest]: So I say just ask, even if even if it's a bad question, it's better you ask and we can

01:54:30.680 --> 01:54:34.520
[Guest]: answer you then you don't ask and you have this misguided assumption.

01:54:34.520 --> 01:54:41.720
[Guest]: I get lots of silly questions, questions ranging all the way from if we offer this basic stuff,

01:54:41.720 --> 01:54:42.720
[Guest]: right.

01:54:42.720 --> 01:54:46.160
[Guest]: So I mean, now more and more progressive companies are offering gender affirmation surgery to

01:54:46.160 --> 01:54:47.160
[Guest]: their employees.

01:54:47.160 --> 01:54:49.640
[Guest]: They're not offering anything extra.

01:54:49.640 --> 01:54:53.720
[Guest]: It's just that say, if you were working at Godrej, and your health insurance would be

01:54:53.720 --> 01:54:55.720
[Guest]: five lakhs or whatever.

01:54:55.720 --> 01:55:00.400
[Guest]: If you happen to transition, you can use your health insurance coverage of that same amount

01:55:00.400 --> 01:55:01.400
[Guest]: to transition.

01:55:01.400 --> 01:55:04.960
[Guest]: Nothing the company has to do, they're paying the same premium for you as everyone else,

01:55:04.960 --> 01:55:07.640
[Guest]: just that your insurer will have to cover that.

01:55:07.640 --> 01:55:12.600
[Guest]: And most insurers across the country are understanding and covering it because it's you know, when

01:55:12.600 --> 01:55:16.040
[Guest]: you do a group insurance, you pay a group premium and whether they use it for a heart

01:55:16.040 --> 01:55:19.900
[Guest]: attack or an accident or this, it doesn't matter to the insurance.

01:55:19.900 --> 01:55:23.200
[Guest]: They charge your premium based on how many people in the group they think will avail

01:55:23.200 --> 01:55:25.960
[Guest]: of it or whatever, right.

01:55:25.960 --> 01:55:30.960
[Guest]: So still, I mean, this is, and more and more companies are offering gender affirmation,

01:55:30.960 --> 01:55:36.120
[Guest]: but you will still hear, there'll be someone who will say, hey, but you know, if I offer

01:55:36.120 --> 01:55:41.080
[Guest]: this, what if so many trans people join me just to do the surgery, and then they leave,

01:55:41.080 --> 01:55:46.760
[Guest]: you know, and then you have to explain to them, first of all, it's not like eating an

01:55:46.760 --> 01:55:49.120
[Guest]: ice cream or going to the movie or whatever.

01:55:49.120 --> 01:55:52.160
[Guest]: It's not like, let's transition.

01:55:52.160 --> 01:55:53.160
[Guest]: It's a process.

01:55:53.160 --> 01:55:54.160
[Guest]: It takes time.

01:55:54.160 --> 01:55:58.240
[Guest]: You have to go through so many evaluations, a doctor has to certify that you're ready

01:55:58.240 --> 01:56:02.800
[Guest]: to transition, you have to begin hormones, then you do the surgery, it takes a lot of

01:56:02.800 --> 01:56:03.800
[Guest]: time.

01:56:03.800 --> 01:56:07.720
[Guest]: Anyone who wants to transition would be serious about it, would be uncomfortable living in

01:56:07.720 --> 01:56:10.760
[Guest]: a body different from the one that they feel and so on.

01:56:10.760 --> 01:56:12.040
[Guest]: So it's a long process.

01:56:12.040 --> 01:56:15.760
[Guest]: No one is going to join you just to avail of the benefit and then leave.

01:56:15.760 --> 01:56:17.720
[Guest]: In fact, it would be the contrary.

01:56:17.720 --> 01:56:21.560
[Guest]: They would join you, they would feel happy that you are offering them this benefit, which

01:56:21.560 --> 01:56:26.040
[Guest]: is so important to them, and it would probably make them more loyal.

01:56:26.040 --> 01:56:31.600
[Guest]: So think about it as you would think about, say, you know, maternity leave, right?

01:56:31.600 --> 01:56:34.320
[Guest]: Now it is a norm for you to give six months maternity leave, right?

01:56:34.320 --> 01:56:38.560
[Guest]: You don't say, oh, someone will join me, become pregnant and then leave.

01:56:38.560 --> 01:56:39.560
[Guest]: No, no.

01:56:39.560 --> 01:56:44.720
[Guest]: You've understood that maternity is something and you can't be equal in this because as

01:56:44.720 --> 01:56:48.080
[Guest]: far as we know right now, men are not able to carry babies.

01:56:48.080 --> 01:56:52.640
[Guest]: So it's something which, you know, that you have to offer your women employees, right?

01:56:52.640 --> 01:56:56.080
[Guest]: You don't think, you've stopped thinking, I don't know if anyone thought, will someone

01:56:56.080 --> 01:56:59.080
[Guest]: join me, take six months maternity leave and then leave.

01:56:59.080 --> 01:57:04.160
[Guest]: So earlier when I was younger, I would get maybe irritable and angry and say, what rubbish,

01:57:04.160 --> 01:57:05.160
[Guest]: what rubbish.

01:57:05.160 --> 01:57:06.160
[Guest]: Now it's just extreme patience.

01:57:06.160 --> 01:57:10.480
[Guest]: I understand that so many of these questions might come out of ignorance.

01:57:10.480 --> 01:57:14.440
[Guest]: I don't think it's willful malice or homophobia at times.

01:57:14.440 --> 01:57:18.120
[Guest]: I think I like to give people the benefit of doubt, maybe they don't know.

01:57:18.120 --> 01:57:23.440
[Guest]: So then I explain to them patiently, things like that, or I personalize it for them.

01:57:23.440 --> 01:57:26.160
[Guest]: Like when people say, when did you know you were gay, I say, when did you know you were

01:57:26.160 --> 01:57:27.160
[Guest]: straight?

01:57:27.160 --> 01:57:32.920
[Guest]: And they're like, ha ha ha, I say, same, no, I mean, you know, they're like, uh, it often

01:57:32.920 --> 01:57:35.880
[Guest]: helps with people to say, you know, think about this.

01:57:35.880 --> 01:57:37.740
[Guest]: What if your child was queer?

01:57:37.740 --> 01:57:39.160
[Guest]: Would you be thinking like this?

01:57:39.160 --> 01:57:42.800
[Guest]: Wouldn't you like your child to go to a school and college in which they were respected and

01:57:42.800 --> 01:57:43.800
[Guest]: not treated differently?

01:57:43.800 --> 01:57:47.880
[Guest]: Remember that the queer people who are coming and working for us are also someone else's

01:57:47.880 --> 01:57:48.880
[Guest]: children.

01:57:48.880 --> 01:57:51.400
[Guest]: So if you don't want your child to be treated differently somewhere else, should you be

01:57:51.400 --> 01:57:52.400
[Guest]: treating?

01:57:52.400 --> 01:57:58.640
[Guest]: So I think a lot of times you have to kind of use different methods and getting the message

01:57:58.640 --> 01:57:59.640
[Guest]: across.

01:57:59.640 --> 01:58:00.640
[Guest]: Is it tiring?

01:58:00.640 --> 01:58:01.640
[Guest]: Yes.

01:58:01.640 --> 01:58:02.640
[Guest]: Is it tedious?

01:58:02.640 --> 01:58:03.640
[Guest]: Yes.

01:58:03.640 --> 01:58:06.640
[Guest]: One of the reasons I wrote this book was also so that I can tell people just read the book

01:58:06.640 --> 01:58:11.000
[Guest]: and then ask questions later, because anything that can be answered by the book, please don't

01:58:11.000 --> 01:58:12.000
[Amit Varma]: ask me.

01:58:12.000 --> 01:58:15.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that can make you very unpopular because one of the things that I have been warned

01:58:15.560 --> 01:58:21.920
[Amit Varma]: not to say to my friends when we are discussing something is, hey, just listen to that episode.

01:58:21.920 --> 01:58:27.260
[Amit Varma]: But but no, I think I think the book is kind of a great service to all of us.

01:58:27.260 --> 01:58:32.760
[Amit Varma]: And I found a couple of terms that you've used in your book concepts, rather extremely

01:58:32.760 --> 01:58:33.760
[Amit Varma]: fascinating.

01:58:33.760 --> 01:58:38.040
[Amit Varma]: And I'd like you to sort of go over them for our listeners.

01:58:38.040 --> 01:58:41.240
[Amit Varma]: One of them is Jugaar resistance.

01:58:41.240 --> 01:58:45.640
[Amit Varma]: What is, I know what is Jugaar and I know what is resistance, tell me about Jugaar resistance.

01:58:45.640 --> 01:58:50.800
[Guest]: The term that I use for my resourceful way of bringing about change by placing myself

01:58:50.800 --> 01:58:53.400
[Guest]: within the system.

01:58:53.400 --> 01:58:59.280
[Guest]: Because I preface that by saying, you know, I have a lot of friends who are in academia

01:58:59.280 --> 01:59:04.560
[Guest]: and activism, who think I'm a sellout or who don't like that I'm in the corporate world.

01:59:04.560 --> 01:59:07.600
[Guest]: And they say, you know, likewise, I have a lot of friends, the corporate world are very

01:59:07.600 --> 01:59:10.800
[Guest]: skeptical of people who are activists, right?

01:59:10.800 --> 01:59:15.880
[Guest]: They'd say, are those chola walas, are those this, are those that, or like, you know, academics

01:59:15.880 --> 01:59:16.880
[Guest]: or whatever.

01:59:16.880 --> 01:59:17.880
[Guest]: Right.

01:59:17.880 --> 01:59:18.880
[Guest]: So I see a lot of distrust.

01:59:18.880 --> 01:59:22.280
[Guest]: But the point is, they're all my friends, and they're all incredible.

01:59:22.280 --> 01:59:24.200
[Guest]: And they're all doing amazing work.

01:59:24.200 --> 01:59:29.360
[Guest]: So, you know, I think of Jugaar resistance as like this thing that I do, which is, you

01:59:29.360 --> 01:59:31.400
[Guest]: know, am I okay with the status quo?

01:59:31.400 --> 01:59:32.400
[Guest]: No.

01:59:32.400 --> 01:59:37.200
[Guest]: Do I want to resist and create a better world, a better, you know, post pandemic, a better

01:59:37.200 --> 01:59:40.720
[Guest]: new normal, a more inclusive new normal, all of that, yes.

01:59:40.720 --> 01:59:43.920
[Guest]: I have chosen to locate myself within the system.

01:59:43.920 --> 01:59:46.640
[Guest]: But within the system, how can I resist?

01:59:46.640 --> 01:59:53.360
[Guest]: How can I kind of keep the door open and, and kind of have this build spaces for conversations

01:59:53.360 --> 01:59:58.840
[Guest]: in which, you know, people from these multiple silos can hang out and maybe help each other.

01:59:58.840 --> 01:59:59.960
[Guest]: That is my Jugaar.

01:59:59.960 --> 02:00:06.200
[Guest]: So it's this kind of micro revolutions of change by placing oneself within the system.

02:00:06.200 --> 02:00:11.320
[Guest]: And drawback of that is that everyone could dislike you, like, you know, your corporate

02:00:11.320 --> 02:00:15.000
[Guest]: world would not trust you, because they think, you know, at heart, you're an activist and

02:00:15.000 --> 02:00:19.600
[Guest]: academic, and activists and academics might not like you, because they think you're from

02:00:19.600 --> 02:00:20.600
[Guest]: the system.

02:00:20.600 --> 02:00:24.080
[Guest]: But I found, thankfully, that the contrary is true.

02:00:24.080 --> 02:00:27.160
[Guest]: I think if you tell everyone very honestly, this is who I am.

02:00:27.160 --> 02:00:30.560
[Guest]: This is where I'm from, darling, this is what I want to do.

02:00:30.560 --> 02:00:32.240
[Guest]: They appreciate the honesty.

02:00:32.240 --> 02:00:36.180
[Guest]: And thankfully, that's what I found over the past 10 years, at least the people appreciate

02:00:36.180 --> 02:00:40.120
[Guest]: that I'm transparent, I'm saying, look, I'm not saying anything more.

02:00:40.120 --> 02:00:44.000
[Guest]: I'm saying this is me, I place myself here, here's what I want to do.

02:00:44.000 --> 02:00:45.760
[Guest]: Let's try and do this together.

02:00:45.760 --> 02:00:46.760
[Guest]: Does it have limitations?

02:00:46.760 --> 02:00:47.760
[Guest]: Sure.

02:00:47.760 --> 02:00:48.760
[Guest]: I mean, that's which I acknowledge, right?

02:00:48.760 --> 02:00:54.080
[Guest]: I even acknowledge in the book, that I'm being permitted to do all of this, I'm being allowed

02:00:54.080 --> 02:00:55.080
[Guest]: to do all of this.

02:00:55.080 --> 02:01:02.000
[Guest]: And any given time, given that I operate within, you know, a framework, a structure, an institution,

02:01:02.000 --> 02:01:07.040
[Guest]: not a, you know, a job, whatever, it could be found not useful, it could be shut down.

02:01:07.040 --> 02:01:13.360
[Guest]: So I understand that I'm at the mercy of, you know, larger structural forces at play.

02:01:13.360 --> 02:01:17.920
[Guest]: And I operate very much from this position of structural inequality, saying that I know

02:01:17.920 --> 02:01:22.760
[Guest]: this is a system in which we work, I know that there is maybe a toehold that one has,

02:01:22.760 --> 02:01:26.920
[Guest]: how can I use this toehold to maybe make the world better is what I'm trying to do in the

02:01:26.920 --> 02:01:27.920
[Amit Varma]: book.

02:01:27.920 --> 02:01:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And, and let's take a quick commercial break now, and when we come back, we'll continue

02:01:32.320 --> 02:01:36.720
[Amit Varma]: talking about, you know, your book, and I promise I won't hold you up too much after

02:01:36.720 --> 02:01:37.720
[Amit Varma]: that.

02:01:37.720 --> 02:01:42.680
[Amit Varma]: There will be no more tangential digressions as I am wont to indulge in.

02:01:42.680 --> 02:01:45.680
[Amit Varma]: So see you in a minute.

02:01:45.680 --> 02:01:46.680
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

02:01:46.680 --> 02:01:49.240
[Amit Varma]: Hi, I'm Vivek Kaul.

02:01:49.240 --> 02:01:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And I'm Amit Verma.

02:01:50.240 --> 02:01:54.600
[Amit Varma]: Here to tell you about a new weekly podcast that Vivek and I have launched called Econ

02:01:54.600 --> 02:01:55.600
[Unknown]: Central.

02:01:55.600 --> 02:02:01.760
[Unknown]: In Econ Central, we will help you make sense of the economic news of the last week.

02:02:01.760 --> 02:02:05.600
[Unknown]: And we'll also try to explain complex subjects in a simple language.

02:02:05.600 --> 02:02:10.640
[Amit Varma]: We will also take events outside the world of economics, like from politics, sports,

02:02:10.640 --> 02:02:15.000
[Amit Varma]: literature, and explain them through the lens of economic thinking.

