[Amit Varma]: Should we boycott Chinese goods?

02:02:22.980 --> 02:02:25.760
[Amit Varma]: What does free speech have to do with incentives?

02:02:25.760 --> 02:02:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Why are the roving bandits of Uttar Pradesh in competition with the biggest protection

02:02:29.600 --> 02:02:32.160
[Unknown]: racket out there, the Indian state?

02:02:32.160 --> 02:02:36.160
[Unknown]: All this and more in our new weekly podcast, Econ Central.

02:02:36.160 --> 02:02:40.560
[Amit Varma]: Econ Central launched a few weeks ago and is free on all podcast apps.

02:02:40.560 --> 02:02:45.520
[Amit Varma]: You can browse our archives at econcentral.in.

02:02:45.520 --> 02:02:49.280
[Unknown]: Econ Central, you have an incentive to listen.

02:02:49.280 --> 02:02:57.680
[Amit Varma]: Don't forget the URL, econcentral.in.

02:02:57.680 --> 02:02:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the Scene and the Unseen.

02:02:59.000 --> 02:03:02.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Parmesh Shani about his amazing book, Where Is Sun and indeed the

02:03:02.680 --> 02:03:05.620
[Amit Varma]: journey that sort of led him to your book.

02:03:05.620 --> 02:03:10.720
[Amit Varma]: Another phrase that really fascinated me in your book and got me to, you know, just stop

02:03:10.720 --> 02:03:13.800
[Amit Varma]: reading and think about it for a bit was the phrase cultural acupuncture.

02:03:13.800 --> 02:03:16.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, tell me a bit about this.

02:03:16.760 --> 02:03:21.920
[Guest]: So it's, it's a phrase that I borrowed from the Harry Potter Alliance, you know, which

02:03:21.920 --> 02:03:27.480
[Guest]: is incredible, which is, you know, Andrew Slack and the others founded it.

02:03:27.480 --> 02:03:32.960
[Guest]: And it's a phrase that actually talks about, you know, using the framework of, you know,

02:03:32.960 --> 02:03:36.280
[Guest]: popular culture to bring about social change.

02:03:36.280 --> 02:03:41.640
[Guest]: So imagining the real world as like, you know, as one of these popular culture spaces to

02:03:41.640 --> 02:03:46.840
[Guest]: imagine the real world as, you know, as a Star Wars universe or as this Harry Potter

02:03:46.840 --> 02:03:47.840
[Guest]: universe.

02:03:47.840 --> 02:03:52.400
[Guest]: What would it mean for young people to create Dumbledore's army and bring about this change?

02:03:52.400 --> 02:03:53.400
[Guest]: Right.

02:03:53.400 --> 02:03:57.040
[Guest]: So there are so many young people across fans, fans, young people across the world, who are

02:03:57.040 --> 02:04:02.520
[Guest]: saying, can we create a Dumbledore's army to petition for trans rights or to petition

02:04:02.520 --> 02:04:05.920
[Guest]: for a trans washroom in our school or college?

02:04:05.920 --> 02:04:06.920
[Guest]: Right.

02:04:06.920 --> 02:04:11.160
[Guest]: So using this popular imagination, and a lot of young people are doing that in the recent

02:04:11.160 --> 02:04:13.040
[Guest]: Hong Kong protests.

02:04:13.040 --> 02:04:20.160
[Guest]: You know, last year, you know, the Bruce Lee's, you know, still like water, imagery was used

02:04:20.160 --> 02:04:21.160
[Guest]: a lot.

02:04:21.160 --> 02:04:25.680
[Guest]: And Henry Jenkins, my guru taught me about this phrase when he came to India, we hosted

02:04:25.680 --> 02:04:27.400
[Guest]: him, he visited us.

02:04:27.400 --> 02:04:28.640
[Guest]: And I kind of liked it.

02:04:28.640 --> 02:04:30.400
[Guest]: I use it in a different context.

02:04:30.400 --> 02:04:35.880
[Guest]: I use it, you know, I, when I use it in the book, I, you know, I honor the origin of the

02:04:35.880 --> 02:04:40.640
[Guest]: phrase and I honor the Harry Potter Alliance from where it came, but I use it more to describe

02:04:40.640 --> 02:04:43.300
[Guest]: the kind of experiments that I am doing.

02:04:43.300 --> 02:04:47.560
[Guest]: So I told you earlier in the interview that, you know, I think, why do I think top down

02:04:47.560 --> 02:04:51.640
[Guest]: approach might be good, because I think you need to know where to press, you need to know

02:04:51.640 --> 02:04:54.200
[Guest]: where to push to bring about that change, right?

02:04:54.200 --> 02:04:58.360
[Guest]: And that's what acupuncture is, you put the needle in at the right place, you know, the

02:04:58.360 --> 02:05:00.160
[Guest]: pain goes away or whatever.

02:05:00.160 --> 02:05:03.320
[Guest]: And often you do it because you don't have resources to press everywhere.

02:05:03.320 --> 02:05:06.800
[Guest]: You have a finite number of like, you know, things that you do, you need to find out where

02:05:06.800 --> 02:05:08.580
[Guest]: to make that change.

02:05:08.580 --> 02:05:15.280
[Guest]: So I use it to talk about the various points that I press both within Godrej and outside,

02:05:15.280 --> 02:05:20.080
[Guest]: you know, within Godrej, through the lab, but also through the other kinds of influence

02:05:20.080 --> 02:05:25.840
[Guest]: that I wield, whether it is with senior leaders, whether it is with, you know, helping curate

02:05:25.840 --> 02:05:31.800
[Guest]: things like the leadership forum, which is a meeting of senior leaders, or whether it

02:05:31.800 --> 02:05:37.120
[Guest]: is as been in utilizing the Godrej platform to talk about change to other companies and

02:05:37.120 --> 02:05:38.240
[Guest]: other organizations.

02:05:38.240 --> 02:05:45.240
[Guest]: So I use it to describe my method of bringing about change by pressing at the right notes.

02:05:45.240 --> 02:05:49.360
[Guest]: And both these phrases come about early in the book, because I really want to give readers

02:05:49.360 --> 02:05:53.760
[Guest]: a sense of what I've been trying to do, but also leave them with a template because you

02:05:53.760 --> 02:05:57.020
[Guest]: know, I think of this book very much as my legacy.

02:05:57.020 --> 02:06:00.800
[Guest]: And for all the young people who are reading it, I want them to read it and say, achha,

02:06:00.800 --> 02:06:02.520
[Guest]: you know, maybe we can do this, right?

02:06:02.520 --> 02:06:06.320
[Guest]: Because the people reading it can be, maybe some of them are in college, maybe some of

02:06:06.320 --> 02:06:07.760
[Guest]: them are working.

02:06:07.760 --> 02:06:12.800
[Guest]: I want them to use this as a method and say, okay, so you know, Parmesh could do this,

02:06:12.800 --> 02:06:15.320
[Guest]: maybe we can go to our principal and say, what about this, right?

02:06:15.320 --> 02:06:18.400
[Guest]: Or maybe we can tell, and it's already happening.

02:06:18.400 --> 02:06:23.120
[Guest]: Like because Godrej has been talking about this and doing this, so many young HR people

02:06:23.120 --> 02:06:27.960
[Guest]: I meet, tell me, you know, we told our boss, look, Godrej is doing this.

02:06:27.960 --> 02:06:30.520
[Guest]: And also they said, okay, Godrej is doing this, we can also.

02:06:30.520 --> 02:06:36.000
[Guest]: So you know, they are using this in a way to kind of get the permissions ready to bring

02:06:36.000 --> 02:06:39.400
[Guest]: about the changes that they want to bring about.

02:06:39.400 --> 02:06:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Another phrase in the book that I was struck by and that spoke to me was circulatory queerness.

02:06:44.000 --> 02:06:48.160
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, you speak about the many notions of the self.

02:06:48.160 --> 02:06:53.200
[Amit Varma]: And I want to read that part out as well, where you say, in India, everything is inextricably

02:06:53.200 --> 02:06:55.480
[Amit Varma]: tied to the idea of family and community.

02:06:55.480 --> 02:06:58.800
[Amit Varma]: And maybe that is where we can locate the hyphenation.

02:06:58.800 --> 02:07:01.040
[Amit Varma]: And you mean between Indian and queer.

02:07:01.040 --> 02:07:05.720
[Amit Varma]: And then you continue, quote, this Western post-enlightenment idea of the self that needs

02:07:05.720 --> 02:07:10.800
[Amit Varma]: to be found, that we need to be the best version of ourselves, that life is a journey of discovering

02:07:10.800 --> 02:07:14.400
[Amit Varma]: and then polishing ourselves, is not so useful to us in India.

02:07:14.400 --> 02:07:17.680
[Amit Varma]: Here we are many selves and there is no one self.

02:07:17.680 --> 02:07:21.440
[Amit Varma]: And each of ourselves is conditional and contextual.

02:07:21.440 --> 02:07:25.940
[Amit Varma]: And as we spend our lives navigating these multiple selves, it is important for workspaces

02:07:25.940 --> 02:07:30.720
[Amit Varma]: to become crucibles of identity formation of some kind, stop quote.

02:07:30.720 --> 02:07:35.080
[Amit Varma]: And later on, you elaborate on, you know, what it means when you say workplaces should

02:07:35.080 --> 02:07:40.240
[Amit Varma]: become crucibles of identity formation, which was, again, a sort of a new thought to me,

02:07:40.240 --> 02:07:45.760
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, you talk about how, you know, you spoke to an audience of Franklin Templeton

02:07:45.760 --> 02:07:51.200
[Amit Varma]: employees in Mumbai, and you address HR managers, and you said that, you know, think about who

02:07:51.200 --> 02:07:55.560
[Amit Varma]: your employees are, quote, someone who has been writing exams their whole life, maybe

02:07:55.560 --> 02:07:58.300
[Amit Varma]: they did well in class 10, and then in class 12.

02:07:58.300 --> 02:08:02.800
[Amit Varma]: And then so on, you sort of line them all up, GE, IIT, MBA, IIM, whatever.

02:08:02.800 --> 02:08:06.920
[Amit Varma]: And then you write, quote, when these young employees come into your system, I told my

02:08:06.920 --> 02:08:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Franklin Templeton audience, they are not fully developed, they know how to mug up write

02:08:11.440 --> 02:08:16.100
[Amit Varma]: exams and pass test, they often sacrificed a lot in their quest to emerge from the narrow

02:08:16.100 --> 02:08:18.480
[Amit Varma]: end of the funnel into your organization.

02:08:18.480 --> 02:08:23.400
[Amit Varma]: And this includes sacrificing thinking of things such as their own identity, or what

02:08:23.400 --> 02:08:27.640
[Amit Varma]: makes them happy, or gives them purpose in life, your workspace needs to welcome them

02:08:27.640 --> 02:08:30.480
[Amit Varma]: to explore their multiple selves.

02:08:30.480 --> 02:08:35.160
[Amit Varma]: You need to reassure them that it is okay to be who they are here, that they can engage

02:08:35.160 --> 02:08:39.840
[Amit Varma]: with the identities that they often tend to suppress at home.

02:08:39.840 --> 02:08:45.880
[Amit Varma]: As a consequence, an Indian corporate structure for an Indian LGBTQ person must be a space

02:08:45.880 --> 02:08:48.440
[Amit Varma]: for reconciliation, stop code.

02:08:48.440 --> 02:08:50.860
[Amit Varma]: And this is a fascinating message.

02:08:50.860 --> 02:08:56.600
[Amit Varma]: And it's also sort of a fascinating message in the sense that I think many companies when

02:08:56.600 --> 02:09:01.320
[Amit Varma]: you talk about LGBTQ rights, would respond to it from a perspective of okay, it makes

02:09:01.320 --> 02:09:04.120
[Amit Varma]: sense we should not discriminate against them.

02:09:04.120 --> 02:09:09.680
[Amit Varma]: But what you are saying here is that no, that is not enough, that there is more that you

02:09:09.680 --> 02:09:11.160
[Amit Varma]: need to do.

02:09:11.160 --> 02:09:14.280
[Amit Varma]: So expand a little bit on that kind of thinking.

02:09:14.280 --> 02:09:17.580
[Amit Varma]: And how receptive have corporates been to it?

02:09:17.580 --> 02:09:22.240
[Guest]: I think corporates have been incredibly receptive, because this is also linking to another theme

02:09:22.240 --> 02:09:25.560
[Guest]: in the book, which is all about family, right?

02:09:25.560 --> 02:09:31.240
[Guest]: So large parts of the book are about personal families, then families of choice, right?

02:09:31.240 --> 02:09:34.560
[Guest]: Personal families when your own parents accept you, families of choice are the families that

02:09:34.560 --> 02:09:36.200
[Guest]: you create.

02:09:36.200 --> 02:09:42.040
[Guest]: So hijraf households are often families of choice, where you create family like structures

02:09:42.040 --> 02:09:47.800
[Guest]: to either compensate for or to supplement, you know, the love that you get from your

02:09:47.800 --> 02:09:49.800
[Guest]: birth families, right?

02:09:49.800 --> 02:09:53.280
[Guest]: And then I actually say that workplaces have to act like families.

02:09:53.280 --> 02:09:58.320
[Guest]: So I think it is very Indian, in this sense of saying that your workplace has to be a

02:09:58.320 --> 02:10:04.160
[Guest]: space for reconciliation, because in so many other countries, you come out first at home,

02:10:04.160 --> 02:10:09.720
[Guest]: and then you go to this workplace as this kind of well formed or whatever individual.

02:10:09.720 --> 02:10:13.240
[Guest]: But in India, because of that passage you read out, right, and that is the experience

02:10:13.240 --> 02:10:14.240
[Guest]: for so many people.

02:10:14.240 --> 02:10:21.040
[Guest]: Anyway, where we talk about happiness, love, purpose, identity in our houses, forget sex

02:10:21.040 --> 02:10:25.560
[Guest]: or gender, or like any of that, right, where we talk about these things.

02:10:25.560 --> 02:10:30.840
[Guest]: So people are really, really, really, really need these spaces.

02:10:30.840 --> 02:10:35.480
[Guest]: And this comes out of the hundreds of talks I've done on college campuses and in offices,

02:10:35.480 --> 02:10:36.480
[Guest]: right?

02:10:36.480 --> 02:10:39.920
[Guest]: When people come up to you, and they tell you, it's the first time you're hearing about

02:10:39.920 --> 02:10:40.920
[Guest]: something like this.

02:10:40.920 --> 02:10:44.320
[Guest]: Now, if you're 24, 25, and it's the first time you're hearing about something like this,

02:10:44.320 --> 02:10:47.520
[Guest]: I just feel like, you know, what have you, how have you spent the rest of your life,

02:10:47.520 --> 02:10:51.480
[Guest]: but you've not thought about something fundamental to who you are.

02:10:51.480 --> 02:10:53.720
[Guest]: So I think the workplace has to be that.

02:10:53.720 --> 02:10:59.680
[Guest]: And people understand, because that's the other thing when people, people who run companies,

02:10:59.680 --> 02:11:03.120
[Guest]: people who are in HR departments are also human beings.

02:11:03.120 --> 02:11:06.680
[Guest]: They've gone through the same process themselves.

02:11:06.680 --> 02:11:12.560
[Guest]: So when you appeal to that inner humanness, when you say, look, you have families at home,

02:11:12.560 --> 02:11:13.560
[Guest]: right?

02:11:13.560 --> 02:11:15.800
[Guest]: You have children at home, you have this.

02:11:15.800 --> 02:11:20.320
[Guest]: We need to act like good, what does it mean for you to be a good parent to your children

02:11:20.320 --> 02:11:21.320
[Guest]: at home?

02:11:21.320 --> 02:11:24.600
[Guest]: Can we not be good parents to our employees?

02:11:24.600 --> 02:11:29.120
[Guest]: Given that this is the context, I mean, more often than not, I have found people getting

02:11:29.120 --> 02:11:33.040
[Guest]: it and saying, okay, what would this mean, etc, right?

02:11:33.040 --> 02:11:38.200
[Guest]: Then of course, it's, it's, I mean, it's manifested in multiple ways and policy changes and, you

02:11:38.200 --> 02:11:39.600
[Guest]: know, and so on.

02:11:39.600 --> 02:11:41.320
[Guest]: And then there are other challenges that come up.

02:11:41.320 --> 02:11:44.760
[Guest]: How do you translate all this intent into practice?

02:11:44.760 --> 02:11:49.520
[Guest]: But I think at a fundamental level, which is why this is such a desi book, when you

02:11:49.520 --> 02:11:53.280
[Guest]: argue on this term, it's very hard for people to not understand.

02:11:53.280 --> 02:11:56.400
[Guest]: And what I've done in the book is I've covered all grounds, right?

02:11:56.400 --> 02:11:59.920
[Guest]: I've argued on a money term, we all love money.

02:11:59.920 --> 02:12:01.360
[Guest]: I've said it makes you more money.

02:12:01.360 --> 02:12:03.280
[Guest]: I've argued on an innovation term.

02:12:03.280 --> 02:12:07.040
[Guest]: It makes you mine, not just me saying it, there's data that backs it.

02:12:07.040 --> 02:12:09.440
[Guest]: I've argued on the talent term.

02:12:09.440 --> 02:12:14.480
[Guest]: But above all, I'm saying, it's in our culture, we need to be like this.

02:12:14.480 --> 02:12:15.720
[Guest]: We need to act like this.

02:12:15.720 --> 02:12:17.160
[Guest]: It's who we are, right?

02:12:17.160 --> 02:12:24.080
[Guest]: So I think I've made a pretty watertight case, in terms of whichever way you look at it,

02:12:24.080 --> 02:12:30.560
[Guest]: whatever aspect of your mind or heart you want to be appealed to, I think the book serves

02:12:30.560 --> 02:12:34.560
[Guest]: that purpose that you know, it shows very clearly, there's no reason to be not inclusive.

02:12:34.560 --> 02:12:41.160
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact, it kind of you have a chapter on how queerness is ingrained in our history,

02:12:41.160 --> 02:12:45.120
[Amit Varma]: whether we are talking about ancient times or medieval times from a Hindu perspective

02:12:45.120 --> 02:12:49.720
[Amit Varma]: or medieval times from, you know, an Islamic perspective all the way to the modern day.

02:12:49.720 --> 02:12:53.680
[Amit Varma]: And that kind of kind of leaves me baffled, because then there is that paradox, that on

02:12:53.680 --> 02:13:00.040
[Amit Varma]: the one hand, in our society, we have so much homophobia, or often just ignorance, while

02:13:00.040 --> 02:13:05.600
[Amit Varma]: actually, you know, these modes of behavior and these modes of living have been ingrained

02:13:05.600 --> 02:13:09.800
[Amit Varma]: in our society for way longer than before, you know, the West came up with words for

02:13:09.800 --> 02:13:16.480
[Amit Varma]: it, like homosexuality or queerness or whatever, you know, and this dichotomy to me just sinking

02:13:16.480 --> 02:13:18.760
[Amit Varma]: aloud extends much beyond this.

02:13:18.760 --> 02:13:23.840
[Amit Varma]: It is, you know, I was once chatting with the politician JP Narayan about our society,

02:13:23.840 --> 02:13:26.280
[Amit Varma]: and I described India as an illiberal society.

02:13:26.280 --> 02:13:30.240
[Amit Varma]: And my reason for saying that, of course, was the way we treat our women and caste and

02:13:30.240 --> 02:13:31.240
[Amit Varma]: all of those things.

02:13:31.240 --> 02:13:34.720
[Amit Varma]: And he pointed out that from another point of view, we are a deeply liberal society,

02:13:34.720 --> 02:13:40.400
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, it's so inclusive in terms of cultural influences, all our food, all

02:13:40.400 --> 02:13:44.160
[Amit Varma]: our clothing, we take influences from everywhere, and we make them up.

02:13:44.160 --> 02:13:48.680
[Amit Varma]: We are a Khichri of our nation, you know, I struggled to wrap my head around this paradox

02:13:48.680 --> 02:13:49.680
[Amit Varma]: and this dichotomy.

02:13:49.680 --> 02:13:51.800
[Guest]: What do you think of it?

02:13:51.800 --> 02:13:56.520
[Guest]: I've also struggled to wrap my head around it, which is why one way of writing this book

02:13:56.520 --> 02:13:58.960
[Guest]: has been to unravel some of this.

02:13:58.960 --> 02:14:03.920
[Guest]: But my position is very clear that, I mean, I've written this book to unravel, but also,

02:14:03.920 --> 02:14:08.820
[Guest]: I mean, the purpose of this book is very much to serve as a manual for change, right?

02:14:08.820 --> 02:14:14.640
[Guest]: So try to make it like simple, and in that sense, very clear, understanding the paradoxes,

02:14:14.640 --> 02:14:17.200
[Guest]: but simplifying it to a point of look.

02:14:17.200 --> 02:14:19.720
[Guest]: I mean, it's very clear, right?

02:14:19.720 --> 02:14:21.960
[Guest]: It's in our culture.

02:14:21.960 --> 02:14:26.320
[Guest]: It's in our family values, our family values are to include, plus, there's all these other

02:14:26.320 --> 02:14:27.320
[Guest]: benefits.

02:14:27.320 --> 02:14:28.520
[Guest]: It makes you money, it makes you this, it makes you that.

02:14:28.520 --> 02:14:33.280
[Guest]: So net net, it's good for you, whichever way you look at it.

02:14:33.280 --> 02:14:39.880
[Guest]: I've not found one reason in my years of research that says that discriminating against someone

02:14:39.880 --> 02:14:40.880
[Guest]: is bad for you.

02:14:40.880 --> 02:14:42.680
[Guest]: Here are all the reasons that's good for you.

02:14:42.680 --> 02:14:45.320
[Guest]: I've not found any reason why it might be bad for you.

02:14:45.320 --> 02:14:46.320
[Amit Varma]: Not discriminating.

02:14:46.320 --> 02:14:48.480
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

02:14:48.480 --> 02:14:52.720
[Guest]: So people seem to get it.

02:14:52.720 --> 02:14:56.560
[Guest]: People don't think, I think a lot of the times there's so much noise, people kind of get

02:14:56.560 --> 02:14:58.320
[Guest]: distracted by the noise, right?

02:14:58.320 --> 02:15:02.640
[Guest]: So a lot of noise comes, this is against our culture, but when you say actually, no, no,

02:15:02.640 --> 02:15:08.800
[Guest]: no, let me show you how it's in our culture, oh yeah, it is in our culture.

02:15:08.800 --> 02:15:15.360
[Guest]: You've forgotten it, which is why I think the work of scholars like Ruth Vanita and

02:15:15.360 --> 02:15:23.600
[Guest]: Salim Kidwai, or writers like Devdutt Patnayak, who have popularized mythology so much over

02:15:23.600 --> 02:15:29.560
[Guest]: the years, is so vital because in a way, Devdutt in his writing, I mean, whether it's very

02:15:29.560 --> 02:15:34.880
[Guest]: directly in Ashikhandi and other stories they don't tell you, or indirectly in, I would

02:15:34.880 --> 02:15:41.200
[Guest]: say most of Devdutt's other works, is about equality, plurality, inclusiveness, widening

02:15:41.200 --> 02:15:46.360
[Guest]: one's horizon about the idea of India, and recognizing that a lot of this, right?

02:15:46.360 --> 02:15:54.840
[Guest]: Even Ruth and Salim write in, you know, their same-sex love in India, that homophobia is

02:15:54.840 --> 02:16:00.360
[Guest]: something that was imported into India with the British. And, you know, they left 70 years

02:16:00.360 --> 02:16:06.120
[Guest]: ago. I find it tragic that, you know, homophobia remains. I think it's time we sent it off

02:16:06.120 --> 02:16:12.680
[Guest]: packing as well. And maybe we can get the Kohinoor diamond back. You know, take your

02:16:12.680 --> 02:16:15.080
[Guest]: homophobia back and give us back our diamond.

02:16:15.080 --> 02:16:20.520
[Amit Varma]: I completely agree with you about giving homophobia away, but the ghar-wapsi of the Kohinoor diamond

02:16:20.520 --> 02:16:22.960
[Guest]: I think is unnecessary.

02:16:22.960 --> 02:16:27.320
[Guest]: I will wear it. I have the perfect setting for it, darling.

02:16:27.320 --> 02:16:33.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, that would be even more visualization, as you say, for your audiences, if you wear

02:16:33.320 --> 02:16:38.520
[Amit Varma]: the Kohinoor diamond on stage. Let's move on to another fascinating section on your

02:16:38.520 --> 02:16:42.880
[Amit Varma]: book, the third of five parts, where you, in a series of different chapters, you lay

02:16:42.880 --> 02:16:48.200
[Amit Varma]: out different aspects of the case for inclusion, and you begin it with a chapter on the meta

02:16:48.200 --> 02:16:53.720
[Amit Varma]: issues. And I really like that, because it struck me that the case for inclusion can

02:16:53.720 --> 02:16:58.800
[Amit Varma]: be made through two different prisms, just as I have always thought about the case for

02:16:58.800 --> 02:17:03.400
[Amit Varma]: individual freedom. Like I've always argued that you can make a case for individual freedom

02:17:03.400 --> 02:17:09.360
[Amit Varma]: on purely moral terms, deontological terms, where you say that it is good in and of itself,

02:17:09.360 --> 02:17:13.440
[Amit Varma]: you have to respect individual autonomy and consent and all of that. But you can also

02:17:13.440 --> 02:17:17.440
[Amit Varma]: make the case for individual freedom, whether in the marketplace or the bedroom, from a

02:17:17.440 --> 02:17:22.040
[Amit Varma]: consequentialist point of view, and say that it's not just better for the individuals involved,

02:17:22.040 --> 02:17:28.680
[Amit Varma]: but for society as a whole, if all of us are, you know, free to express ourselves and to

02:17:28.680 --> 02:17:33.480
[Amit Varma]: live our lives as we please, provided we don't infringe the right of others. Now, so the

02:17:33.480 --> 02:17:37.280
[Amit Varma]: case can be made both ways. And it's often a strategic choice, right? If you're making

02:17:37.280 --> 02:17:41.840
[Amit Varma]: the case, which way do you make it? And you've spoken about the same sort of dilemma about

02:17:41.840 --> 02:17:46.680
[Amit Varma]: making the case for inclusion, where you end up making it in, you know, three excellent

02:17:46.680 --> 02:17:51.800
[Amit Varma]: chapters in consequentialist terms by pointing out that companies in their self interest

02:17:51.800 --> 02:17:57.160
[Amit Varma]: should be inclusive, because, you know, ABC, which we'll discuss. And of course, you also

02:17:57.160 --> 02:18:01.080
[Amit Varma]: point out the moral case for it, you and you discuss a dialogue with a friend of yours

02:18:01.080 --> 02:18:04.640
[Amit Varma]: who was saying no, it should only be the moral case, the rest of it may change with fashion

02:18:04.640 --> 02:18:09.440
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And I actually agree with you on this and not so much with your friend,

02:18:09.440 --> 02:18:14.520
[Amit Varma]: because I think that even though individuals, you know, you can appeal to their sense of

02:18:14.520 --> 02:18:21.200
[Amit Varma]: morality, companies are finally a moral beast. So appealing to that kind of self interest

02:18:21.200 --> 02:18:25.720
[Amit Varma]: of this will make us more money, this will get us better employees is a good case to

02:18:25.720 --> 02:18:29.800
[Amit Varma]: make, especially since as you've shared in the book, and, you know, I've also spoken

02:18:29.800 --> 02:18:34.160
[Amit Varma]: about elsewhere, there is so much data to back up the benefits of diversity. But tell

02:18:34.160 --> 02:18:39.720
[Amit Varma]: me a bit about each of those three cases that you make for why corporations should be inclusive

02:18:39.720 --> 02:18:45.480
[Amit Varma]: and should, you know, go out of their way to be LGBTQ friendly. Yeah, so I, and you

02:18:45.480 --> 02:18:50.920
[Guest]: know, I told you earlier, I'm a maximalist. So why do one when you can buy one argument

02:18:50.920 --> 02:18:55.040
[Guest]: when you can have four. And I'm glad you're coming to this side of the spectrum, Amit,

02:18:55.040 --> 02:18:59.600
[Guest]: with like, you know, minimalistic arguments are pointless. So welcome. I'm happy that

02:18:59.600 --> 02:19:09.600
[Guest]: over the course of this podcast, I have taken you a little bit into excess. So I think,

02:19:09.600 --> 02:19:14.200
[Guest]: and that initial thing is very important, right? Because this is also a, I mean, this

02:19:14.200 --> 02:19:19.760
[Guest]: is a moral, it's a moral dilemma for inclusion advocates all over the world, right? I'm saying

02:19:19.760 --> 02:19:26.400
[Guest]: that this is, it's deeply personal. Queer people are four to 6% of the population. But

02:19:26.400 --> 02:19:30.320
[Guest]: even morally, even if there's just one queer person in the world, it should be inclusive.

02:19:30.320 --> 02:19:35.200
[Guest]: And if you base it on business, and so on, then you are in a sense, are you diminishing

02:19:35.200 --> 02:19:40.040
[Guest]: the moral case for it, and so on. But over the years, I mean, people are recognizing

02:19:40.040 --> 02:19:44.040
[Guest]: that, you know, I've anyway never believed in either or kind of things. I've always been

02:19:44.040 --> 02:19:50.280
[Guest]: a big advocate of both. So I think, I mean, this fits in very much with that. And I this

02:19:50.280 --> 02:19:56.800
[Guest]: is what I was seeing on the ground. So I put in, I made the case for it on all these terms,

02:19:56.800 --> 02:20:00.400
[Guest]: because I was seeing all these terms play themselves out on the ground, right? There

02:20:00.400 --> 02:20:06.800
[Guest]: is a clear moral case for inclusion, you know, which I've laid out from a human rights or

02:20:06.800 --> 02:20:12.440
[Guest]: just from whatever a decency perspective. I mean, it's a no brainer. Should we be decent

02:20:12.440 --> 02:20:20.120
[Guest]: to everyone? And treat everyone the same? Of course. And how novel and radical that

02:20:20.120 --> 02:20:24.880
[Guest]: I have to have a whole chapter in the book telling people why decency is a good thing.

02:20:24.880 --> 02:20:29.560
[Guest]: But there you have it. We do. Having said that, the other things I thought were very

02:20:29.560 --> 02:20:33.760
[Guest]: important, because, you know, we don't have data out of India as such, but there is enough

02:20:33.760 --> 02:20:39.000
[Guest]: data coming from other parts of the world that tell you that make very direct links

02:20:39.000 --> 02:20:44.280
[Guest]: between profitability, you know, both the company's profitability and the level of the

02:20:44.280 --> 02:20:49.520
[Guest]: inclusion as well as, you know, things like GDP, the economy and so on. Just to give you

02:20:49.520 --> 02:20:56.400
[Guest]: some numbers, the market size of India's queer economy is about $200 billion with a B. This

02:20:56.400 --> 02:21:01.760
[Guest]: is assuming, you know, 4 to 10% of the population is queer. That's a lot of money. Who wants

02:21:01.760 --> 02:21:08.280
[Guest]: a piece of that queer market? I know I do. Working in a company, certainly so many others,

02:21:08.280 --> 02:21:12.680
[Guest]: so many of your podcast listeners who are corporate people will say, hey, we want a

02:21:12.680 --> 02:21:21.240
[Guest]: bit of this market. So one way of getting it is by being inclusive, you know, to your

02:21:21.240 --> 02:21:25.560
[Guest]: queer employees, present and future, to your customers, indicating your customers that

02:21:25.560 --> 02:21:30.800
[Guest]: this is what you stand for. And, you know, as we have shown with other companies, you

02:21:30.800 --> 02:21:34.520
[Guest]: know, you will support it. And there's enough case studies about this, whether it's Subaru

02:21:34.520 --> 02:21:38.360
[Guest]: in the West or like Lalit Hotels or whatever in India, and so on. Companies that stand

02:21:38.360 --> 02:21:45.400
[Guest]: up for what they believe in make more money. And likewise, I mean, the World Bank did this

02:21:45.400 --> 02:21:50.360
[Guest]: incredible report in 2014, which looked at the cost of homophobia. And Leigh Badgett,

02:21:50.360 --> 02:21:54.600
[Guest]: who authored this, has gone on record to say that the number that she initially thought

02:21:54.600 --> 02:22:00.760
[Guest]: of, which was $32 billion is the cost of homophobia in India for that year, which was 2012, is

02:22:00.760 --> 02:22:06.640
[Guest]: a conservative number, which means in that year, $32 billion was about 1% of the GDP

02:22:06.640 --> 02:22:12.000
[Guest]: that year. And so the World Bank and Leigh Badgett's case was that if India had been

02:22:12.000 --> 02:22:16.160
[Guest]: more inclusive that year, they would have got a bump of GDP bump of 1%. And that is

02:22:16.160 --> 02:22:22.560
[Guest]: huge, which finance minister does not want this GDP bump of 1%, right? I mean, I think

02:22:22.560 --> 02:22:28.240
[Guest]: it would be very prudent for people to understand these studies and the direct links as so many

02:22:28.240 --> 02:22:32.480
[Guest]: other countries have done, as so many other cities have done, and so on, right? Then the

02:22:32.480 --> 02:22:37.840
[Guest]: second case is a link between innovation and being inclusive. And this, I mean, it should

02:22:37.840 --> 02:22:44.120
[Guest]: be a no brainer. But you know, when there are people making decisions, when everyone

02:22:44.120 --> 02:22:48.860
[Guest]: around the table looks the same and sounds the same, it's very hard to be innovative,

02:22:48.860 --> 02:22:54.240
[Guest]: because you are thinking about life from your perspective, right? If there are 10 people

02:22:54.240 --> 02:22:59.680
[Guest]: around the table, working on the design of a sanitary napkin for the future, it's going

02:22:59.680 --> 02:23:06.040
[Guest]: to be and they all happen to be, you know, male, it would be very hard. The design would

02:23:06.040 --> 02:23:10.840
[Guest]: be much better if you widen that to include even one woman in that group, because you

02:23:10.840 --> 02:23:15.640
[Guest]: know, she'll say, well, you know, being a woman as someone who might have used this

02:23:15.640 --> 02:23:19.760
[Guest]: product, can I just tell you this, this, this, right? And then your product becomes better,

02:23:19.760 --> 02:23:24.240
[Guest]: whatever, right? Would it be better if you had two? Yes, of course, then a range of other

02:23:24.240 --> 02:23:29.160
[Guest]: and so on, right? So basic example, but just to say that, you know, the more diverse teams

02:23:29.160 --> 02:23:36.120
[Guest]: you have, and diversities across various pillars, gender is one, ability is one, if you have

02:23:36.120 --> 02:23:42.240
[Guest]: PWDs on your team, you can help imagine better things. If you have people who might be LGBT

02:23:42.240 --> 02:23:47.080
[Guest]: on your team, it might be better. Caste is an important pillar of diversity in our country

02:23:47.080 --> 02:23:52.880
[Guest]: as well. And so many other, you know, frameworks, religion, caste, age, so many of these other

02:23:52.880 --> 02:23:56.640
[Guest]: things, right, which are different pillars of diversity. And there is enough research

02:23:56.640 --> 02:24:02.800
[Guest]: that now shows that companies that have more diverse teams, innovate better, their products

02:24:02.800 --> 02:24:08.080
[Guest]: do better in the market, and have better outcomes, which eventually leads to more money. So even

02:24:08.080 --> 02:24:12.320
[Guest]: the innovation case is very, very clear, you know, the more innovative you are, the better

02:24:12.320 --> 02:24:16.640
[Amit Varma]: you will do, the more money you will make. In fact, I've spoken in past episodes about

02:24:16.640 --> 02:24:23.040
[Amit Varma]: studies which show that the most important factor in good decision making is not IQ or

02:24:23.040 --> 02:24:28.080
[Amit Varma]: education or any of those things. It's diversity, because you just have so many different viewpoints

02:24:28.080 --> 02:24:32.000
[Amit Varma]: coming in that there will be people thinking out of your box, not necessarily out of the

02:24:32.000 --> 02:24:36.320
[Amit Varma]: box, but out of your box. And it's important to have that for its own sake, which doesn't

02:24:36.320 --> 02:24:42.240
[Amit Varma]: mean that, you know, you value diversity over any of these other attributes necessarily.

02:24:42.240 --> 02:24:46.360
[Amit Varma]: But I would say the way I would interpret is that whenever you can choose between two

02:24:46.360 --> 02:24:51.840
[Amit Varma]: equal candidates, choose the one who will, you know, improve your diversity. And ultimately,

02:24:51.840 --> 02:24:55.640
[Amit Varma]: that affects the bottom line. And as you point out, so many studies have shown. And that's

02:24:55.640 --> 02:25:00.040
[Guest]: what positive discrimination essentially is, right? To say that, how can you widen your,

02:25:00.040 --> 02:25:06.280
[Guest]: you know, your pool of talent to reflect the world outside because people, I mean, you're

02:25:06.280 --> 02:25:10.600
[Guest]: employees, your customers, other stakeholders are living in this world outside in which

02:25:10.600 --> 02:25:15.920
[Guest]: they are witnessing diversity. So in any society, four to 10% of people are queer, there are

02:25:15.920 --> 02:25:22.200
[Guest]: disabled people, and there are people of color, you know, etc. Why is that diversity not being

02:25:22.200 --> 02:25:26.200
[Guest]: reflected in workplaces? I mean, that's the question, right? And if that diversity was

02:25:26.200 --> 02:25:30.720
[Guest]: reflected in workplaces, if you had workplaces which are more reflective of the world that

02:25:30.720 --> 02:25:38.320
[Guest]: we are living in, you know, it would be better. I mean, it's not rocket science. It's actually

02:25:38.320 --> 02:25:42.000
[Guest]: quite simple, right? And this is not true of just a corporate level, it's true of cities

02:25:42.000 --> 02:25:47.800
[Guest]: and countries. So Richard Florida, you know, has done work now for about 15-20 years on

02:25:47.800 --> 02:25:51.920
[Guest]: cities. And he wrote this incredible book called The Rise of the Creative Class some

02:25:51.920 --> 02:25:56.840
[Guest]: years ago, which made a direct correlation between, you know, cities and their productivity

02:25:56.840 --> 02:26:02.680
[Guest]: and the output. And he had certain parameters, which he looked at, that linked the city's

02:26:02.680 --> 02:26:09.360
[Guest]: competitive index, and one of which was that is the city more inclusive to LGBTQ people.

02:26:09.360 --> 02:26:14.000
[Guest]: And since then, the work has expanded to look at countries to look at regions and so on.

02:26:14.000 --> 02:26:20.440
[Guest]: And in every case, it's very, very clear, at the city level, at the region level, at

02:26:20.440 --> 02:26:26.960
[Guest]: a state level, at a country level, if you are more inclusive, you do better. And you

02:26:26.960 --> 02:26:33.200
[Guest]: in every way, including financially, right? So even say in the US, right? Other parts

02:26:33.200 --> 02:26:37.880
[Guest]: of the US might be having recessions. But you know, certain regions, right, whether

02:26:37.880 --> 02:26:42.960
[Guest]: it's San Francisco, Palo Alto, New York, etc, are thriving, because they have been so inclusive

02:26:42.960 --> 02:26:47.800
[Guest]: in so many ways, that talent gravitates over there, talent gravitates, innovative ideas

02:26:47.800 --> 02:26:51.240
[Guest]: come from there, innovative ideas come from there, it benefits the economy, and things

02:26:51.240 --> 02:26:57.360
[Guest]: like that, right. So there are so many countries like Chile, who started Startup Chile programs,

02:26:57.360 --> 02:27:01.680
[Guest]: welcoming innovative people into their country. And you know, countries like Israel, Chile,

02:27:01.680 --> 02:27:07.360
[Guest]: and all have made innovation, like one of the key things that they want to import talent,

02:27:07.360 --> 02:27:10.200
[Guest]: because they recognize that the future of the countries is going to be based on the

02:27:10.200 --> 02:27:14.920
[Guest]: talent that they can attract. And if you want to attract global talent, you have to be that

02:27:14.920 --> 02:27:20.400
[Guest]: kind of society that global talent will want to navigate, gravitate towards, right. So

02:27:20.400 --> 02:27:26.120
[Guest]: I mean, that's, you know, on innovation on multiple levels. And I also write in the chapter

02:27:26.120 --> 02:27:31.000
[Guest]: about how we want to preserve our talent. And one of the, say, in the IIT petition,

02:27:31.000 --> 02:27:37.000
[Guest]: for example, in the 2018, you know, hearing, so many of the IIT students had said that,

02:27:37.000 --> 02:27:41.160
[Guest]: you know, they were considering so many of their, you know, former IIT graduates had

02:27:41.160 --> 02:27:46.440
[Guest]: already migrated to countries like Canada, etc. Not for anything else, but other that

02:27:46.440 --> 02:27:51.440
[Guest]: they did not feel comfortable living in India at that time. So my question is, why should

02:27:51.440 --> 02:27:56.160
[Guest]: our best talent be migrating away to other queer friendly countries? Why don't we create

02:27:56.160 --> 02:28:01.360
[Guest]: a queer friendly environment so that, because we have spent our taxpayer money, you know,

02:28:01.360 --> 02:28:06.920
[Guest]: into educating all these IIT students, it's our money that's gone into educating them.

02:28:06.920 --> 02:28:10.800
[Guest]: And they want to leave and go to other parts of the world, because those parts are more

02:28:10.800 --> 02:28:15.200
[Guest]: queer friendly. Why don't we just create a more queer friendly environment so our talent

02:28:15.200 --> 02:28:23.480
[Guest]: can remain here, and then add to the innovation, potential and output of our economy. So this

02:28:23.480 --> 02:28:27.440
[Guest]: bit is a little nationalistic, but I mean, you know, it makes sense, right? I mean, we

02:28:27.440 --> 02:28:34.000
[Guest]: want, so from every perspective that you look at, I mean, you know, the link between innovation

02:28:34.000 --> 02:28:40.360
[Guest]: and inclusion is very clear. And then finally, I go on into, you know, into talent, into

02:28:40.360 --> 02:28:45.560
[Guest]: reputation, talking about Millennials and Gen Zs, and how in today's world, you know,

02:28:45.560 --> 02:28:51.000
[Guest]: it is a reputation economy, and how young people really, really want to either buy products

02:28:51.000 --> 02:28:56.280
[Guest]: from or work at companies that are standing up and doing the right thing. And for them,

02:28:56.280 --> 02:29:02.320
[Guest]: caring for the environment, caring for, you know, thinking about diversity and inclusion.

02:29:02.320 --> 02:29:06.240
[Guest]: And you know, there are a bunch of things which are the right thing. So you know, I

02:29:06.240 --> 02:29:08.840
[Guest]: mean, those, these are the pillars on which I make my argument.

02:29:08.840 --> 02:29:13.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, the three basic pillars. One is it will directly lead you to profit. Two is that it

02:29:13.520 --> 02:29:17.520
[Amit Varma]: will attract innovative people. And as you point out in that chapter on, you know, attracting

02:29:17.520 --> 02:29:21.960
[Amit Varma]: innovative people, it creates a virtuous cycle. Because once you have innovation and inclusion

02:29:21.960 --> 02:29:26.400
[Amit Varma]: within a company, you know, more and more people will want to work in that place, not

02:29:26.400 --> 02:29:31.800
[Amit Varma]: just LGBTQ people, but people who just like that openness and the sort of the innovation

02:29:31.800 --> 02:29:36.800
[Amit Varma]: that happens from there. I mean, again, personal flashback came here. I remember when I sort

02:29:36.800 --> 02:29:41.320
[Amit Varma]: of graduated from college in 94. I worked for a year in advertising in Delhi. And then

02:29:41.320 --> 02:29:45.480
[Amit Varma]: I moved to Bombay to work at channel B, I just gave up my job. And I just landed there.

02:29:45.480 --> 02:29:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And why? Because I saw so much creativity coming out of there at the time, like if you

02:29:49.920 --> 02:29:54.320
[Amit Varma]: remember quick gun, gun, and so on. And of course, I didn't create anything remotely

02:29:54.320 --> 02:29:59.600
[Amit Varma]: that creative, which is entirely to do with me and not to do with channel B. But and later

02:29:59.600 --> 02:30:03.960
[Amit Varma]: on, I remember when I was working at Crick Info in the early 2000s, and there was so

02:30:03.960 --> 02:30:09.560
[Amit Varma]: much great cricket writing that automatically, you know, once you established yourself as

02:30:09.560 --> 02:30:14.220
[Amit Varma]: a place where there is good writing happening, anybody who wanted to write like that would

02:30:14.220 --> 02:30:18.920
[Amit Varma]: gravitate towards you. And, you know, we became a magnet for young writing talent, many of

02:30:18.920 --> 02:30:22.360
[Amit Varma]: whom have gone on to do great writing, apart from cricket. So that's a great point. And

02:30:22.360 --> 02:30:27.600
[Amit Varma]: your third point was about just the reputational benefits that, you know, if you have that

02:30:27.600 --> 02:30:32.040
[Amit Varma]: warm, fuzzy feeling about a company, or even at an intellectual level, a sense of admiration

02:30:32.040 --> 02:30:36.720
[Amit Varma]: for what they're doing, you are more likely to buy their products, like, again, contextualizing

02:30:36.720 --> 02:30:41.880
[Amit Varma]: this to myself, I remember a few years ago, I went to Costa once, and I said something

02:30:41.880 --> 02:30:46.640
[Amit Varma]: to the waiter, and he couldn't hear me. And then I realized that they're hiring, you know,

02:30:46.640 --> 02:30:51.500
[Amit Varma]: deaf and dumb stuff. And, you know, as a company policy, and immediately, then that increases

02:30:51.500 --> 02:30:56.960
[Amit Varma]: your loyalty to that particular place, because you're like that, you know, wow, this is,

02:30:56.960 --> 02:31:02.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, and so those knock on benefits also, you know, are there. Now, let's let's kind

02:31:02.040 --> 02:31:07.960
[Amit Varma]: of move on to you know, the fourth section of your book is a fascinating five step guide

02:31:07.960 --> 02:31:14.280
[Amit Varma]: for what companies can do for, you know, having now that you've sold them the case, that inclusion

02:31:14.280 --> 02:31:18.680
[Amit Varma]: is good for you, how do they become inclusive, and you've got this guide for that. So can

02:31:18.680 --> 02:31:22.320
[Amit Varma]: you take us through, you know, some of the points that you've kind of raised in that?

02:31:22.320 --> 02:31:26.640
[Guest]: Well, I do want them to buy the book also. So I don't want to take them through so many

02:31:26.640 --> 02:31:32.640
[Guest]: points that they don't buy the book. But I will briefly, we are running out of time anyway.

02:31:32.640 --> 02:31:38.240
[Guest]: So we'll cover this briefly. I mean, this is think of this as the tasting menu, not

02:31:38.240 --> 02:31:45.600
[Guest]: the main course. And, you know, the main course is very good. So you have to come. I think

02:31:45.600 --> 02:31:49.760
[Amit Varma]: I think, you know, even the subjects that we have discussed, you know, we have just

02:31:49.760 --> 02:31:54.880
[Amit Varma]: touched the surface of it. And people really have to buy the book to get a full sense of

02:31:54.880 --> 02:31:59.200
[Guest]: the depth of the arguments and the data presented. So I think that goes without saying, I don't

02:31:59.200 --> 02:32:02.160
[Guest]: worry about that, my listeners buy books.

02:32:02.160 --> 02:32:06.160
[Guest]: Very good. I'm so glad. So since you all buy books, you can feel free to buy it in all

02:32:06.160 --> 02:32:09.920
[Guest]: formats. It's a paper book, there's a Kindle, there's also Audible, you can buy it in all

02:32:09.920 --> 02:32:12.560
[Amit Varma]: formats. Now having sold that.

02:32:12.560 --> 02:32:17.040
[Amit Varma]: Not just that, buy multiple copies and gift it to people who you think they need to be

02:32:17.040 --> 02:32:18.040
[Amit Varma]: gifted to.

02:32:18.040 --> 02:32:23.640
[Guest]: Yeah, it's bright, it's colorful. It's a perfect gift for anything, whichever festival is coming

02:32:23.640 --> 02:32:24.640
[Amit Varma]: up, you know, gifted.

02:32:24.640 --> 02:32:29.720
[Amit Varma]: Though the picture of you in it is like, almost besides a bow tie, it's a very boring corporatish

02:32:29.720 --> 02:32:30.720
[Guest]: picture.

02:32:30.720 --> 02:32:35.720
[Guest]: You have to do this in the line, right?

02:32:35.720 --> 02:32:36.720
[Guest]: Serious.

02:32:36.720 --> 02:32:43.640
[Guest]: Yeah, but next edition, we'll do something more flamboyant. So just to give you an overview

02:32:43.640 --> 02:32:49.080
[Guest]: of in terms of the different sections, I mean, in terms of, it starts with basic policies

02:32:49.080 --> 02:32:56.240
[Guest]: that one can change right from having an anti-discrimination policy. And I make it very easy. I give you

02:32:56.240 --> 02:32:59.800
[Guest]: the Godrej, a large part of the book, I'm just giving you, I'm saying, here's what we

02:32:59.800 --> 02:33:04.400
[Guest]: have at Godrej, copy and paste it, okay? Because a lot of people who are reading it might say,

02:33:04.400 --> 02:33:07.840
[Guest]: oh, now we don't know how to make one, how to make one, it's there, you know, use it,

02:33:07.840 --> 02:33:12.040
[Guest]: we don't mind, there's no copyright. Use it.

02:33:12.040 --> 02:33:17.080
[Guest]: So what is an anti-discrimination policy? I tell you, I say you can use this. What does

02:33:17.080 --> 02:33:24.000
[Guest]: it mean to have, you know, a more comprehensive posh policy? We put that in. So a lot of policies

02:33:24.000 --> 02:33:28.920
[Guest]: and benefits. What are benefits? Same sex partnership benefits. Here is what they are.

02:33:28.920 --> 02:33:33.760
[Guest]: And this is what we offer. Gender affirmation, surgery and benefits. This is what it means.

02:33:33.760 --> 02:33:38.240
[Guest]: This is, you know, so all the early, the first step is just, you know, having all of this

02:33:38.240 --> 02:33:42.760
[Guest]: in place. And then I also say, don't have it and do it quietly, right? You're doing

02:33:42.760 --> 02:33:47.880
[Guest]: this, you must make some noise about it so that people know. Now, having the policies

02:33:47.880 --> 02:33:51.680
[Guest]: and benefits in place doesn't mean that tomorrow, like hundreds of people will come out and

02:33:51.680 --> 02:33:55.840
[Guest]: start using it, right? Because people are not closeted because you don't, people are

02:33:55.840 --> 02:34:00.840
[Guest]: closeted because of various things. So you might have the best policies and benefits,

02:34:00.840 --> 02:34:04.640
[Guest]: but you might not have a culture of inclusion. So people might want to avail of it, but they

02:34:04.640 --> 02:34:09.880
[Guest]: might be afraid, okay, if I come out, will my boss treat me differently or will my coworkers

02:34:09.880 --> 02:34:13.840
[Guest]: and will my dad, right? So you have to supplement your policy and benefits with a whole bunch

02:34:13.840 --> 02:34:18.240
[Guest]: of other things. And so all those other steps are about these other things. Like, what does

02:34:18.240 --> 02:34:23.760
[Guest]: it mean to sensitize people within, right? How are the different ways you can sensitize?

02:34:23.760 --> 02:34:27.720
[Guest]: And I show people, whether through workshops, whether through roundtables, whether through

02:34:27.720 --> 02:34:33.040
[Guest]: carnivals, what does sensitization mean? How do you go out and actively recruit LGBTQ people?

02:34:33.040 --> 02:34:37.920
[Guest]: Because now there's an ecosystem. Say you're, you want to be LGBTQ friendly and you know,

02:34:37.920 --> 02:34:41.880
[Guest]: you want to say, okay, I'm sure I have queer employees. I'm going to do all of this, but

02:34:41.880 --> 02:34:45.960
[Guest]: I'd like to attract more queer talent. Now there's a whole, there are consulting companies

02:34:45.960 --> 02:34:51.800
[Guest]: that are job fairs. There is a whole, there's so much that you can do, including basic things,

02:34:51.800 --> 02:34:56.680
[Guest]: like even just signaling. This is what Ali Portia from McKinsey told me. You can put

02:34:56.680 --> 02:35:01.920
[Guest]: even all your posts on naukri.com. You know, even if you just put one rainbow around it,

02:35:01.920 --> 02:35:05.560
[Guest]: the queer people who are reading it will understand, Oh, they're queer friendly. Maybe I can apply

02:35:05.560 --> 02:35:09.120
[Guest]: or whatever. You don't have to say they're queer friendly. Basic signaling also goes

02:35:09.120 --> 02:35:14.560
[Guest]: a long way, right? And that's the thing. So it tells you about how you can, you know,

02:35:14.560 --> 02:35:18.880
[Guest]: participate and create this. There's a specific chapter on, on all the things that you have

02:35:18.880 --> 02:35:23.880
[Guest]: to be careful and mindful about when you are reaching out to trans employees, because trans

02:35:23.880 --> 02:35:30.520
[Guest]: employees have a unique set of needs. And so as a company, you have to be more sensitive.

02:35:30.520 --> 02:35:35.680
[Guest]: Basic stuff, right? A trans person might have a 10 standard school leaving certificate with

02:35:35.680 --> 02:35:41.240
[Guest]: one gender and might have transitioned to something else. So you have to tell your HR

02:35:41.240 --> 02:35:46.120
[Guest]: department, please don't create difficulties and say, but your school leaving certificate

02:35:46.120 --> 02:35:49.840
[Guest]: says Mr. And now you are Miss and all that. You have to understand and you have to accept

02:35:49.840 --> 02:35:54.360
[Guest]: and you have to say, fine, we accept this certificate and we accept this also. Like

02:35:54.360 --> 02:35:57.640
[Guest]: that there are so many other things, right? We spoke about Kochi Metro earlier and saying

02:35:57.640 --> 02:36:02.280
[Guest]: how you might have to help with housing, opening bank accounts, so many other things, right?

02:36:02.280 --> 02:36:06.960
[Guest]: The other thing is with trans people, often because of systematic discrimination, levels

02:36:06.960 --> 02:36:11.200
[Guest]: of education might not be so high. So when you are, if you're serious about hiring trans

02:36:11.200 --> 02:36:15.960
[Guest]: people, you might want to do a combination of skill building and training and hiring,

02:36:15.960 --> 02:36:19.600
[Guest]: which is what, you know, ANZ and so many of these other, you know, banks have done to

02:36:19.600 --> 02:36:25.480
[Guest]: great success, you know, working with community organizations, doing a skill building workshop

02:36:25.480 --> 02:36:30.120
[Guest]: for six weeks. And, you know, then the 25 trans people who've attended the skill building

02:36:30.120 --> 02:36:35.120
[Guest]: workshops, the ones that do well, get absorbed into the company and the ones that the company

02:36:35.120 --> 02:36:39.760
[Guest]: does not want gives, they are given certificates and, you know, then they have a better chance

02:36:39.760 --> 02:36:43.840
[Guest]: of working with other companies and so on. So, I mean, it's a useful chapter in that

02:36:43.840 --> 02:36:49.200
[Guest]: sense. So I end by talking about how, if you really want to go the whole hog, then you

02:36:49.200 --> 02:36:54.480
[Guest]: have to really talk about it to the world because, you know, I, I personally don't think

02:36:54.480 --> 02:36:58.520
[Guest]: being in, I mean, you know, I think it's everyone's choice, but I think you shouldn't be a closeted

02:36:58.520 --> 02:37:04.240
[Guest]: company also, because in the words of the famous Rakhi Sawant, jo dikhta hai, wo bikhta

02:37:04.240 --> 02:37:10.680
[Guest]: hai. So if you are being inclusive, why not tell the world about it and show it to the

02:37:10.680 --> 02:37:16.200
[Guest]: world and get the love and appreciation that the world will give you for it. So don't be

02:37:16.200 --> 02:37:21.800
[Guest]: closeted, talk about it at public forums, visibly support queer culture by sponsoring

02:37:21.800 --> 02:37:28.360
[Guest]: film festivals, you know, literature festivals, pride marches, whatever it takes. Support

02:37:28.360 --> 02:37:33.160
[Guest]: your employees when they want to go on things like that. Help community organizations through

02:37:33.160 --> 02:37:39.600
[Guest]: your CSR in whatever way you can. Just be an out and proud ally, because, you know,

02:37:39.600 --> 02:37:45.240
[Guest]: the love and affection and market share and everything else that you will get in it is

02:37:45.240 --> 02:37:51.120
[Guest]: far greater than you will put in it. That I can guarantee you. So, you know, it's a

02:37:51.120 --> 02:37:56.080
[Guest]: multiple step approach. I hope everyone who reads it follows all the steps.

02:37:56.080 --> 02:38:00.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, you are the first person on my show to quote Rakhi Sawant as a management guru.

02:38:00.680 --> 02:38:05.520
[Amit Varma]: That was fascinating. I have two final questions for you. My penultimate question is this,

02:38:05.520 --> 02:38:13.440
[Amit Varma]: that what we often see in social movements is that sometimes a cause can be hurt by radical

02:38:13.440 --> 02:38:18.080
[Amit Varma]: fringes and there is a danger of going too far. For example, you know, you've spoken

02:38:18.080 --> 02:38:23.800
[Amit Varma]: very wisely of the many cells within us, that our identity is not just focused around, you

02:38:23.800 --> 02:38:28.720
[Amit Varma]: know, one aspect, but various aspects and they all come together. But it strikes me

02:38:28.720 --> 02:38:36.440
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, this deep focus on, you know, particular strands of our identity can sometimes

02:38:36.440 --> 02:38:41.600
[Amit Varma]: get reductive, you know, if you if you focus too hard on it, and you build these narratives

02:38:41.600 --> 02:38:46.360
[Amit Varma]: of oppression and victimhood and so on. And I think they don't have enough respect for

02:38:46.360 --> 02:38:53.240
[Amit Varma]: individual complexity and individual autonomy. And those can get eroded, where you just,

02:38:53.240 --> 02:38:57.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, once you embrace that narrative of yourself as a victim, you might be condemning

02:38:57.520 --> 02:39:01.520
[Amit Varma]: yourself to a perpetual feeling of victimhood, which can't be good. And, you know, which

02:39:01.520 --> 02:39:06.920
[Amit Varma]: is something that one could otherwise get across. Now, you know, without sort of getting

02:39:06.920 --> 02:39:11.240
[Amit Varma]: into specifics, is this something that you think about? I mean, even within this movement,

02:39:11.240 --> 02:39:15.520
[Amit Varma]: of course, it's one thing that there are many differences, but those differences get, you

02:39:15.520 --> 02:39:20.480
[Amit Varma]: know, more and more heated over time, you know, just a few months ago, JK Rowling would

02:39:20.480 --> 02:39:25.320
[Amit Varma]: have been considered such an ally of the movement. And then there was this, you know, vociferous

02:39:25.320 --> 02:39:30.640
[Amit Varma]: backlash against her and she was called transphobic and all of that, without getting into the

02:39:30.640 --> 02:39:36.640
[Amit Varma]: merits of the case per se, is that perhaps an issue of too much zealotry here and also

02:39:36.640 --> 02:39:42.880
[Amit Varma]: of the reductiveness, which is kind of dangerous, where you only see yourself as x, without

02:39:42.880 --> 02:39:47.960
[Amit Varma]: accepting that we all contain the whole alphabet within us to varying degrees.

02:39:47.960 --> 02:39:57.160
[Guest]: So very briefly, yes, I think, off late, and you know, certainly social media, etc, have

02:39:57.160 --> 02:40:02.560
[Guest]: amplified a lot of, it has been very easy for a lot of people to take positions and

02:40:02.560 --> 02:40:05.600
[Guest]: it's not just social media, if you look at the nature of our television, if you look

02:40:05.600 --> 02:40:11.160
[Guest]: at the overall toxicity, not just in India, all over the world, I would say, in terms

02:40:11.160 --> 02:40:16.560
[Guest]: of, you know, position taking and attacking the other and so on. So I think it's very

02:40:16.560 --> 02:40:22.720
[Guest]: easy to lose out on nuance, it's very easy to, it's much easier for people to look at

02:40:22.720 --> 02:40:28.920
[Guest]: what the differences between each other than what unites us commonly. And certainly within

02:40:28.920 --> 02:40:33.480
[Guest]: the queer movement, we have seen in India and other parts of the world, it's easier

02:40:33.480 --> 02:40:40.280
[Guest]: to like have differences than to say that, you know, we are under one common umbrella.

02:40:40.280 --> 02:40:44.160
[Guest]: I'm not, one can recognize that one is under one common umbrella and still recognize the

02:40:44.160 --> 02:40:48.360
[Guest]: issues with it with that umbrella, right? I've always said, I think the queer movement

02:40:48.360 --> 02:40:53.760
[Guest]: really, we also need to deeply reflect. And this book is also a call to the queer movement

02:40:53.760 --> 02:40:58.520
[Guest]: to ask ourselves, what histories are we telling? Whose histories are we telling? But having

02:40:58.520 --> 02:41:03.680
[Guest]: said that, I'm given that at least, you know, this book, and this book is very much set

02:41:03.680 --> 02:41:08.760
[Guest]: in business. And it's very much a call to action. And it's an action oriented book.

02:41:08.760 --> 02:41:17.720
[Guest]: I like what Devdutt calls samvad, not vivad. So I like conversations, not confrontations.

02:41:17.720 --> 02:41:22.560
[Guest]: I'm very okay with disagreements. You know, I think the world would be very boring without

02:41:22.560 --> 02:41:26.800
[Guest]: disagreements. But I like disagreements that are respectful. And you know, we don't always

02:41:26.800 --> 02:41:29.720
[Guest]: have to agree on, you know, each other's perspectives.

02:41:29.720 --> 02:41:32.800
[Amit Varma]: So you won't stop talking to me just because I don't like Shahrukh?

02:41:32.800 --> 02:41:39.640
[Guest]: No, I mean, will I try overtly and covertly to influence you to become a Shahrukh fan?

02:41:39.640 --> 02:41:48.000
[Guest]: Of course. But that is samvad, no? I mean, I won't say you like Shahrukh. I was like,

02:41:48.000 --> 02:41:54.880
[Guest]: no, okay, there's hope here. Let me show you. Have you seen Paheli? It's an underrated gem.

02:41:54.880 --> 02:41:58.240
[Guest]: Maybe you like Shahrukh after that, right? And even if you don't, if you don't, then

02:41:58.240 --> 02:42:02.040
[Guest]: I would say, okay, you're missing out a lot. What can I say? Maybe we can find something

02:42:02.040 --> 02:42:07.040
[Guest]: else to bond over. But my aim, that's my thing, right? I mean, so even with this book, right,

02:42:07.040 --> 02:42:13.440
[Guest]: the aim is very much to get people to hire more queer people like me. I mean, if the

02:42:13.440 --> 02:42:20.040
[Guest]: book has been written as a manifesto to get people to understand that queer people matter,

02:42:20.040 --> 02:42:25.000
[Guest]: we need jobs, we need recognitions, we need equality. And with that stated aim in mind,

02:42:25.000 --> 02:42:29.960
[Guest]: I think samvad is a better answer, within the movement and outside. Because when you

02:42:29.960 --> 02:42:35.240
[Guest]: do samvad, you always leave the door open for possibilities. I think more and more when

02:42:35.240 --> 02:42:40.600
[Guest]: we do vivaad, we shut those doors. And I think where the world is going, the more doors we

02:42:40.600 --> 02:42:42.920
[Amit Varma]: open, the more bridges we build, it's better.

02:42:42.920 --> 02:42:47.400
[Amit Varma]: Very wise words. And I would just add to that by saying that I found your book such a wonderful

02:42:47.400 --> 02:42:52.400
[Amit Varma]: read that I think either of those terms memoir and manifesto or even both of them together

02:42:52.400 --> 02:42:57.040
[Amit Varma]: don't do justice to it. So I, you know, recommend everybody pick it up and read it even if you

02:42:57.040 --> 02:43:01.760
[Amit Varma]: feel that, hey, this subject doesn't link, you know, interest me, I'm not LGBTQ, why

02:43:01.760 --> 02:43:06.520
[Amit Varma]: should I read this, even then it will open your eyes to the world around us. And a lot

02:43:06.520 --> 02:43:11.400
[Amit Varma]: of it is just universal, like, so many passages within it spoke so intimately to me, like

02:43:11.400 --> 02:43:15.760
[Amit Varma]: what you wrote about many selves and so on. For a final question, I'll turn away from

02:43:15.760 --> 02:43:17.000
[Amit Varma]: the book and back to you.

02:43:17.000 --> 02:43:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Rapid fire, rapid fire. Is that a hamper?

02:43:21.360 --> 02:43:27.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm sorry. This is a virtual, this thing. I could give you a virtual hamper. You know,

02:43:27.680 --> 02:43:28.680
[Guest]: what is it?

02:43:28.680 --> 02:43:39.880
[Amit Varma]: Sir, I am humble person. I am not Kejo. I am Eva. Eva sounds good, actually. Yeah. Okay.

02:43:39.880 --> 02:43:44.580
[Amit Varma]: So I watched this interview of yours from 10 years ago on this excellent series called

02:43:44.580 --> 02:43:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Project Bolo. All these links will be in the show notes, by the way. So please check them

02:43:48.920 --> 02:43:53.920
[Amit Varma]: out. So the excellent series called Project Bolo, which had conversations with various

02:43:53.920 --> 02:43:59.520
[Amit Varma]: people from within the movement about their lived experiences and so on. And in that interview

02:43:59.520 --> 02:44:04.120
[Amit Varma]: of yours, you know, this quote struck me and this was 10 years ago. So I asked you about

02:44:04.120 --> 02:44:10.400
[Amit Varma]: it today. And you said, I want to live in interesting times, stop quote. And now that,

02:44:10.400 --> 02:44:15.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, the preceding 10 years have certainly included many interesting times. And I'm going

02:44:15.680 --> 02:44:20.040
[Amit Varma]: to end this show with my staple question to all my guests that looking ahead, maybe just

02:44:20.040 --> 02:44:28.120
[Amit Varma]: looking ahead 10 years and not too much. What gives you hope and what gives you despair?

02:44:28.120 --> 02:44:35.440
[Guest]: What gives me hope are all the young people that I have met on this journey. The world,

02:44:35.440 --> 02:44:40.280
[Guest]: the future of the world, not just the queer movement in India belongs to the young. And

02:44:40.280 --> 02:44:46.000
[Guest]: whether it is young queer people, you know, I write in this book about this incredible

02:44:46.000 --> 02:44:53.840
[Guest]: young poet in Jabalpur who is out to his family and whose father buys him mascara very normally,

02:44:53.840 --> 02:44:59.040
[Guest]: you know, to this wonderful lesbian couple I met in Lucknow. We're living a very happy

02:44:59.040 --> 02:45:05.480
[Guest]: life together to the young founders of these brilliant, you know, intersectional queer

02:45:05.480 --> 02:45:13.280
[Guest]: spaces across the country, whether it's Yaal in Manipur, Zookia in Assam, Queerabad in

02:45:13.280 --> 02:45:17.240
[Guest]: Ahmedabad, you know, Queer Alankar, there's so many, right? There's Awad Queer Festival,

02:45:17.240 --> 02:45:24.520
[Guest]: like there's so many festivals, organizations, places, things, Chinky Homo Project out of

02:45:24.520 --> 02:45:30.640
[Guest]: Delhi that addresses Northeast. I spoke about Grace Bhanu already and A Bond of Interest,

02:45:30.640 --> 02:45:36.000
[Guest]: you know, Pink List, which is at the intersection of political activism and queerness. You know,

02:45:36.000 --> 02:45:40.600
[Guest]: I just, you know, there's a whole list. And I end the book with about 200 of these organizations

02:45:40.600 --> 02:45:46.440
[Guest]: and Dalit Queer Project, Queer Muslim Project, all of which are looking at various aspects

02:45:46.440 --> 02:45:53.640
[Guest]: of queerness. So what gives me hope are these incredible young rainbow warriors striving

02:45:53.640 --> 02:45:59.040
[Guest]: to really not just imagine people like Jyoti Chand, right, who have come out, who are out

02:45:59.040 --> 02:46:04.720
[Guest]: and proud and running for the country. People like Narthaki Nataraj was honored by the present

02:46:04.720 --> 02:46:09.320
[Guest]: government with the Padma Bhushan, you know, for as the first transgender, I think that

02:46:09.320 --> 02:46:14.760
[Guest]: the first transgender dancer to win this award. So many state governments, I would say, across

02:46:14.760 --> 02:46:21.320
[Guest]: the country who are recognizing that inclusion is an imperative and are slowly building the

02:46:21.320 --> 02:46:26.520
[Guest]: networks for it, whether through welfare boards like, you know, Maharashtra, Kerala, Tamil

02:46:26.520 --> 02:46:34.280
[Guest]: Nadu, and so on, or other initiatives. So, I mean, what gives me hope are these young,

02:46:34.280 --> 02:46:39.320
[Guest]: incredible changemakers who are in a sense, pushing everyone around them to imagine, to

02:46:39.320 --> 02:46:43.600
[Guest]: create and to live in this, you know, tomorrow, which I've called with great love and affection

02:46:43.600 --> 02:46:53.040
[Guest]: Queeristan. What scares me is that our present generation might disappoint them. You know,

02:46:53.040 --> 02:46:58.000
[Guest]: the passion and the power of their dreams, and the interconnected equal world that this

02:46:58.000 --> 02:47:04.880
[Guest]: tomorrow's generation is imagining is so strong and so beautiful. And I really wish and hope

02:47:04.880 --> 02:47:10.880
[Guest]: that some of us who are running the world today, either join these tomorrow's queer,

02:47:10.880 --> 02:47:18.280
[Guest]: you know, action superstars, or step out of the way, but not get into their way. So that

02:47:18.280 --> 02:47:24.360
[Guest]: is what gives me, you know, that is my fear. Your words of hope are very inspiring. But

02:47:24.360 --> 02:47:28.760
[Amit Varma]: I have to say that, you know, your words of despair are a bit overstated, because I don't

02:47:28.760 --> 02:47:33.040
[Amit Varma]: think you'll disappoint anybody with this wonderful, remarkable book, which I think

02:47:33.040 --> 02:47:37.960
[Amit Varma]: will be read for hopefully decades from now. Parmesh, thank you so much for coming on my

02:47:37.960 --> 02:47:41.840
[Guest]: show. It was so good to catch up with you again after so long. Thank you. And it was

02:47:41.840 --> 02:47:48.040
[Guest]: exactly three hours. So it's perfect. It's the length of a wonderful, old style Bollywood

02:47:48.040 --> 02:47:53.480
[Amit Varma]: film with Shahrukh Khan. See, I know now that if you compare me with Shahrukh Khan, Shahrukh

02:47:53.480 --> 02:47:59.520
[Amit Varma]: is winning. So this is, but, you know, thanks a lot. I'm going to go and, you know, search

02:47:59.520 --> 02:48:03.360
[Amit Varma]: for Paheli now and watch it just out of respect for you, Parmesh.

02:48:03.360 --> 02:48:10.080
[Guest]: Thank you. And to everyone who's listening, thank you so much. Lots and lots of love.

